children.name: interfaces
children.description: Interface parameters.

children.name: interface
children.description:
The list of interfaces on the device.

The status of an interface is available in this list in the
operational state.  If the configuration of a
system-controlled interface cannot be used by the system
(e.g., the interface hardware present does not match the
interface type), then the configuration is not applied to
the system-controlled interface shown in the operational
state.  If the configuration of a user-controlled interface
cannot be used by the system, the configured interface is
not instantiated in the operational state.

System-controlled interfaces created by the system are
always present in this list in the operational state,
whether or not they are configured.

children.name: name
children.description:
The name of the interface.

A device MAY restrict the allowed values for this leaf,
possibly depending on the type of the interface.
For system-controlled interfaces, this leaf is the
device-specific name of the interface.

If a client tries to create configuration for a
system-controlled interface that is not present in the
operational state, the server MAY reject the request if
the implementation does not support pre-provisioning of
interfaces or if the name refers to an interface that can
never exist in the system.  A Network Configuration
Protocol (NETCONF) server MUST reply with an rpc-error
with the error-tag 'invalid-value' in this case.

If the device supports pre-provisioning of interface
configuration, the 'pre-provisioning' feature is
advertised.

If the device allows arbitrarily named user-controlled
interfaces, the 'arbitrary-names' feature is advertised.
When a configured user-controlled interface is created by
the system, it is instantiated with the same name in the
operational state.

A server implementation MAY map this leaf to the ifName
MIB object.  Such an implementation needs to use some
mechanism to handle the differences in size and characters
allowed between this leaf and ifName.  The definition of
such a mechanism is outside the scope of this document.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifName

children.name: description
children.description:
A textual description of the interface.

A server implementation MAY map this leaf to the ifAlias
MIB object.  Such an implementation needs to use some
mechanism to handle the differences in size and characters
allowed between this leaf and ifAlias.  The definition of
such a mechanism is outside the scope of this document.

Since ifAlias is defined to be stored in non-volatile
storage, the MIB implementation MUST map ifAlias to the
value of 'description' in the persistently stored
configuration.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifAlias

children.name: type
children.description:
The type of the interface.

When an interface entry is created, a server MAY
initialize the type leaf with a valid value, e.g., if it
is possible to derive the type from the name of the
interface.

If a client tries to set the type of an interface to a
value that can never be used by the system, e.g., if the
type is not supported or if the type does not match the
name of the interface, the server MUST reject the request.
A NETCONF server MUST reply with an rpc-error with the
error-tag 'invalid-value' in this case.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifType

children.name: enabled
children.description:
This leaf contains the configured, desired state of the
interface.

Systems that implement the IF-MIB use the value of this
leaf in the intended configuration to set
IF-MIB.ifAdminStatus to 'up' or 'down' after an ifEntry
has been initialized, as described in RFC 2863.

Changes in this leaf in the intended configuration are
reflected in ifAdminStatus.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifAdminStatus

children.name: link-up-down-trap-enable
children.description:
Controls whether linkUp/linkDown SNMP notifications
should be generated for this interface.

If this node is not configured, the value 'enabled' is
operationally used by the server for interfaces that do
not operate on top of any other interface (i.e., there are
no 'lower-layer-if' entries), and 'disabled' otherwise.
children.reference:
RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB -
          ifLinkUpDownTrapEnable

children.name: admin-status
children.description:
The desired state of the interface.

This leaf has the same read semantics as ifAdminStatus.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifAdminStatus

children.name: oper-status
children.description:
The current operational state of the interface.

This leaf has the same semantics as ifOperStatus.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifOperStatus

children.name: last-change
children.description:
The time the interface entered its current operational
state.  If the current state was entered prior to the
last re-initialization of the local network management
subsystem, then this node is not present.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifLastChange

children.name: if-index
children.description:
The ifIndex value for the ifEntry represented by this
interface.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifIndex

children.name: phys-address
children.description:
The interface's address at its protocol sub-layer.  For
example, for an 802.x interface, this object normally
contains a Media Access Control (MAC) address.  The
interface's media-specific modules must define the bit
and byte ordering and the format of the value of this
object.  For interfaces that do not have such an address
(e.g., a serial line), this node is not present.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifPhysAddress

children.name: higher-layer-if
children.description:
A list of references to interfaces layered on top of this
interface.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifStackTable

children.name: lower-layer-if
children.description:
A list of references to interfaces layered underneath this
interface.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifStackTable

children.name: speed
children.description:
An estimate of the interface's current bandwidth in bits
per second.  For interfaces that do not vary in
bandwidth or for those where no accurate estimation can
be made, this node should contain the nominal bandwidth.
For interfaces that have no concept of bandwidth, this
node is not present.
children.reference:
RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB -
          ifSpeed, ifHighSpeed

children.name: statistics
children.description: A collection of interface-related statistics objects.

children.name: discontinuity-time
children.description:
The time on the most recent occasion at which any one or
more of this interface's counters suffered a
discontinuity.  If no such discontinuities have occurred
since the last re-initialization of the local management
subsystem, then this node contains the time the local
management subsystem re-initialized itself.

children.name: in-octets
children.description:
The total number of octets received on the interface,
including framing characters.

Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifHCInOctets

children.name: in-unicast-pkts
children.description:
The number of packets, delivered by this sub-layer to a
higher (sub-)layer, that were not addressed to a
multicast or broadcast address at this sub-layer.

Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifHCInUcastPkts

children.name: in-broadcast-pkts
children.description:
The number of packets, delivered by this sub-layer to a
higher (sub-)layer, that were addressed to a broadcast
address at this sub-layer.

Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference:
RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB -
          ifHCInBroadcastPkts

children.name: in-multicast-pkts
children.description:
The number of packets, delivered by this sub-layer to a
higher (sub-)layer, that were addressed to a multicast
address at this sub-layer.  For a MAC-layer protocol,
this includes both Group and Functional addresses.


Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference:
RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB -
          ifHCInMulticastPkts

children.name: in-discards
children.description:
The number of inbound packets that were chosen to be
discarded even though no errors had been detected to
prevent their being deliverable to a higher-layer
protocol.  One possible reason for discarding such a
packet could be to free up buffer space.

Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifInDiscards

children.name: in-errors
children.description:
For packet-oriented interfaces, the number of inbound
packets that contained errors preventing them from being
deliverable to a higher-layer protocol.  For character-
oriented or fixed-length interfaces, the number of
inbound transmission units that contained errors
preventing them from being deliverable to a higher-layer
protocol.

Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifInErrors

children.name: in-unknown-protos
children.description:
For packet-oriented interfaces, the number of packets
received via the interface that were discarded because
of an unknown or unsupported protocol.  For
character-oriented or fixed-length interfaces that
support protocol multiplexing, the number of
transmission units received via the interface that were
discarded because of an unknown or unsupported protocol.
For any interface that does not support protocol
multiplexing, this counter is not present.

Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifInUnknownProtos

children.name: out-octets
children.description:
The total number of octets transmitted out of the
interface, including framing characters.

Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifHCOutOctets

children.name: out-unicast-pkts
children.description:
The total number of packets that higher-level protocols
requested be transmitted and that were not addressed
to a multicast or broadcast address at this sub-layer,
including those that were discarded or not sent.

Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifHCOutUcastPkts

children.name: out-broadcast-pkts
children.description:
The total number of packets that higher-level protocols
requested be transmitted and that were addressed to a
broadcast address at this sub-layer, including those
that were discarded or not sent.

Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference:
RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB -
          ifHCOutBroadcastPkts

children.name: out-multicast-pkts
children.description:
The total number of packets that higher-level protocols
requested be transmitted and that were addressed to a
multicast address at this sub-layer, including those
that were discarded or not sent.  For a MAC-layer
protocol, this includes both Group and Functional
addresses.

Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference:
RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB -
          ifHCOutMulticastPkts

children.name: out-discards
children.description:
The number of outbound packets that were chosen to be
discarded even though no errors had been detected to
prevent their being transmitted.  One possible reason
for discarding such a packet could be to free up buffer
space.


Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifOutDiscards

children.name: out-errors
children.description:
For packet-oriented interfaces, the number of outbound
packets that could not be transmitted because of errors.
For character-oriented or fixed-length interfaces, the
number of outbound transmission units that could not be
transmitted because of errors.

Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifOutErrors

children.name: ipv6-address
children.description: IPv6 address of the local DS-Lite endpoint (AFTR or B4).
children.reference:
RFC 6333: Dual-Stack Lite Broadband Deployments Following
          IPv4 Exhaustion

children.name: ipv4-address
children.description:
IPv4 address of the local DS-Lite AFTR or B4.

192.0.0.1 is reserved for the AFTR element, while
192.0.0.0/29 is reserved for the B4 element.

This address can be used to report ICMP problems and will
appear in traceroute outputs.
children.reference:
RFC 6333: Dual-Stack Lite Broadband Deployments Following
          IPv4 Exhaustion

children.name: aftr-ipv6-addr
children.description:
Indicates the AFTR's IPv6 address to be used by a B4
element.
children.reference:
RFC 6333: Dual-Stack Lite Broadband Deployments Following
          IPv4 Exhaustion

children.name: tunnel-mtu
children.description:
Configures a tunnel MTU.

RFC 6908 specifies that since fragmentation and reassembly
are not optimal, the operator should do everything possible
to eliminate the need for them.  If the operator uses simple
IPv4-in-IPv6 softwire, it is recommended that the MTU size
of the IPv6 network between the B4 and the AFTR account
for the additional overhead (40 bytes).
children.reference: RFC 6908: Deployment Considerations for Dual-Stack Lite

children.name: v6-v4-dscp-preservation
children.description:
Copies the DSCP value from the IPv6 header, and vice versa.

According to Section 2.10 of RFC 6908, operators should
use the uniform model by provisioning the network such
that the AFTR/B4 copies the DSCP value in the IPv4 header
to the Traffic Class field in the IPv6 header, after the
IPv4-in-IPv6 encapsulation.
children.reference: Section 2.10 of RFC 6908

children.name: ipv4
children.description: Parameters for the IPv4 address family.

children.name: enabled
children.description:
Controls whether IPv4 is enabled or disabled on this
interface.  When IPv4 is enabled, this interface is
connected to an IPv4 stack, and the interface can send
and receive IPv4 packets.

children.name: forwarding
children.description:
Controls IPv4 packet forwarding of datagrams received by,
but not addressed to, this interface.  IPv4 routers
forward datagrams.  IPv4 hosts do not (except those
source-routed via the host).

children.name: mtu
children.description:
The size, in octets, of the largest IPv4 packet that the
interface will send and receive.

The server may restrict the allowed values for this leaf,
depending on the interface's type.

If this leaf is not configured, the operationally used MTU
depends on the interface's type.
children.reference: RFC 791: Internet Protocol

children.name: address
children.description: The list of IPv4 addresses on the interface.

children.name: ip
children.description: The IPv4 address on the interface.

children.name: subnet
children.description:
The subnet can be specified as a prefix length or,
if the server supports non-contiguous netmasks, as
a netmask.

children.name: prefix-length
children.description: The length of the subnet prefix.

children.name: netmask
children.description: The subnet specified as a netmask.

children.name: origin
children.description: The origin of this address.

children.name: neighbor
children.description:
A list of mappings from IPv4 addresses to
link-layer addresses.

Entries in this list in the intended configuration are
used as static entries in the ARP Cache.

In the operational state, this list represents the ARP
Cache.
children.reference: RFC 826: An Ethernet Address Resolution Protocol

children.name: ip
children.description: The IPv4 address of the neighbor node.

children.name: link-layer-address
children.description: The link-layer address of the neighbor node.

children.name: origin
children.description: The origin of this neighbor entry.

children.name: bind-ni-name
children.description: Network instance to which IPv4 interface is bound.

children.name: vrrp
children.description: Configures VRRP version 2 or 3 for IPv4.

children.name: vrrp-instance
children.description:
Defines a virtual router, identified by a VRID, within the
IPv4 address space.

children.name: vrid
children.description: Virtual Router ID (i.e., VRID).

children.name: version
children.description: Version 2 or 3 of VRRP.

children.name: log-state-change
children.description:
Generates VRRP state change messages each time the
VRRP instance changes state (from 'up' to 'down'
or 'down' to 'up').

children.name: preempt
children.description:
Enables a higher-priority VRRP backup router to preempt a
lower-priority VRRP master.

children.name: enabled
children.description: 'true' if preemption is enabled.

children.name: hold-time
children.description:
Hold time, in seconds, for which a higher-priority VRRP
backup router must wait before preempting a lower-priority
VRRP master.

children.name: priority
children.description:
Configures the VRRP election priority for the backup
virtual router.

children.name: accept-mode
children.description:
Controls whether a virtual router in master state will
accept packets addressed to the address owner's IPvX address
as its own if it is not the IPvX address owner.  The default
is 'false'.  Deployments that rely on, for example, pinging
the address owner's IPvX address may wish to configure
accept-mode to 'true'.

Note: IPv6 Neighbor Solicitations and Neighbor
Advertisements MUST NOT be dropped when accept-mode
is 'false'.

children.name: advertise-interval-choice
children.description:
The options for the advertisement interval at which VRRPv2
or VRRPv3 advertisements are sent from the specified
interface.

children.name: advertise-interval-sec
children.description:
Configures the interval that VRRPv2 advertisements
are sent from the specified interface.

children.name: advertise-interval-centi-sec
children.description:
Configures the interval that VRRPv3 advertisements
are sent from the specified interface.

children.name: track
children.description:
Enables the specified VRRP instance to track interfaces
or networks.

children.name: interfaces
children.description:
Enables the specified VRRPv2 or VRRPv3 instance to track
interfaces.  Interface tracking prevents traffic loss by
detecting the availability of interfaces.  The operational
states of other interfaces are associated with the
priority of a VRRP router.  When a tracked interface
becomes unavailable (or 'operational down'), the priority
of the VRRP router decrements.  When an unavailable
interface becomes available again, the priority of the
VRRP router is incremented by the same amount.

children.name: interface
children.description: Interface to track.

children.name: interface
children.description: Interface to track.

children.name: priority-decrement
children.description:
Specifies how much to decrement the priority of the
VRRP instance if the interface goes down.

children.name: networks
children.description:
Enables the VRRPv2 or VRRPv3 router instance to track the
specified networks through their IPv4 network prefixes.
Network tracking prevents traffic loss by detecting
network connectivity failure.  The states of
connectivity to some networks are associated with the
priority of a VRRP router.  When connectivity to a
tracked network represented by its prefix is lost, the
priority of the VRRP router decrements.  When an
unavailable network is again reachable, the priority of
the VRRP router is incremented by the same amount.

children.name: network
children.description:
Enables the specified VRRPv2 or VRRPv3 instance to
track an IPv4 network by specifying the prefix of the
IPv4 network.

children.name: prefix
children.description: The IPv4 prefix of the network to track.

children.name: priority-decrement
children.description:
Specifies how much to decrement the priority of the
VRRP router if there is a failure in the IPv4
network.

children.name: virtual-ipv4-addresses
children.description:
Configures the virtual IPv4 address for the
VRRP interface.

children.name: virtual-ipv4-address
children.description:
Virtual IPv4 addresses for a single VRRP instance.  For a
VRRP owner router, the virtual address must match one
of the IPv4 addresses configured on the interface
corresponding to the virtual router.

children.name: ipv4-address
children.description: An IPv4 address associated with a virtual router.
children.reference:
RFC 5798: Virtual Router Redundancy Protocol (VRRP)
          Version 3 for IPv4 and IPv6.  Section 1.2

children.name: state
children.description: Operational state.

children.name: is-owner
children.description: Set to 'true' if this virtual router is the owner.

children.name: last-adv-source
children.description: Last advertised IPv4/IPv6 source address.

children.name: up-datetime
children.description:
The date and time when this virtual router
transitioned out of 'init' state.

children.name: master-down-interval
children.description:
Time interval for the backup virtual router to declare
'master down'.

children.name: skew-time
children.description:
Calculated based on the priority and advertisement
interval configuration command parameters.  See RFC 3768.

children.name: last-event
children.description: Last reported event.

children.name: new-master-reason
children.description:
Indicates why the virtual router has transitioned to
master state.

children.name: statistics
children.description: VRRP statistics.

children.name: discontinuity-datetime
children.description:
The time on the most recent occasion at which any one or
more of the VRRP statistics counters suffered a
discontinuity.  If no such discontinuities have occurred
since the last re-initialization of the local management
subsystem, then this node contains the time that the
local management subsystem re-initialized itself.

children.name: master-transitions
children.description:
The total number of times that this virtual router's
state has transitioned to 'master'.

children.name: advertisement-rcvd
children.description:
The total number of VRRP advertisements received by
this virtual router.

children.name: advertisement-sent
children.description:
The total number of VRRP advertisements sent by
this virtual router.

children.name: interval-errors
children.description:
The total number of VRRP advertisement packets received
with an advertisement interval different than the
interval configured for the local virtual router.

children.name: priority-zero-pkts-rcvd
children.description:
The total number of VRRP packets received by the
virtual router with a priority of 0.

children.name: priority-zero-pkts-sent
children.description:
The total number of VRRP packets sent by the
virtual router with a priority of 0.

children.name: invalid-type-pkts-rcvd
children.description:
The number of VRRP packets received by the virtual
router with an invalid value in the 'type' field.

children.name: address-list-errors
children.description:
The total number of packets received with an
address list that does not match the locally
configured address list for the virtual router.

children.name: packet-length-errors
children.description:
The total number of packets received with a packet
length less than the length of the VRRP header.

children.name: ipv6
children.description: Parameters for the IPv6 address family.

children.name: enabled
children.description:
Controls whether IPv6 is enabled or disabled on this
interface.  When IPv6 is enabled, this interface is
connected to an IPv6 stack, and the interface can send
and receive IPv6 packets.

children.name: forwarding
children.description:
Controls IPv6 packet forwarding of datagrams received by,
but not addressed to, this interface.  IPv6 routers
forward datagrams.  IPv6 hosts do not (except those
source-routed via the host).
children.reference:
RFC 4861: Neighbor Discovery for IP version 6 (IPv6)
          Section 6.2.1, IsRouter

children.name: mtu
children.description:
The size, in octets, of the largest IPv6 packet that the
interface will send and receive.

The server may restrict the allowed values for this leaf,
depending on the interface's type.

If this leaf is not configured, the operationally used MTU
depends on the interface's type.
children.reference:
RFC 8200: Internet Protocol, Version 6 (IPv6)
          Specification
          Section 5

children.name: address
children.description: The list of IPv6 addresses on the interface.

children.name: ip
children.description: The IPv6 address on the interface.

children.name: prefix-length
children.description: The length of the subnet prefix.

children.name: origin
children.description: The origin of this address.

children.name: status
children.description:
The status of an address.  Most of the states correspond
to states from the IPv6 Stateless Address
Autoconfiguration protocol.
children.reference:
RFC 4293: Management Information Base for the
          Internet Protocol (IP)
          - IpAddressStatusTC
RFC 4862: IPv6 Stateless Address Autoconfiguration

children.name: neighbor
children.description:
A list of mappings from IPv6 addresses to
link-layer addresses.

Entries in this list in the intended configuration are
used as static entries in the Neighbor Cache.

In the operational state, this list represents the
Neighbor Cache.
children.reference: RFC 4861: Neighbor Discovery for IP version 6 (IPv6)

children.name: ip
children.description: The IPv6 address of the neighbor node.

children.name: link-layer-address
children.description:
The link-layer address of the neighbor node.

In the operational state, if the neighbor's 'state' leaf
is 'incomplete', this leaf is not instantiated.

children.name: origin
children.description: The origin of this neighbor entry.

children.name: is-router
children.description: Indicates that the neighbor node acts as a router.

children.name: state
children.description:
The Neighbor Unreachability Detection state of this
entry.
children.reference:
RFC 4861: Neighbor Discovery for IP version 6 (IPv6)
          Section 7.3.2

children.name: dup-addr-detect-transmits
children.description:
The number of consecutive Neighbor Solicitation messages
sent while performing Duplicate Address Detection on a
tentative address.  A value of zero indicates that
Duplicate Address Detection is not performed on
tentative addresses.  A value of one indicates a single
transmission with no follow-up retransmissions.
children.reference: RFC 4862: IPv6 Stateless Address Autoconfiguration

children.name: autoconf
children.description:
Parameters to control the autoconfiguration of IPv6
addresses, as described in RFC 4862.
children.reference: RFC 4862: IPv6 Stateless Address Autoconfiguration

children.name: create-global-addresses
children.description:
If enabled, the host creates global addresses as
described in RFC 4862.
children.reference:
RFC 4862: IPv6 Stateless Address Autoconfiguration
          Section 5.5

children.name: create-temporary-addresses
children.description:
If enabled, the host creates temporary addresses as
described in RFC 4941.
children.reference:
RFC 4941: Privacy Extensions for Stateless Address
          Autoconfiguration in IPv6

children.name: temporary-valid-lifetime
children.description:
The time period during which the temporary address
is valid.
children.reference:
RFC 4941: Privacy Extensions for Stateless Address
          Autoconfiguration in IPv6
          - TEMP_VALID_LIFETIME

children.name: temporary-preferred-lifetime
children.description:
The time period during which the temporary address is
preferred.
children.reference:
RFC 4941: Privacy Extensions for Stateless Address
          Autoconfiguration in IPv6
          - TEMP_PREFERRED_LIFETIME

children.name: ipv6-router-advertisements
children.description: Support for IPv6 Router Advertisements.

children.name: send-advertisements
children.description:
A flag indicating whether or not the router sends
periodic Router Advertisements and responds to
Router Solicitations.
children.reference:
RFC 4861: Neighbor Discovery for IP version 6 (IPv6)
          - AdvSendAdvertisements

children.name: max-rtr-adv-interval
children.description:
The maximum time allowed between sending unsolicited
multicast Router Advertisements from the interface.
children.reference:
RFC 4861: Neighbor Discovery for IP version 6 (IPv6)
          - MaxRtrAdvInterval

children.name: min-rtr-adv-interval
children.description:
The minimum time allowed between sending unsolicited
multicast Router Advertisements from the interface.

The default value to be used operationally if this
leaf is not configured is determined as follows:

- if max-rtr-adv-interval >= 9 seconds, the default
  value is 0.33 * max-rtr-adv-interval;

- otherwise, it is 0.75 * max-rtr-adv-interval.
children.reference:
RFC 4861: Neighbor Discovery for IP version 6 (IPv6)
          - MinRtrAdvInterval

children.name: managed-flag
children.description:
The value to be placed in the 'Managed address
configuration' flag field in the Router
Advertisement.
children.reference:
RFC 4861: Neighbor Discovery for IP version 6 (IPv6)
          - AdvManagedFlag

children.name: other-config-flag
children.description:
The value to be placed in the 'Other configuration'
flag field in the Router Advertisement.
children.reference:
RFC 4861: Neighbor Discovery for IP version 6 (IPv6)
          - AdvOtherConfigFlag

children.name: link-mtu
children.description:
The value to be placed in MTU options sent by the
router.  A value of zero indicates that no MTU options
are sent.
children.reference:
RFC 4861: Neighbor Discovery for IP version 6 (IPv6)
          - AdvLinkMTU

children.name: reachable-time
children.description:
The value to be placed in the Reachable Time field in
the Router Advertisement messages sent by the router.
A value of zero means unspecified (by this router).
children.reference:
RFC 4861: Neighbor Discovery for IP version 6 (IPv6)
          - AdvReachableTime

children.name: retrans-timer
children.description:
The value to be placed in the Retrans Timer field in
the Router Advertisement messages sent by the router.
A value of zero means unspecified (by this router).
children.reference:
RFC 4861: Neighbor Discovery for IP version 6 (IPv6)
          - AdvRetransTimer

children.name: cur-hop-limit
children.description:
The value to be placed in the Cur Hop Limit field in
the Router Advertisement messages sent by the router.
A value of zero means unspecified (by this router).

If this parameter is not configured, the device SHOULD
use the IANA-specified value for the default IPv4
Time to Live (TTL) parameter that was in effect at the
time of implementation.
children.reference:
RFC 3232: Assigned Numbers: RFC 1700 is Replaced by
          an On-line Database
RFC 4861: Neighbor Discovery for IP version 6 (IPv6)
          - AdvCurHopLimit
IANA: IP Parameters
      (https://www.iana.org/assignments/ip-parameters)

children.name: default-lifetime
children.description:
The value to be placed in the Router Lifetime field of
Router Advertisements sent from the interface, in
seconds.  It MUST be either zero or between
max-rtr-adv-interval and 9000 seconds.  A value of zero
indicates that the router is not to be used as a
default router.  These limits may be overridden by
specific documents that describe how IPv6 operates over
different link layers.

If this parameter is not configured, the device SHOULD
use a value of 3 * max-rtr-adv-interval.
children.reference:
RFC 4861: Neighbor Discovery for IP version 6 (IPv6)
          - AdvDefaultLifetime

children.name: prefix-list
children.description:
Support for prefixes to be placed in Prefix
Information options in Router Advertisement messages
sent from the interface.

Prefixes that are advertised by default but do not
have their entries in the child 'prefix' list are
advertised with the default values of all parameters.

The link-local prefix SHOULD NOT be included in the
list of advertised prefixes.
children.reference:
RFC 4861: Neighbor Discovery for IP version 6 (IPv6)
          - AdvPrefixList

children.name: prefix
children.description: Support for an advertised prefix entry.

children.name: prefix-spec
children.description: IPv6 address prefix.

children.name: control-adv-prefixes
children.description:
Either (1) the prefix is explicitly removed from the
set of advertised prefixes or (2) the parameters with
which the prefix is advertised are specified (default
case).

children.name: no-advertise
children.description:
The prefix will not be advertised.

This can be used for removing the prefix from
the default set of advertised prefixes.

children.name: valid-lifetime
children.description:
The value to be placed in the Valid Lifetime
in the Prefix Information option.  The
designated value of all 1's (0xffffffff)
 represents infinity.
children.reference:
RFC 4861: Neighbor Discovery for IP version 6
          (IPv6) - AdvValidLifetime

children.name: on-link-flag
children.description:
The value to be placed in the on-link flag
('L-bit') field in the Prefix Information
option.
children.reference:
RFC 4861: Neighbor Discovery for IP version 6
          (IPv6) - AdvOnLinkFlag

children.name: preferred-lifetime
children.description:
The value to be placed in the Preferred
Lifetime in the Prefix Information option.
The designated value of all 1's (0xffffffff)
represents infinity.
children.reference:
RFC 4861: Neighbor Discovery for IP version 6
          (IPv6) - AdvPreferredLifetime

children.name: autonomous-flag
children.description:
The value to be placed in the Autonomous Flag
field in the Prefix Information option.
children.reference:
RFC 4861: Neighbor Discovery for IP version 6
          (IPv6) - AdvAutonomousFlag

children.name: bind-ni-name
children.description: Network instance to which IPv6 interface is bound.

children.name: vrrp
children.description: Configures VRRP version 3 for IPv6.

children.name: vrrp-instance
children.description:
Defines a virtual router, identified by a VRID, within the
IPv6 address space.

children.name: vrid
children.description: Virtual Router ID (i.e., VRID).

children.name: version
children.description: Version 2 or 3 of VRRP.

children.name: log-state-change
children.description:
Generates VRRP state change messages each time the
VRRP instance changes state (from 'up' to 'down'
or 'down' to 'up').

children.name: preempt
children.description:
Enables a higher-priority VRRP backup router to preempt a
lower-priority VRRP master.

children.name: enabled
children.description: 'true' if preemption is enabled.

children.name: hold-time
children.description:
Hold time, in seconds, for which a higher-priority VRRP
backup router must wait before preempting a lower-priority
VRRP master.

children.name: priority
children.description:
Configures the VRRP election priority for the backup
virtual router.

children.name: accept-mode
children.description:
Controls whether a virtual router in master state will
accept packets addressed to the address owner's IPvX address
as its own if it is not the IPvX address owner.  The default
is 'false'.  Deployments that rely on, for example, pinging
the address owner's IPvX address may wish to configure
accept-mode to 'true'.

Note: IPv6 Neighbor Solicitations and Neighbor
Advertisements MUST NOT be dropped when accept-mode
is 'false'.

children.name: advertise-interval-centi-sec
children.description:
Configures the interval that VRRPv3 advertisements
are sent from the specified interface.

children.name: track
children.description:
Enables the specified VRRP instance to track interfaces
or networks.

children.name: interfaces
children.description:
Enables the specified VRRPv2 or VRRPv3 instance to track
interfaces.  Interface tracking prevents traffic loss by
detecting the availability of interfaces.  The operational
states of other interfaces are associated with the
priority of a VRRP router.  When a tracked interface
becomes unavailable (or 'operational down'), the priority
of the VRRP router decrements.  When an unavailable
interface becomes available again, the priority of the
VRRP router is incremented by the same amount.

children.name: interface
children.description: Interface to track.

children.name: interface
children.description: Interface to track.

children.name: priority-decrement
children.description:
Specifies how much to decrement the priority of the
VRRP instance if the interface goes down.

children.name: networks
children.description:
Enables the VRRPv2 or VRRPv3 router instance to track the
specified networks through their IPv6 network prefixes.
Network tracking prevents traffic loss by detecting
network connectivity failure.  The states of
connectivity to some networks are associated with the
priority of a VRRP router.  When connectivity to a
tracked network represented by its prefix is lost, the
priority of the VRRP router decrements.  When an
unavailable network is again reachable, the priority of
the VRRP router is incremented by the same amount.

children.name: network
children.description:
Enables the specified VRRPv2 or VRRPv3 instance to
track an IPv6 network by specifying the prefix of the
IPv6 network.

children.name: prefix
children.description: The IPv6 prefix of the network to track.

children.name: priority-decrement
children.description:
Specifies how much to decrement the priority of the
VRRP router if there is a failure in the IPv6
network.

children.name: virtual-ipv6-addresses
children.description:
Configures the virtual IPv6 address for the
VRRP interface.

children.name: virtual-ipv6-address
children.description:
Two IPv6 addresses are allowed.  The first address must
be a link-local address.  The second address can be a
link-local or global address.

children.name: ipv6-address
children.description: An IPv6 address associated with a virtual router.
children.reference:
RFC 5798: Virtual Router Redundancy Protocol (VRRP)
          Version 3 for IPv4 and IPv6.  Section 1.3

children.name: state
children.description: Operational state.

children.name: is-owner
children.description: Set to 'true' if this virtual router is the owner.

children.name: last-adv-source
children.description: Last advertised IPv4/IPv6 source address.

children.name: up-datetime
children.description:
The date and time when this virtual router
transitioned out of 'init' state.

children.name: master-down-interval
children.description:
Time interval for the backup virtual router to declare
'master down'.

children.name: skew-time
children.description:
Calculated based on the priority and advertisement
interval configuration command parameters.  See RFC 3768.

children.name: last-event
children.description: Last reported event.

children.name: new-master-reason
children.description:
Indicates why the virtual router has transitioned to
master state.

children.name: statistics
children.description: VRRP statistics.

children.name: discontinuity-datetime
children.description:
The time on the most recent occasion at which any one or
more of the VRRP statistics counters suffered a
discontinuity.  If no such discontinuities have occurred
since the last re-initialization of the local management
subsystem, then this node contains the time that the
local management subsystem re-initialized itself.

children.name: master-transitions
children.description:
The total number of times that this virtual router's
state has transitioned to 'master'.

children.name: advertisement-rcvd
children.description:
The total number of VRRP advertisements received by
this virtual router.

children.name: advertisement-sent
children.description:
The total number of VRRP advertisements sent by
this virtual router.

children.name: interval-errors
children.description:
The total number of VRRP advertisement packets received
with an advertisement interval different than the
interval configured for the local virtual router.

children.name: priority-zero-pkts-rcvd
children.description:
The total number of VRRP packets received by the
virtual router with a priority of 0.

children.name: priority-zero-pkts-sent
children.description:
The total number of VRRP packets sent by the
virtual router with a priority of 0.

children.name: invalid-type-pkts-rcvd
children.description:
The number of VRRP packets received by the virtual
router with an invalid value in the 'type' field.

children.name: address-list-errors
children.description:
The total number of packets received with an
address list that does not match the locally
configured address list for the virtual router.

children.name: packet-length-errors
children.description:
The total number of packets received with a packet
length less than the length of the VRRP header.

children.name: bind-lne-name
children.description:
Logical network element ID to which the interface is
bound.

children.name: bind-ni-name
children.description: Network instance to which an interface is bound.

children.name: interfaces-state
children.description: Data nodes for the operational state of interfaces.

children.name: interface
children.description:
The list of interfaces on the device.

System-controlled interfaces created by the system are
always present in this list, whether or not they are
configured.

children.name: name
children.description:
The name of the interface.

A server implementation MAY map this leaf to the ifName
MIB object.  Such an implementation needs to use some
mechanism to handle the differences in size and characters
allowed between this leaf and ifName.  The definition of
such a mechanism is outside the scope of this document.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifName

children.name: type
children.description: The type of the interface.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifType

children.name: admin-status
children.description:
The desired state of the interface.

This leaf has the same read semantics as ifAdminStatus.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifAdminStatus

children.name: oper-status
children.description:
The current operational state of the interface.

This leaf has the same semantics as ifOperStatus.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifOperStatus

children.name: last-change
children.description:
The time the interface entered its current operational
state.  If the current state was entered prior to the
last re-initialization of the local network management
subsystem, then this node is not present.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifLastChange

children.name: if-index
children.description:
The ifIndex value for the ifEntry represented by this
interface.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifIndex

children.name: phys-address
children.description:
The interface's address at its protocol sub-layer.  For
example, for an 802.x interface, this object normally
contains a Media Access Control (MAC) address.  The
interface's media-specific modules must define the bit
and byte ordering and the format of the value of this
object.  For interfaces that do not have such an address
(e.g., a serial line), this node is not present.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifPhysAddress

children.name: higher-layer-if
children.description:
A list of references to interfaces layered on top of this
interface.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifStackTable

children.name: lower-layer-if
children.description:
A list of references to interfaces layered underneath this
interface.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifStackTable

children.name: speed
children.description:
An estimate of the interface's current bandwidth in bits
per second.  For interfaces that do not vary in
bandwidth or for those where no accurate estimation can

be made, this node should contain the nominal bandwidth.
For interfaces that have no concept of bandwidth, this
node is not present.
children.reference:
RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB -
          ifSpeed, ifHighSpeed

children.name: statistics
children.description: A collection of interface-related statistics objects.

children.name: discontinuity-time
children.description:
The time on the most recent occasion at which any one or
more of this interface's counters suffered a
discontinuity.  If no such discontinuities have occurred
since the last re-initialization of the local management
subsystem, then this node contains the time the local
management subsystem re-initialized itself.

children.name: in-octets
children.description:
The total number of octets received on the interface,
including framing characters.

Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifHCInOctets

children.name: in-unicast-pkts
children.description:
The number of packets, delivered by this sub-layer to a
higher (sub-)layer, that were not addressed to a
multicast or broadcast address at this sub-layer.
Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifHCInUcastPkts

children.name: in-broadcast-pkts
children.description:
The number of packets, delivered by this sub-layer to a
higher (sub-)layer, that were addressed to a broadcast
address at this sub-layer.

Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference:
RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB -
          ifHCInBroadcastPkts

children.name: in-multicast-pkts
children.description:
The number of packets, delivered by this sub-layer to a
higher (sub-)layer, that were addressed to a multicast
address at this sub-layer.  For a MAC-layer protocol,
this includes both Group and Functional addresses.

Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference:
RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB -
          ifHCInMulticastPkts

children.name: in-discards
children.description:
The number of inbound packets that were chosen to be
discarded even though no errors had been detected to
prevent their being deliverable to a higher-layer
protocol.  One possible reason for discarding such a
packet could be to free up buffer space.

Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifInDiscards

children.name: in-errors
children.description:
For packet-oriented interfaces, the number of inbound
packets that contained errors preventing them from being
deliverable to a higher-layer protocol.  For character-
oriented or fixed-length interfaces, the number of
inbound transmission units that contained errors
preventing them from being deliverable to a higher-layer
protocol.

Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifInErrors

children.name: in-unknown-protos
children.description:
For packet-oriented interfaces, the number of packets
received via the interface that were discarded because
of an unknown or unsupported protocol.  For
character-oriented or fixed-length interfaces that
support protocol multiplexing, the number of
transmission units received via the interface that were
discarded because of an unknown or unsupported protocol.
For any interface that does not support protocol
multiplexing, this counter is not present.
Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifInUnknownProtos

children.name: out-octets
children.description:
The total number of octets transmitted out of the
interface, including framing characters.

Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifHCOutOctets

children.name: out-unicast-pkts
children.description:
The total number of packets that higher-level protocols
requested be transmitted and that were not addressed
to a multicast or broadcast address at this sub-layer,
including those that were discarded or not sent.

Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifHCOutUcastPkts

children.name: out-broadcast-pkts
children.description:
The total number of packets that higher-level protocols
requested be transmitted and that were addressed to a
broadcast address at this sub-layer, including those
that were discarded or not sent.

Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference:
RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB -
          ifHCOutBroadcastPkts

children.name: out-multicast-pkts
children.description:
The total number of packets that higher-level protocols
requested be transmitted and that were addressed to a
multicast address at this sub-layer, including those
that were discarded or not sent.  For a MAC-layer
protocol, this includes both Group and Functional
addresses.

Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference:
RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB -
          ifHCOutMulticastPkts

children.name: out-discards
children.description:
The number of outbound packets that were chosen to be
discarded even though no errors had been detected to
prevent their being transmitted.  One possible reason
for discarding such a packet could be to free up buffer
space.

Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB - ifOutDiscards

children.name: out-errors
children.description:
For packet-oriented interfaces, the number of outbound
packets that could not be transmitted because of errors.
For character-oriented or fixed-length interfaces, the
number of outbound transmission units that could not be
transmitted because of errors.

Discontinuities in the value of this counter can occur
at re-initialization of the management system and at
other times as indicated by the value of
'discontinuity-time'.

children.name: ipv6-router-advertisements
children.description: Parameters of IPv6 Router Advertisements.

children.name: send-advertisements
children.description:
A flag indicating whether or not the router sends
periodic Router Advertisements and responds to
Router Solicitations.

children.name: max-rtr-adv-interval
children.description:
The maximum time allowed between sending unsolicited
multicast Router Advertisements from the interface.

children.name: min-rtr-adv-interval
children.description:
The minimum time allowed between sending unsolicited
multicast Router Advertisements from the interface.

children.name: managed-flag
children.description:
The value that is placed in the 'Managed address
configuration' flag field in the Router Advertisement.

children.name: other-config-flag
children.description:
The value that is placed in the 'Other configuration' flag
field in the Router Advertisement.

children.name: link-mtu
children.description:
The value that is placed in MTU options sent by the
router.  A value of zero indicates that no MTU options
are sent.

children.name: reachable-time
children.description:
The value that is placed in the Reachable Time field in
the Router Advertisement messages sent by the router.  A
value of zero means unspecified (by this router).

children.name: retrans-timer
children.description:
The value that is placed in the Retrans Timer field in the
Router Advertisement messages sent by the router.  A value
of zero means unspecified (by this router).

children.name: cur-hop-limit
children.description:
The value that is placed in the Cur Hop Limit field in the
Router Advertisement messages sent by the router.  A value
of zero means unspecified (by this router).

children.name: default-lifetime
children.description:
The value that is placed in the Router Lifetime field of
Router Advertisements sent from the interface, in seconds.
A value of zero indicates that the router is not to be
used as a default router.

children.name: prefix-list
children.description:
A list of prefixes that are placed in Prefix Information
options in Router Advertisement messages sent from the
interface.

By default, these are all prefixes that the router
advertises via routing protocols as being on-link for the
interface from which the advertisement is sent.

children.name: prefix
children.description: Advertised prefix entry and its parameters.

children.name: prefix-spec
children.description: IPv6 address prefix.

children.name: valid-lifetime
children.description:
The value that is placed in the Valid Lifetime in the
Prefix Information option.  The designated value of
all 1's (0xffffffff) represents infinity.

An implementation SHOULD keep this value constant in
consecutive advertisements, except when it is
explicitly changed in configuration.

children.name: on-link-flag
children.description:
The value that is placed in the on-link flag ('L-bit')
field in the Prefix Information option.

children.name: preferred-lifetime
children.description:
The value that is placed in the Preferred Lifetime in
the Prefix Information option, in seconds.  The
designated value of all 1's (0xffffffff) represents
infinity.

An implementation SHOULD keep this value constant in
consecutive advertisements, except when it is
explicitly changed in configuration.

children.name: autonomous-flag
children.description:
The value that is placed in the Autonomous Flag field
in the Prefix Information option.

Separate lifetime specification for accept

children.description:
AES Key Wrap encryption for key-chain key-strings.  The

strings using the hex-key-string leaf.

children.description: Enable AES Key Wrap encryption.

children.name: l2vpn-svc
children.description: Container for L2VPN services.

children.name: vpn-profiles
children.description: Container for VPN profiles.

children.name: valid-provider-identifiers
children.description: Container for valid provider identifiers.

children.name: cloud-identifier
children.description:
Identification of the public cloud service or
Internet service.  Local to each administration.

children.name: qos-profile-identifier
children.description:
Identification of the QoS profile to be used.
Local to each administration.

children.name: bfd-profile-identifier
children.description:
Identification of the SP BFD profile to be used.
Local to each administration.

children.name: remote-carrier-identifier
children.description:
Identification of the remote carrier name to be used.
It can be an L2VPN partner, data-center SP, or
private CSP.  Local to each administration.

children.name: vpn-services
children.description: Container for VPN services.

children.name: vpn-service
children.description: List of VPN services.

children.name: vpn-id
children.description: Defines a service identifier.

children.name: vpn-svc-type
children.description: Service type.  By default, the service type is 'vpws'.

children.name: customer-name
children.description: Customer name.

children.name: svc-topo
children.description:
Defines the service topology, e.g.,
'any-to-any', 'hub-spoke'.

children.name: cloud-accesses
children.description: Container for cloud access configurations.

children.name: cloud-access
children.description: Cloud access configuration.

children.name: cloud-identifier
children.description:
Identification of the cloud service.
Local to each administration.

children.name: list-flavor
children.description:
Choice for cloud access policy.
By default, all sites in the L2VPN
MUST be authorized to access the cloud.

children.name: permit-any
children.description: Allow all sites.

children.name: permit-site
children.description: Site ID to be authorized.

children.name: deny-site
children.description: Site ID to be denied.

children.name: frame-delivery
children.description: Multicast global parameters for the VPN service.

children.name: customer-tree-flavors
children.description: Types of trees used by the customer.

children.name: tree-flavor
children.description: Type of tree to be used.

children.name: bum-deliveries
children.description: Defines the frame delivery types and modes.

children.name: bum-delivery
children.description: List of frame delivery types and modes.

children.name: frame-type
children.description:
Type of frame delivery.  It supports unicast
frame delivery, multicast frame delivery,
and broadcast frame delivery.

children.name: delivery-mode
children.description:
Defines the frame delivery mode
('unconditional' (default), 'conditional',
or 'discard').  By default, service frames are
unconditionally delivered to the destination site.

children.name: multicast-gp-port-mapping
children.description:
Describes the way in which each interface is
associated with the multicast group.

children.name: extranet-vpns
children.description: Container for extranet VPN configurations.

children.name: extranet-vpn
children.description:
List of extranet VPNs to which the local VPN
is attached.

children.name: vpn-id
children.description:
Identifies the target VPN that the local VPN wants to
access.

children.name: local-sites-role
children.description:
Describes the role of the local sites in the target
VPN topology.  In the any-to-any VPN service topology,
the local sites must have the same role, which will be
'any-to-any-role'.  In the Hub-and-Spoke VPN service
topology or the Hub-and-Spoke-Disjoint VPN service
topology, the local sites must have a Hub role or a
Spoke role.

children.name: ce-vlan-preservation
children.description:
Preserves the CE-VLAN ID from ingress to egress, i.e.,
the CE-VLAN tag of the egress frame is identical to
that of the ingress frame that yielded this
egress service frame.  If all-to-one bundling within
a site is enabled, then preservation applies to all
ingress service frames.  If all-to-one bundling is
disabled, then preservation applies to tagged
ingress service frames having CE-VLAN IDs 1 through 4094.

children.name: ce-vlan-cos-preservation
children.description:
CE VLAN CoS preservation.  The PCP bits in the CE-VLAN tag
of the egress frame are identical to those of the
ingress frame that yielded this egress service frame.

children.name: carrierscarrier
children.description: The VPN is using CsC, and so MPLS is required.

children.name: sites
children.description: Container of site configurations.

children.name: site
children.description: List of sites.

children.name: site-id
children.description: Identifier of the site.

children.name: site-vpn-flavor
children.description:
Defines the way that the VPN multiplexing is
done, e.g., whether the site belongs to
a single VPN site or a multi-VPN site.  By
default, the site belongs to a single VPN.

children.name: devices
children.description: Device configurations.

children.name: device
children.description: List of devices requested by the customer.

children.name: device-id
children.description: Identifier for the device.

children.name: location
children.description: Location of the device.

children.name: management
children.description:
Management configuration.  Applicable only for a
co-managed device.

children.name: transport
children.description:
Transport protocol or address family
used for management.

children.name: address
children.description: Management address.

children.name: management
children.description: Management configuration.

children.name: type
children.description: Management type of the connection.

children.name: locations
children.description: Location of the site.

children.name: location
children.description: List of locations.

children.name: location-id
children.description: Location ID.

children.name: address
children.description: Address (number and street) of the site.

children.name: postal-code
children.description:
Postal code of the site.  The format of 'postal-code'
is similar to the 'PC' (postal code) label format
defined in RFC 4119.

children.name: state
children.description:
State (region) of the site.  This leaf can also be used
to describe a region of a country that does not have
states.

children.name: city
children.description: City of the site.

children.name: country-code
children.description:
Country of the site.  The format of 'country-code' is
similar to the 'country' label defined in RFC 4119.

children.name: site-diversity
children.description: The type of diversity constraint.

children.name: groups
children.description:
Groups to which the site belongs.
All site network accesses will inherit those group
values.

children.name: group
children.description: List of group-ids.

children.name: group-id
children.description: The group-id to which the site belongs.

children.name: vpn-policies
children.description: VPN policy.

children.name: vpn-policy
children.description: List of VPN policies.

children.name: vpn-policy-id
children.description: Unique identifier for the VPN policy.

children.name: entries
children.description: List of entries for an export policy.

children.name: id
children.description: Unique identifier for the policy entry.

children.name: filters
children.description:
If a more granular VPN attachment is necessary,
filtering can be used.  If used, it permits the
splitting of site LANs among multiple VPNs.  The
site LAN can be split based on either the LAN tag or
the LAN prefix.  If no filter is used, all the LANs
will be part of the same VPNs with the same role.

children.name: filter
children.description:
List of filters used on the site.  This list can
be augmented.

children.name: type
children.description: Type of VPN policy filter.

children.name: lan-tag
children.description:
List of Ethernet LAN tags to be matched.  An
Ethernet LAN tag identifies a particular
broadcast domain in a VPN.

children.name: vpn
children.description: List of VPNs with which the LAN is associated.

children.name: vpn-id
children.description: Reference to an L2VPN.

children.name: site-role
children.description: Role of the site in the L2VPN.

children.name: service
children.description: Service parameters on the attachment.

children.name: qos
children.description: QoS configuration.

children.name: qos-classification-policy
children.description: Configuration of the traffic classification policy.

children.name: rule
children.description: List of marking rules.

children.name: id
children.description:
A description identifying the QoS classification
policy rule.

children.name: match-type
children.description: Choice for classification.

children.name: match-flow
children.description: Describes flow-matching criteria.

children.name: dscp
children.description: DSCP value.

children.name: dot1q
children.description:
802.1Q matching.  It is a VLAN tag added into
a frame.

children.name: pcp
children.description: PCP value.

children.name: src-mac
children.description: Source MAC.

children.name: dst-mac
children.description: Destination MAC.

children.name: color-type
children.description: Color types.

children.name: target-sites
children.description: Identifies a site as a traffic destination.

children.name: any
children.description: Allow all.

children.name: vpn-id
children.description: Reference to the target VPN.

children.name: match-application
children.description: Defines the application to match.

children.name: target-class-id
children.description:
Identification of the CoS.
This identifier is internal to the
administration.

children.name: qos-profile
children.description: Qos profile configuration.

children.name: qos-profile
children.description:
Choice for the QoS profile.
Can be a standard profile or a customized profile.

children.name: standard
children.description: Standard QoS profile.

children.name: profile
children.description: QoS profile to be used.

children.name: custom
children.description: Customized QoS profile.

children.name: classes
children.description: Container for list of CoS entries.

children.name: class
children.description: List of CoS entries.

children.name: class-id
children.description:
Identification of the CoS.  This identifier is
internal to the administration.

children.name: direction
children.description:
The direction in which the QoS profile is
applied.  By default, the direction is
bidirectional.

children.name: byte-offset

(e.g., extra VLAN tags).

children.name: frame-delay

children.name: use-lowest-latency
children.description:
The traffic class should use the path
with the lowest delay.

children.name: delay-bound
children.description:
The traffic class should use a path
with a defined maximum delay.

children.name: frame-jitter

children.name: frequency
children.description:
The number of times to detect MAC duplication, where
a 'duplicate MAC address' situation has occurred and
the duplicate MAC address has been added to a list of
duplicate MAC addresses.  By default, the number of

children.name: retry-timer
children.description:

children.description:

initiating the auto-speed negotiation and

other end.  'Passive mode' means not initiating

LACP speed.  By default, the LACP speed is 10
Mbps.

children.description:

into service.

children.name: system-priority

The range is from 0 to 65535.
The default is 32768.

children.name: micro-bfd

MEP up/down.  By default, MEP up is used.

children.description:
The lowest-priority defect that is

to be reported.

The priority parameter for CCMs transmitted by

children.description:
Remote MEP ID.  The non-existence of this
leaf means that no measurements are to be
reported.

children.description:
Defines the interval between Y.1731
performance-monitoring messages.  The message
period is expressed in milliseconds.

children.name: measurement-interval
children.description:
Specifies the measurement interval for
statistics.  The measurement interval is
expressed in seconds.

children.name: cos
children.description:
CoS.  The non-existence of this leaf means that
no measurements are to be reported.

children.name: loss-measurement
children.description:
Indicates whether or not to enable loss
measurement.  By default, loss
measurement is not enabled.

children.name: synthetic-loss-measurement
children.description:
Indicates whether or not to enable synthetic loss
measurement.  By default, synthetic loss
measurement is not enabled.

children.name: delay-measurement

children.name: enable-dm
children.description:
Indicates whether or not to enable delay
measurement.  By default, delay measurement
is not enabled.

children.name: two-way
children.description:
Indicates whether delay measurement is two-way
('true') or one-way ('false').  By default,
one-way measurement is enabled.

children.name: frame-size
children.description:
Frame size.  The non-existence of this leaf
means that no measurements are to be reported.

children.name: session-type
children.description:
Session type.  By default, the session type
is 'on-demand'.  The non-existence of this
leaf means that no measurements are to be
reported.

children.description: Container of available optional configurations.

children.description:
Access priority.  The higher the access-priority

traffic.

logical access to a VPN.  In this case,
the vpn-id must be configured.

children.name: site-role
children.description:
Role of the site in the L2VPN.  When referencing
a vpn-id, the site-role setting must be added to

service topology.

input/output bandwidth of the connection or
download/upload bandwidth from the SP/site
to the site/SP.

children.description:
List of bandwidth values (e.g., per CoS,
per vpn-id).

children.description:
Indicates the bandwidth direction.  It can be
the bandwidth download direction from the SP to
the site or the bandwidth upload direction from
the site to the SP.

children.name: type
children.description:
Bandwidth type.  By default, the bandwidth type
is set to 'bw-per-cos'.

Identifier of the CoS, indicated by DSCP or a
CE-VLAN CoS (802.1p) value in the service frame.

children.description:
Identifies the target VPN.  If the bandwidth
type is set as bandwidth per VPN service, the
vpn-id MUST be specified.

children.description:
Committed Information Rate.  The maximum number
of bits that a port can receive or send over
an interface in one second.

children.name: cbs
children.description:
Committed Burst Size (CBS).  Controls the bursty
nature of the traffic.  Traffic that does not
use the configured Committed Information Rate
(CIR) accumulates credits until the credits
reach the configured CBS.

children.name: eir
children.description:
Excess Information Rate (EIR), i.e., excess frame
delivery allowed that is not subject to an SLA.
The traffic rate can be limited by the EIR.

children.name: ebs
children.description:
Excess Burst Size (EBS).  The bandwidth available
for burst traffic from the EBS is subject to the
amount of bandwidth that is accumulated during
periods when traffic allocated by the EIR
policy is not used.

children.name: pir
children.description:
Peak Information Rate, i.e., maximum frame
delivery allowed.  It is equal to or less
than the sum of the CIR and the EIR.

children.name: pbs
children.description:
Peak Burst Size.  It is measured in bytes per
second.

children.name: svc-mtu
children.description:
SVC MTU.  It is also known as the maximum
transmission unit or maximum frame size.  When
a frame is larger than the MTU, it is broken
down, or fragmented, into smaller pieces by
the network protocol to accommodate the MTU
of the network.  If CsC is enabled,
the requested svc-mtu leaf will refer to the
MPLS MTU and not to the link MTU.

children.description: List of MAC addresses.

children.name: mac-address
children.description: MAC addresses.

children.name: mac-addr-limit
children.description: Container of MAC address limit configurations.

children.name: limit-number
children.description:
Maximum number of MAC addresses learned from
the subscriber for a single service instance.
The default allowed maximum number of MAC
addresses is 2.

children.name: time-interval
children.description:
The aging time of the MAC address.  By default,
the aging time is set to 300 seconds.

children.name: action
children.description:
Specifies the action taken when the upper limit is
exceeded: drop the packet, flood the packet, or
simply send a warning log message.  By default,
the action is set to 'warning'.

modules.name: ietf-l3-unicast-topology-state
modules.description:
This module defines a model for Layer 3 Unicast topology
state, representing topology that either is learned or
results from applying topology that has been configured per
the 'ietf-l3-unicast-topology' model, mirroring the
corresponding data nodes in this model.

This model mirrors 'ietf-l3-unicast-topology' but contains only
read-only state data.  The model is not needed when the
underlying implementation infrastructure supports the Network
Management Datastore Architecture (NMDA).

Copyright (c) 2018 IETF Trust and the persons identified as
authors of the code.  All rights reserved.

Redistribution and use in source and binary forms, with or
without modification, is permitted pursuant to, and subject
to the license terms contained in, the Simplified BSD License
set forth in Section 4.c of the IETF Trust's Legal Provisions
Relating to IETF Documents
(https://trustee.ietf.org/license-info).

This version of this YANG module is part of RFC 8346;
see the RFC itself for full legal notices.
