children.name: l3vpn-svc
children.description: Main container for L3VPN service configuration.

children.name: vpn-profiles
children.description: Container for VPN Profiles.

children.name: valid-provider-identifiers
children.description: Container for Valid Provider Identifies.

children.name: cloud-identifier
children.description: List for Cloud Identifiers.

children.name: id
children.description:
Identification of cloud service.
Local administration meaning.

children.name: encryption-profile-identifier
children.description: List for encryption profile identifiers.

children.name: id
children.description:
Identification of the SP encryption profile
to be used.  Local administration meaning.

children.name: qos-profile-identifier
children.description: List for QoS Profile Identifiers.

children.name: id
children.description:
Identification of the QoS Profile to be used.
Local administration meaning.

children.name: bfd-profile-identifier
children.description: List for BFD Profile identifiers.

children.name: id
children.description:
Identification of the SP BFD Profile to be used.
Local administration meaning.

children.name: vpn-services
children.description: Top-level container for the VPN services.

children.name: vpn-service
children.description: List of VPN services.

children.name: vpn-id
children.description: VPN identifier.  Local administration meaning.

children.name: customer-name
children.description:
Name of the customer that actually uses the VPN service.
In the case that any intermediary (e.g., Tier-2 provider
or partner) sells the VPN service to their end user
on behalf of the original service provider (e.g., Tier-1
provider), the original service provider may require the
customer name to provide smooth activation/commissioning
and operation for the service.

children.name: vpn-service-topology
children.description: VPN service topology.

children.name: cloud-accesses
children.description: Container for cloud access configurations.

children.name: cloud-access
children.description: Cloud access configuration.

children.name: cloud-identifier
children.description:
Identification of cloud service.
Local administration meaning.

children.name: list-flavor
children.description:
Choice for cloud access policy.  By
default, all sites in the IP VPN MUST
be authorized to access the cloud.

children.name: permit-any
children.description: Allows all sites.

children.name: permit-site
children.description: Site ID to be authorized.

children.name: deny-site
children.description: Site ID to be denied.

children.name: address-translation
children.description: Container for NAT.

children.name: nat44
children.description: IPv4-to-IPv4 translation.

children.name: enabled
children.description:
Controls whether or not Network address
translation from IPv4 to IPv4 (NAT44)
[RFC3022] is required.

children.name: nat44-customer-address
children.description:
Address to be used for network address
translation from IPv4 to IPv4.  This is
to be used if the customer is providing
the IPv4 address.  If the customer address
is not set, the model assumes that the
provider will allocate the address.

children.name: multicast
children.description: Multicast global parameters for the VPN service.

children.name: enabled
children.description: Enables multicast.

children.name: customer-tree-flavors
children.description: Type of trees used by customer.

children.name: tree-flavor
children.description: Type of tree to be used.

children.name: rp
children.description: RP parameters.

children.name: rp-group-mappings
children.description: RP-to-group mappings parameters.

children.name: rp-group-mapping
children.description: List of RP-to-group mappings.

children.name: id
children.description: Unique identifier for the mapping.

children.name: provider-managed
children.description: Parameters for a provider-managed RP.

children.name: enabled
children.description:
Set to true if the Rendezvous Point (RP)
must be a provider-managed node.  Set to false
if it is a customer-managed node.

children.name: rp-redundancy
children.description:
If true, a redundancy mechanism for the RP
is required.

children.name: optimal-traffic-delivery
children.description:
If true, the SP must ensure that
traffic uses an optimal path.  An SP may use
Anycast RP or RP-tree-to-SPT switchover
architectures.

children.name: rp-address
children.description:
Defines the address of the RP.
Used if the RP is customer-managed.

children.name: groups
children.description: Multicast groups associated with the RP.

children.name: group
children.description: List of multicast groups.

children.name: id
children.description: Identifier for the group.

children.name: group-format
children.description: Choice for multicast group format.

children.name: group-address
children.description: A single multicast group address.

children.name: group-start
children.description:
The first multicast group address in
the multicast group address range.

children.name: group-end
children.description:
The last multicast group address in
the multicast group address range.

children.name: rp-discovery
children.description: RP discovery parameters.

children.name: rp-discovery-type
children.description: Type of RP discovery used.

children.name: bsr-candidates
children.description:
Container for List of Customer
BSR candidate's addresses.

children.name: bsr-candidate-address
children.description: Address of BSR candidate.

children.name: carrierscarrier
children.description: The VPN is using CsC, and so MPLS is required.

children.name: extranet-vpns
children.description: Container for extranet VPN configuration.

children.name: extranet-vpn
children.description:
List of extranet VPNs or target VPNs the local VPN is
attached to.

children.name: vpn-id
children.description: Identifies the target VPN the local VPN want to access.

children.name: local-sites-role
children.description:
This describes the role of the
local sites in the target VPN topology.  In the any-to-any VPN
service topology, the local sites must have the same role, which
will be 'any-to-any-role'.  In the Hub-and-Spoke VPN service
topology or the Hub-and-Spoke disjoint VPN service topology,
the local sites must have a Hub role or a Spoke role.

children.name: sites
children.description: Container for sites.

children.name: site
children.description: List of sites.

children.name: site-id
children.description: Identifier of the site.

children.name: requested-site-start
children.description:
Optional leaf indicating requested date and
time when the service at a particular site is
expected to start.

children.name: requested-site-stop
children.description:
Optional leaf indicating requested date and
time when the service at a particular site is
expected to stop.

children.name: locations
children.description: List of locations for the site.

children.name: location
children.description: Location of the site.

children.name: location-id
children.description: Identifier for a particular location.

children.name: address
children.description: Address (number and street) of the site.

children.name: postal-code
children.description: Postal code of the site.

children.name: state
children.description:
State of the site.  This leaf can also be
used to describe a region for a country that
does not have states.

children.name: city
children.description: City of the site.

children.name: country-code
children.description:
Country of the site.
Expressed as ISO ALPHA-2 code.

children.name: devices
children.description: Device configuration.

children.name: device
children.description: List of devices requested by customer.

children.name: device-id
children.description: Identifier for the device.

children.name: location
children.description: Location of the device.

children.name: management
children.description:
Management configuration.  Applicable only for
co-managed device.

children.name: address-family
children.description: Address family used for management.

children.name: address
children.description: Management address.

children.name: site-diversity
children.description:
Diversity constraint type.  All
site-network-accesses will inherit
the group values defined here.

children.name: groups
children.description: Groups the site or site-network-access belongs to.

children.name: group
children.description: List of group-ids.

children.name: group-id
children.description: Group-id the site belongs to.

children.name: management
children.description: Management configuration.

children.name: type
children.description: Management type of the connection.

children.name: vpn-policies
children.description: VPN policy.

children.name: vpn-policy
children.description: List of VPN policies.

children.name: vpn-policy-id
children.description: Unique identifier for the VPN policy.

children.name: entries
children.description: List of entries for export policy.

children.name: id
children.description: Unique identifier for the policy entry.

children.name: filters
children.description:
If a more-granular VPN attachment is necessary, filtering can
be used.  If used, it permits the splitting of site LANs among
multiple VPNs.  The Site LAN can be split based on either LAN
Tag or LAN prefix.  If no filter is used, all the LANs will be
part of the same VPNs with the same role.

children.name: filter
children.description:
List of filters used on the site.  This list can
be augmented.

children.name: type
children.description: Type of VPN Policy filter.

children.name: lan-tag
children.description:
List of 'lan-tag' items to be matched.  LAN Tag
is an Internal tag to be used in VPN policies

children.name: ipv4-lan-prefix
children.description: List of IPv4 prefixes as LAN Prefixes to be matched.

children.name: ipv6-lan-prefix
children.description: List of IPv6 prefixes as LAN prefixes to be matched.

children.name: vpn
children.description: List of VPNs the LAN is associated with.

children.name: vpn-id
children.description: Reference to an IP VPN.

children.name: site-role
children.description: Role of the site in the IP VPN.

children.name: site-vpn-flavor
children.description:
Defines the way the VPN multiplexing is done, e.g., whether
the site belongs to a single VPN site or a multiVPN; or, in the case
of a multiVPN, whether the logical accesses of the sites belong
to the same set of VPNs or each logical access maps to
different VPNs.

children.name: maximum-routes
children.description: Defines 'maximum-routes' for the VRF.

children.name: address-family
children.description: List of address families.

children.name: af
children.description: Address family.

children.name: maximum-routes
children.description:
Maximum prefixes the VRF can accept
for this address family.

children.name: security
children.description: Site-specific security parameters.

children.name: authentication
children.description: Authentication parameters.

children.name: encryption
children.description: Encryption parameters.

children.name: enabled
children.description: If true, traffic encryption on the connection is required.

children.name: layer
children.description: Layer on which encryption is applied.

children.name: encryption-profile
children.description: Profile of encryption to be applied.

children.name: profile
children.description:
Choice of encryption profile.  The encryption
profile can be the provider profile or customer profile.

children.name: profile-name
children.description: Name of the SP profile to be applied.

children.name: algorithm
children.description: Encryption algorithm to be used.

children.name: key-type
children.description: Type of keys to be used.

children.name: preshared-key
children.description: Pre-Shared Key (PSK) coming from the customer.

children.name: service
children.description: Service parameters on the attachment.

children.name: qos
children.description: QoS configuration.

children.name: qos-classification-policy
children.description: Configuration of the traffic classification policy.

children.name: rule
children.description: List of marking rules.

children.name: id
children.description:
A description identifying the
qos-classification-policy rule.

children.name: match-type
children.description: Choice for classification.

children.name: match-flow
children.description: Describes flow-matching criteria.

children.name: dscp
children.description: DSCP value.

children.name: dot1p
children.description: 802.1p matching.

children.name: ipv4-src-prefix
children.description: Match on IPv4 src address.

children.name: ipv6-src-prefix
children.description: Match on IPv6 src address.

children.name: ipv4-dst-prefix
children.description: Match on IPv4 dst address.

children.name: ipv6-dst-prefix
children.description: Match on IPv6 dst address.

children.name: l4-src-port
children.description: Match on Layer 4 src port.

children.name: target-sites
children.description: Identify a site as traffic destination.

children.name: l4-src-port-range
children.description:
Match on Layer 4 src port range.  When
only the lower-port is present, it represents
a single port.  When both the lower-port and
upper-port are specified, it implies
a range inclusive of both values.

children.name: lower-port
children.description: Lower boundary for port.

children.name: upper-port
children.description: Upper boundary for port.

children.name: l4-dst-port
children.description: Match on Layer 4 dst port.

children.name: l4-dst-port-range
children.description:
Match on Layer 4 dst port range.  When only
lower-port is present, it represents a single
port.  When both lower-port and upper-port are
specified, it implies a range inclusive of both
values.

children.name: lower-port
children.description: Lower boundary for port.

children.name: upper-port
children.description:
Upper boundary for port.  If it exists,
upper boundary must be higher than lower
boundary.

children.name: protocol-field
children.description: Match on IPv4 protocol or IPv6 Next Header field.

children.name: match-application
children.description: Defines the application to match.

children.name: target-class-id
children.description:
Identification of the class of service.
This identifier is internal to the administration.

children.name: qos-profile
children.description: QoS profile configuration.

children.name: qos-profile
children.description:
Choice for QoS profile.
Can be standard profile or customized profile.

children.name: standard
children.description: Standard QoS profile.

children.name: profile
children.description: QoS profile to be used.

children.name: custom
children.description: Customized QoS profile.

children.name: classes
children.description: Container for list of classes of services.

children.name: class

This module defines typedefs and groupings but no schema
tree elements.

modules.name: ietf-lmap-control
modules.description:
This module defines a data model for controlling Measurement
Agents that are part of a Large-Scale Measurement Platform
(LMAP).  This data model is expected to be implemented by
Measurement Agents.

Working Group

          <j.schoenwaelder@jacobs-university.de>

children.name: program
children.description:
The (local) program to invoke in order to execute
the Task.

children.name: agent
children.description:
Configuration of parameters affecting the whole
Measurement Agent.

children.name: agent-id
children.description:
The agent-id identifies a Measurement Agent with
a very low probability of collision.  In certain
deployments, the agent-id may be considered
sensitive, and hence this object is optional.

children.name: group-id
children.description:
The group-id identifies a group of Measurement
Agents.  In certain deployments, the group-id
may be considered less sensitive than the
agent-id.

children.name: measurement-point
children.description:
The measurement point indicating where the
 Measurement Agent is located on a path.
children.reference:
RFC 7398: A Reference Path and Measurement Points
          for Large-Scale Measurement of Broadband
          Performance

children.name: report-agent-id
children.description:
The 'report-agent-id' controls whether the
'agent-id' is reported to Collectors.

children.name: report-group-id
children.description:
The 'report-group-id' controls whether the
'group-id' is reported to Collectors.

children.name: report-measurement-point
children.description:
The 'report-measurement-point' controls whether
the 'measurement-point' is reported to Collectors.

children.name: controller-timeout
children.description:
A timer is started after each successful contact
with a Controller.  When the timer reaches the
controller-timeout, an event (controller-lost) is
raised indicating that connectivity to the Controller
has been lost.

children.name: last-started
children.description: The date and time the Measurement Agent last started.

children.name: tasks
children.description: Configuration of LMAP Tasks.

children.name: task
children.description:
The list of Tasks configured on the Measurement
Agent.  Note that a configured Task MUST resolve to a
Task listed in the capabilities.  Attempts to execute
a configured Task that is not listed in the capabilities
result in a runtime execution error.

children.name: name
children.description: The unique name of a Task.

children.name: function
children.description: A list of entries in a registry identifying functions.

children.name: uri
children.description: A URI identifying an entry in a registry.

children.name: role
children.description: A set of roles for the identified registry entry.

children.name: program
children.description:
The (local) program to invoke in order to execute
the Task.  If this leaf is not set, then the system
will try to identify a suitable program based on
the registry information present.

children.name: option
children.description:
A list of options passed to the Task.  It is a list of
key/value pairs and may be used to model options.
Options may be used to identify the role of a Task
or to pass a Channel name to a Task.

children.name: id
children.description:
An identifier uniquely identifying an option.  This
identifier is required by YANG to uniquely identify
a name/value pair, but it otherwise has no semantic
value

children.name: name
children.description: The name of the option.

children.name: value
children.description: The value of the option.

children.name: tag
children.description:
A set of Task-specific tags that are reported
together with the measurement results to a Collector.
A tag can be used, for example, to carry the
Measurement Cycle ID.

children.name: schedules
children.description:
Configuration of LMAP Schedules.  Schedules control
which Tasks are executed by the LMAP implementation.

children.name: schedule
children.description: Configuration of a particular Schedule.

children.name: name
children.description:
The locally unique, administratively assigned name
for this Schedule.

children.name: start
children.description:
The event source controlling the start of the
scheduled Actions.

children.name: stop
children.description:
This choice contains optional leafs that control the
graceful forced termination of scheduled Actions.
When the end has been reached, the scheduled Actions
should be forced to terminate the measurements.
This may involve being active some additional time in
order to properly finish the Action's activity (e.g.,
waiting for any messages that are still outstanding).

children.name: end
children.description:
The event source controlling the graceful
forced termination of the scheduled Actions.

children.name: duration
children.description:
The duration controlling the graceful forced
termination of the scheduled Actions.

children.name: execution-mode
children.description:
The execution mode of this Schedule determines in
which order the Actions of the Schedule are executed.

children.name: tag
children.description:
A set of Schedule-specific tags that are reported
together with the measurement results to a Collector.

children.name: suppression-tag
children.description:
A set of Suppression tags that are used to select
Schedules to be suppressed.

children.name: state
children.description: The current state of the Schedule.

children.name: storage
children.description:
The amount of secondary storage (e.g., allocated in a
file system) holding temporary data allocated to the
Schedule in bytes.  This object reports the amount of
allocated physical storage and not the storage used
by logical data records.

children.name: invocations
children.description:
Number of invocations of this Schedule.  This counter
does not include suppressed invocations or invocations
that were prevented due to an overlap with a previous
invocation of this Schedule.

children.name: suppressions
children.description: Number of suppressed executions of this Schedule.

children.name: overlaps
children.description:
Number of executions prevented due to overlaps with
a previous invocation of this Schedule.

children.name: failures
children.description:
Number of failed executions of this Schedule.  A
failed execution is an execution where at least
one Action failed.

children.name: last-invocation
children.description:
The date and time of the last invocation of
this Schedule.

children.name: action
children.description:
An Action describes a Task that is invoked by the
Schedule.  Multiple Actions are invoked according to
the execution-mode of the Schedule.

children.name: name
children.description: The unique identifier for this Action.

children.name: task
children.description: The Task invoked by this Action.

children.name: parameters
children.description:
This container is a placeholder for runtime
parameters defined in Task-specific data models
augmenting the base LMAP control data model.

children.name: extension
children.description:
This choice is provided to augment in different
sets of parameters.

children.name: option
children.description:
A list of options passed to the Task.  It is a list of
key/value pairs and may be used to model options.
Options may be used to identify the role of a Task
or to pass a Channel name to a Task.

children.name: id
children.description:
An identifier uniquely identifying an option.  This
identifier is required by YANG to uniquely identify
a name/value pair, but it otherwise has no semantic
value

children.name: name
children.description: The name of the option.

children.name: value
children.description: The value of the option.

children.name: destination
children.description:
A set of Schedules receiving the output produced
by this Action.  The output is stored temporarily
since the Destination Schedules will in general
not be running when output is passed to them.  The
behavior of an Action passing data to its own
Schedule is implementation specific.

Data passed to a sequential or pipelined Schedule
is received by the Schedule's first Action.  Data
passed to a parallel Schedule is received by all
Actions of the Schedule.

children.name: tag
children.description:
A set of Action-specific tags that are reported
together with the measurement results to a
Collector.

children.name: suppression-tag
children.description:
A set of Suppression tags that are used to select
Actions to be suppressed.

children.name: state
children.description: The current state of the Action.

children.name: storage
children.description:
The amount of secondary storage (e.g., allocated in a
file system) holding temporary data allocated to the
Schedule in bytes.  This object reports the amount of
allocated physical storage and not the storage used
by logical data records.

children.name: invocations
children.description:
Number of invocations of this Action.  This counter
does not include suppressed invocations or invocations
that were prevented due to an overlap with a previous
invocation of this Action.

children.name: suppressions
children.description: Number of suppressed executions of this Action.

children.name: overlaps
children.description:
Number of executions prevented due to overlaps with
a previous invocation of this Action.

children.name: failures
children.description: Number of failed executions of this Action.

children.name: last-invocation
children.description:
The date and time of the last invocation of
this Action.

children.name: last-completion
children.description:
The date and time of the last completion of
this Action.

children.name: last-status
children.description:
The status code returned by the last execution of
this Action.

children.name: last-message
children.description:
The status message produced by the last execution
of this Action.

children.name: last-failed-completion
children.description:
The date and time of the last failed completion
of this Action.

children.name: last-failed-status
children.description:
The status code returned by the last failed
execution of this Action.

children.name: last-failed-message
children.description:
The status message produced by the last failed
execution of this Action.

children.name: suppressions
children.description:
Suppression information to prevent Schedules or
certain Actions from starting.

children.name: suppression
children.description: Configuration of a particular Suppression.

children.name: name
children.description:
The locally unique, administratively assigned name
for this Suppression.

children.name: start
children.description:
The event source controlling the start of the
Suppression period.

children.name: end
children.description:
The event source controlling the end of the
Suppression period.  If not present, Suppression
continues indefinitely.

children.name: match
children.description:
A set of Suppression match patterns.  The Suppression
will apply to all Schedules (and their Actions) that
have a matching value in their suppression-tags
and to all Actions that have a matching value in
their suppression-tags.

children.name: stop-running
children.description:
If 'stop-running' is true, running Schedules and
Actions matching the Suppression will be terminated
when Suppression is activated.  If 'stop-running' is
false, running Schedules and Actions will not be
affected if Suppression is activated.

children.name: state
children.description: The current state of the Suppression.

children.name: events
children.description:
Configuration of LMAP events.

Implementations may be forced to delay acting
upon the occurrence of events in the face of local
constraints.  An Action triggered by an event
therefore should not rely on the accuracy
provided by the scheduler implementation.

children.name: event
children.description:
The list of event sources configured on the
Measurement Agent.

children.name: name
children.description: The unique name of an event source.

children.name: random-spread
children.description:
This optional leaf adds a random spread to the
computation of the event's trigger time.  The
random spread is a uniformly distributed random
number taken from the interval [0:random-spread].

children.name: cycle-interval
children.description:
The optional cycle-interval defines the duration
of the time interval in seconds that is used to
calculate cycle numbers.  No cycle number is
calculated if the optional cycle-interval does
not exist.

children.name: event-type
children.description:
Different types of events are handled by
different branches of this choice.  Note that
this choice can be extended via augmentations.

children.name: periodic
children.description:
A periodic timing object triggers periodically
according to a regular interval.

children.name: interval
children.description:
The number of seconds between two triggers
generated by this periodic timing object.

children.name: start
children.description:
The date and time when the Event object
starts to create triggers.

children.name: end
children.description:
The date and time when the Event object
stops to create triggers.

It is generally a good idea to always configure
an end time and to refresh the end time as needed
to ensure that agents that lose connectivity to
their Controller do not continue executing Schedules
forever.

children.name: calendar
children.description:
A calendar timing object triggers based on the
current calendar date and time.

children.name: month
children.description:
A set of months at which this calendar timing
will trigger.  The wildcard means all months.

children.name: day-of-month
children.description:
A set of days of the month at which this
calendar timing will trigger.  The wildcard means
all days of a month.

children.name: day-of-week
children.description:
A set of weekdays at which this calendar timing
will trigger.  The wildcard means all weekdays.

children.name: hour
children.description:
A set of hours at which this calendar timing will
trigger.  The wildcard means all hours of a day.

children.name: minute
children.description:
A set of minutes at which this calendar timing
will trigger.  The wildcard means all minutes of
an hour.

children.name: second
children.description:
A set of seconds at which this calendar timing
will trigger.  The wildcard means all seconds of
a minute.

children.name: timezone-offset
children.description:
The time zone in which this calendar timing
object will be evaluated.  If not present,
the system's local time zone will be used.

children.name: start
children.description:
The date and time when the Event object
starts to create triggers.

children.name: end
children.description:
The date and time when the Event object
stops to create triggers.

It is generally a good idea to always configure
an end time and to refresh the end time as needed
to ensure that agents that lose connectivity to
their Controller do not continue executing Schedules
forever.

children.name: one-off
children.description: A one-off timing object triggers exactly once.

children.name: time
children.description:
This one-off timing object triggers once at
the configured date and time.

children.name: immediate
children.description:
This immediate Event object triggers immediately
when it is configured.

children.name: startup
children.description:
This startup Event object triggers whenever the
Measurement Agent (re)starts.

children.name: controller-lost
children.description:
The controller-lost Event object triggers when
the connectivity to the Controller has been lost
for at least 'controller-timeout' seconds.

children.name: controller-connected
children.description:
The controller-connected Event object triggers
when the connectivity to the Controller has been
restored after it was lost for at least
'controller-timeout' seconds.

modules.name: ietf-lmap-report
modules.description:
This module defines a data model for reporting results from
Measurement Agents, which are part of a Large-Scale Measurement
Platform (LMAP), to result data Collectors.  This data model is
expected to be implemented by a Collector.
modules.organization:
IETF Large-Scale Measurement of Broadband Performance
Working Group
modules.contact:
WG Web:   <https://datatracker.ietf.org/wg/lmap>
WG List:  <mailto:lmap@ietf.org>

Editor:   Juergen Schoenwaelder
          <j.schoenwaelder@jacobs-university.de>

Editor:   Vaibhav Bajpai
          <bajpaiv@in.tum.de>

children.name: report
children.description:
The report operation is used by a Measurement Agent to
submit measurement results produced by Measurement Tasks to
a Collector.

children.name: date
children.description:
The date and time when this result report was sent to
a Collector.

children.name: agent-id
children.description:
The agent-id of the agent from which this
report originates.

children.name: group-id
children.description:
The group-id of the agent from which this
report originates.

children.name: measurement-point
children.description:
The measurement-point of the agent from which this
report originates.

children.name: result
children.description: The list of Tasks for which results are reported.

children.name: schedule
children.description: The name of the Schedule that produced the result.

children.name: action
children.description:
The name of the Action in the Schedule that produced
the result.

children.name: task
children.description: The name of the Task that produced the result.

children.name: parameters
children.description:
This container is a placeholder for runtime
parameters defined in Task-specific data models
augmenting the base LMAP report data model.

children.name: extension
children.description:
This choice is provided to augment in different
sets of parameters.

children.name: option
children.description:
A list of options passed to the Task.  It is a list of
key/value pairs and may be used to model options.
Options may be used to identify the role of a Task
or to pass a Channel name to a Task.

children.name: id
children.description:
An identifier uniquely identifying an option.  This
identifier is required by YANG to uniquely identify
a name/value pair, but it otherwise has no semantic
value

children.name: name
children.description: The name of the option.

children.name: value
children.description: The value of the option.

children.name: tag
children.description:
A tag contains additional information that is passed
with the result record to the Collector.  This is the
joined set of tags defined for the Task object, the
Schedule object, and the Action object.  A tag can be
used to carry the Measurement Cycle ID.

children.name: event
children.description:
The date and time of the event that triggered the
Schedule of the Action that produced the reported
result values.  The date and time does not include
any added randomization.

children.name: start
children.description:
The date and time when the Task producing
this result started.

children.name: end
children.description:
The date and time when the Task producing
this result finished.

children.name: cycle-number
children.description:
The optional cycle number is the time closest to
the time reported in the event leaf that is a multiple
of the cycle-interval of the event that triggered the
execution of the Schedule.  The value is only present
if the event that triggered the execution of the
Schedule has a defined cycle-interval.

children.name: status
children.description:
The status code returned by the execution of this
Action.

children.name: conflict
children.description:
The names of Tasks overlapping with the execution
of the Task that has produced this result.

children.name: schedule-name
children.description:
The name of a Schedule that might have impacted
the execution of the Task that has produced this
result.

children.name: action-name
children.description:
The name of an Action within the Schedule that
might have impacted the execution of the Task that
has produced this result.

children.name: task-name
children.description:
The name of the Task executed by an Action within
the Schedule that might have impacted the execution
of the Task that has produced this result.

children.name: table
children.description: A list of result tables.

children.name: function
children.description: A list of entries in a registry identifying functions.

children.name: uri
children.description: A URI identifying an entry in a registry.

children.name: role
children.description: A set of roles for the identified registry entry.

children.name: column
children.description:
An ordered list of column labels.  The order is
determined by the system and must match the order
of the columns in the result rows.

children.name: row
children.description: The rows of a result table.

children.name: value
children.description: The value of a cell in the result row.

children.name: logical-network-elements
children.description:
Allows a network device to support multiple logical
network element (device) instances.

children.name: logical-network-element
children.description: List of logical network elements.

children.name: name
children.description:
Device-wide unique identifier for the
logical network element.

children.name: managed
children.description:
True if the host can access LNE information
using the root mount point.  This value
may not be modifiable in all implementations.

children.name: description
children.description: Description of the logical network element.

children.name: root
children.description: Container for mount point.

children.name: bind-lne-name-failed
children.description:
Indicates an error in the association of an interface to an
LNE.  Only generated after success is initially returned
when bind-lne-name is set.

children.name: name
children.description:
Contains the interface name associated with the
failure.

children.name: bind-lne-name
children.description:
Contains the bind-lne-name associated with the
failure.

children.name: error-info
children.description:
Optionally, indicates the source of the assignment
failure.

modules.name: ietf-mud
modules.description:
This YANG module defines a component that augments the
IETF description of an access list.  This specific module
focuses on additional filters that include local, model,
and same-manufacturer.

This module is intended to be serialized via JSON and stored
as a file, as described in RFC 8520.

Copyright (c) 2019 IETF Trust and the persons identified as
authors of the code.  All rights reserved.

Redistribution and use in source and binary forms, with or
without modification, is permitted pursuant to, and subject
to the license terms contained in, the Simplified BSD License
set forth in Section 4.c of the IETF Trust's Legal Provisions
Relating to IETF Documents
(http://trustee.ietf.org/license-info).

This version of this YANG module is part of RFC 8520; see
the RFC itself for full legal notices.
modules.organization: IETF OPSAWG (Operations and Management Area Working Group)
modules.contact:
WG Web: <https://datatracker.ietf.org/wg/opsawg/>
WG List: opsawg&ietf.org

Author: Eliot Lear
        lear@cisco.com

Author: Ralph Droms
        rdroms@gmail.com

Author: Dan Romascanu
        dromasca@gmail.com

children.name: mud
children.description:
MUD-related information, as specified
by RFC 8520.

children.name: mud-version
children.description:
This is the version of the MUD
specification.  This memo specifies version 1.

children.name: mud-url
children.description:
This is the MUD URL associated with the entry found
in a MUD file.

children.name: last-update
children.description:
This is intended to be when the current MUD file
was generated.  MUD managers SHOULD NOT check
for updates between this time plus cache validity.

children.name: mud-signature
children.description:
A URI that resolves to a signature as
described in this specification.

children.name: cache-validity
children.description:
The information retrieved from the MUD server is
valid for these many hours, after which it should
be refreshed.  N.B., MUD manager implementations
need not discard MUD files beyond this period.

children.name: is-supported
children.description:
This boolean indicates whether or not the Thing is
currently supported by the manufacturer.

children.name: systeminfo
children.description:
A UTF-8 description of this Thing.  This
should be a brief description that may be
displayed to the user to determine whether
to allow the Thing on the
network.

children.name: mfg-name
children.description:
Manufacturer name, as described in
the ietf-hardware YANG module.

children.name: model-name
children.description:
Model name, as described in the
ietf-hardware YANG module.

children.name: firmware-rev
children.description:
firmware-rev, as described in the
ietf-hardware YANG module.  Note that this field
MUST NOT be included when the device can be
updated but the MUD URL cannot.

children.name: software-rev
children.description:
software-rev, as described in the
ietf-hardware YANG module.  Note that this field
MUST NOT be included when the device can be
updated but the MUD URL cannot.

children.name: documentation
children.description:
This URL points to documentation that
relates to this device and any classes that it uses
in its MUD file.  A caution: MUD managers need
not resolve this URL on their own but rather simply
provide it to the administrator.  Parsing HTML is
not an intended function of a MUD manager.

children.name: extensions
children.description:
A list of extension names that are used in this MUD
file.  Each name is registered with the IANA and
described in an RFC.

children.name: from-device-policy
children.description:
The policies that should be enforced on traffic
coming from the device.  These policies are not
necessarily intended to be enforced at a single
point but may be rendered by the controller to any
relevant enforcement points in the network or
elsewhere.

children.name: access-lists
children.description:
The access lists that should be applied to traffic
to or from the device.

children.name: access-list
children.description:
Each entry on this list refers to an ACL that
should be present in the overall access list
data model.  Each ACL is identified by name and
type.

children.name: name
children.description: The name of the ACL for this entry.

children.name: to-device-policy
children.description:
The policies that should be enforced on traffic
going to the device.  These policies are not
necessarily intended to be enforced at a single
point but may be rendered by the controller to any
relevant enforcement points in the network or
elsewhere.

children.name: access-lists
children.description:
The access lists that should be applied to traffic
to or from the device.

children.name: access-list
children.description:
Each entry on this list refers to an ACL that
should be present in the overall access list
data model.  Each ACL is identified by name and
type.

children.name: name
children.description: The name of the ACL for this entry.

modules.name: ietf-nat
modules.description:
This module is a YANG module for NAT implementations.

NAT44, Network Address and Protocol Translation from IPv6
Clients to IPv4 Servers (NAT64), customer-side translator
(CLAT), Stateless IP/ICMP Translation (SIIT), Explicit
Address Mappings (EAM) for SIIT, IPv6 Network Prefix
Translation (NPTv6), and Destination NAT are covered.

Copyright (c) 2018 IETF Trust and the persons identified as
authors of the code.  All rights reserved.

Redistribution and use in source and binary forms, with or
without modification, is permitted pursuant to, and subject
to the license terms contained in, the Simplified BSD License
set forth in Section 4.c of the IETF Trust's Legal Provisions
Relating to IETF Documents
(http://trustee.ietf.org/license-info).

This version of this YANG module is part of RFC 8512; see
the RFC itself for full legal notices.

modules.contact:
