WG List:  <mailto:opsawg@ietf.org>

Editor:  Mohamed Boucadair
         <mailto:mohamed.boucadair@orange.com>

Author:  Senthil Sivakumar
         <mailto:ssenthil@cisco.com>

Author:  Christian Jacquenet
         <mailto:christian.jacquenet@orange.com>

Author:  Suresh Vinapamula
         <mailto:sureshk@juniper.net>

Author:  Qin Wu
         <mailto:bill.wu@huawei.com>

children.name: nat
children.description: NAT module

children.name: instances
children.description: NAT instances

children.name: instance
children.description:
A NAT instance.  This identifier can be automatically
assigned or explicitly configured.

children.name: id
children.description:
NAT instance identifier.

The identifier must be greater than zero.
children.reference:
RFC 7659: Definitions of Managed Objects for Network
          Address Translators (NATs)

children.name: name
children.description: A name associated with the NAT instance.
children.reference:
RFC 7659: Definitions of Managed Objects for Network
          Address Translators (NATs)

children.name: enable
children.description: Status of the NAT instance.

children.name: capabilities
children.description: NAT capabilities.

children.name: nat-flavor
children.description: Supported translation type(s).

children.name: per-interface-binding
children.description:
Indicates the capability of a NAT to associate a
particular NAT session not only with the five
tuples used for the transport connection on both
sides of the NAT but also with the internal
interface on which the user device is
connected to the NAT.
children.reference: Section 4 of RFC 6619

children.name: transport-protocols
children.description: List of supported protocols.

children.name: protocol-id
children.description:
The upper-layer protocol associated with a mapping.

Values are taken from the IANA Protocol Numbers
registry.

For example, this field contains 6 for TCP,
17 for UDP, 33 for DCCP, or 132 for SCTP.

children.name: protocol-name
children.description:
The name of the upper-layer protocol associated
with this mapping.

For example, TCP, UDP, DCCP, and SCTP.

children.name: restricted-port-support
children.description: Indicates source port NAT restriction support.
children.reference:
RFC 7596: Lightweight 4over6: An Extension to
          the Dual-Stack Lite Architecture

children.name: static-mapping-support
children.description: Indicates whether static mappings are supported.

children.name: port-randomization-support
children.description: Indicates whether port randomization is supported.
children.reference: Section 4.2.1 of RFC 4787

children.name: port-range-allocation-support
children.description: Indicates whether port range allocation is supported.
children.reference: Section 1.1 of RFC 7753

children.name: port-preservation-suport
children.description: Indicates whether port preservation is supported.
children.reference: Section 4.2.1 of RFC 4787

children.name: port-parity-preservation-support
children.description:
Indicates whether port parity preservation is
supported.
children.reference: Section 8 of RFC 7857

children.name: address-roundrobin-support
children.description:
Indicates whether address allocation round robin is
supported.

children.name: paired-address-pooling-support
children.description:
Indicates whether paired-address-pooling is
supported
children.reference: REQ-2 of RFC 4787

children.name: endpoint-independent-mapping-support
children.description:
Indicates whether endpoint-independent-
mapping is supported.
children.reference: Section 4 of RFC 4787

children.name: address-dependent-mapping-support
children.description:
Indicates whether address-dependent-mapping is
supported.
children.reference: Section 4 of RFC 4787

children.name: address-and-port-dependent-mapping-support
children.description:
Indicates whether address-and-port-dependent-mapping is
supported.
children.reference: Section 4 of RFC 4787

children.name: endpoint-independent-filtering-support
children.description:
Indicates whether endpoint-independent-filtering is
supported.
children.reference: Section 5 of RFC 4787

children.name: address-dependent-filtering
children.description:
Indicates whether address-dependent-filtering is
supported.
children.reference: Section 5 of RFC 4787

children.name: address-and-port-dependent-filtering
children.description:
Indicates whether address-and-port-dependent is
supported.
children.reference: Section 5 of RFC 4787

children.name: fragment-behavior
children.description:
The fragment behavior is the NAT instance's capability to
translate fragments received on the external interface of
the NAT.

children.name: type
children.description:
Specify the translation type.  Particularly useful when
multiple translation flavors are supported.

If one type is supported by a NAT, this parameter is by
default set to that type.

children.name: per-interface-binding
children.description:
A NAT that associates a particular NAT session not
only with the five tuples used for the transport
connection on both sides of the NAT but also with
the internal interface on which the user device is
connected to the NAT.

If supported, this mode of operation should be
configurable, and it should be disabled by default in
general-purpose NAT devices.
If one single per-interface binding behavior is
supported by a NAT, this parameter is by default set to
that behavior.
children.reference: Section 4 of RFC 6619

children.name: nat-pass-through
children.description: IP prefix NAT pass-through.

children.name: id
children.description: An identifier of the IP prefix pass-through.

children.name: prefix
children.description:
The IP addresses that match should not be translated.

It must be possible to administratively turn
off translation for specific destination addresses
and/or ports.
children.reference: REQ-6 of RFC 6888

children.name: port
children.description:
It must be possible to administratively turn off
translation for specific destination addresses
and/or ports.

If no prefix is defined, the NAT pass-through bound
to a given port applies for any destination address.
children.reference: REQ-6 of RFC 6888

children.name: policy
children.description: NAT parameters for a given instance

children.name: id
children.description:
An identifier of the NAT policy.  It must be unique
within the NAT instance.

children.name: clat-parameters
children.description: CLAT parameters.

children.name: clat-ipv6-prefixes
children.description:
464XLAT double-translation treatment is stateless
when a dedicated /64 is available for translation
on the CLAT.  Otherwise, the CLAT will have both
stateful and stateless translation since it requires
NAT44 from the LAN to a single IPv4 address and then
stateless translation to a single IPv6 address.
children.reference:
RFC 6877: 464XLAT: Combination of Stateful and
          Stateless Translation

children.name: ipv6-prefix
children.description: An IPv6 prefix used for CLAT.

children.name: ipv4-prefixes
children.description:
Pool of IPv4 addresses used for CLAT.
192.0.0.0/29 is the IPv4 service continuity prefix.
children.reference: RFC 7335: IPv4 Service Continuity Prefix

children.name: ipv4-prefix
children.description:
464XLAT double-translation treatment is
stateless when a dedicated /64 is available
for translation on the CLAT.  Otherwise, the
CLAT will have both stateful and stateless
translation since it requires NAT44 from the
LAN to a single IPv4 address and then stateless
translation to a single IPv6 address.
The CLAT performs NAT44 for all IPv4 LAN
packets so that all the LAN-originated IPv4
packets appear from a single IPv4 address
and are then statelessly translated to one
interface IPv6 address that is claimed by
the CLAT.

An IPv4 address from this pool is also
provided to an application that makes
use of literals.
children.reference:
RFC 6877: 464XLAT: Combination of Stateful and
          Stateless Translation

children.name: nptv6-prefixes
children.description:
Provides one or a list of (internal IPv6 prefix,
external IPv6 prefix) required for NPTv6.

In its simplest form, NPTv6 interconnects two
network links: one is an 'internal' network
link attached to a leaf network within a single
administrative domain, and the other is an
'external' network with connectivity to the
global Internet.
children.reference: RFC 6296: IPv6-to-IPv6 Network Prefix Translation

children.name: internal-ipv6-prefix
children.description:
An IPv6 prefix used by an internal interface of
NPTv6.
children.reference: RFC 6296: IPv6-to-IPv6 Network Prefix Translation

children.name: external-ipv6-prefix
children.description:
An IPv6 prefix used by the external interface of
NPTv6.
children.reference: RFC 6296: IPv6-to-IPv6 Network Prefix Translation

children.name: eam
children.description:
The Explicit Address Mapping Table is a conceptual
table in which each row represents an EAM.

Each EAM describes a mapping between IPv4 and IPv6
prefixes/addresses.
children.reference: Section 3.1 of RFC 7757

children.name: ipv4-prefix
children.description: The IPv4 prefix of an EAM.
children.reference: Section 3.2 of RFC 7757

children.name: ipv6-prefix
children.description: The IPv6 prefix of an EAM.
children.reference: Section 3.2 of RFC 7757

children.name: nat64-prefixes
children.description:
Provides one or a list of NAT64 prefixes
with or without a list of destination IPv4 prefixes.
It allows mapping IPv4 address ranges to IPv6 prefixes.
For example:
192.0.2.0/24 is mapped to 2001:db8:122:300::/56.
198.51.100.0/24 is mapped to 2001:db8:122::/48.
children.reference: Section 5.1 of RFC 7050

children.name: nat64-prefix
children.description:
A NAT64 prefix.  Can be a Network-Specific Prefix (NSP)
or a Well-Known Prefix (WKP).

Organizations deploying stateless IPv4/IPv6 translation
should assign an NSP to their IPv4/IPv6 translation
service.

For stateless NAT64, IPv4-translatable IPv6 addresses
must use the selected NSP.

Both IPv4-translatable IPv6 addresses and
IPv4-converted IPv6 addresses should use
the same prefix.
children.reference: Sections 3.3 and 3.4 of RFC 6052

children.name: destination-ipv4-prefix
children.description: An IPv4 prefix/address.

children.name: ipv4-prefix
children.description: An IPv4 address/prefix.

children.name: stateless-enable
children.description: Enable explicitly stateless NAT64.

children.name: external-ip-address-pool
children.description:
Pool of external IP addresses used to service internal
hosts.

A pool is a set of IP prefixes.

children.name: pool-id
children.description:
An identifier that uniquely identifies the address pool
within a NAT instance.

The identifier must be greater than zero.
children.reference:
RFC 7659: Definitions of Managed Objects for
          Network Address Translators (NATs)

children.name: external-ip-pool
children.description: An IPv4 prefix used for NAT purposes.

children.name: port-set-restrict
children.description:
Configures contiguous and non-contiguous port ranges.

The port set is used to restrict the external source
port numbers used by the translator.

children.name: port-type
children.description: Port type: port-range or port-set-algo.
children.reference:
RFC 7597: Mapping of Address and Port with
          Encapsulation (MAP-E)

children.name: start-port-number
children.description: Beginning of the port range.
children.reference: Section 3.2.9 of RFC 8045

children.name: end-port-number
children.description: End of the port range.
children.reference: Section 3.2.10 of RFC 8045

children.name: psid-offset
children.description:
The number of offset bits (a.k.a., 'a' bits).

Specifies the numeric value for the excluded port
range/offset bits.

Allowed values are between 0 and 15.
children.reference: Section 5.1 of RFC 7597

children.name: psid-len
children.description:
The length of PSID, representing the sharing
ratio for an IPv4 address.

(also known as 'k').

The address-sharing ratio would be 2^k.
children.reference: Section 5.1 of RFC 7597

children.name: psid
children.description:
PSID value, which identifies a set
of ports algorithmically.
children.reference: Section 5.1 of RFC 7597

children.name: dst-nat-enable
children.description:
Enable/disable Destination NAT.

A NAT44 may be configured to enable Destination
NAT, too.

children.name: dst-ip-address-pool
children.description: Pool of IP addresses used for Destination NAT.

children.name: pool-id
children.description: An identifier of the address pool.

children.name: dst-in-ip-pool
children.description:
Is used to identify an internal destination
IP prefix/address to be translated.

children.name: dst-out-ip-pool
children.description: IP address/prefix used for Destination NAT.

children.name: transport-protocols
children.description:
Configure the transport protocols to be handled by
the translator.

TCP and UDP are supported by default.

children.name: protocol-id
children.description:
The upper-layer protocol associated with this
mapping.

Values are taken from the IANA Protocol Numbers
registry.

For example, this field contains 6 for TCP,
17 for UDP, 33 for DCCP, or 132 for SCTP.

children.name: protocol-name
children.description:
The name of the upper-layer protocol associated
with this mapping.

For example, TCP, UDP, DCCP, and SCTP.

children.name: subscriber-mask-v6
children.description:
The subscriber mask is an integer that indicates
the length of significant bits to be applied on
the source IPv6 address (internal side) to
unambiguously identify a user device (e.g., CPE).

Subscriber mask is a system-wide configuration
parameter that is used to enforce generic
per-subscriber policies (e.g., port-quota).

The enforcement of these generic policies does not
require the configuration of every subscriber's
prefix.

Example: suppose the 2001:db8:100:100::/56 prefix
is assigned to a NAT64-serviced CPE.  Suppose also
that 2001:db8:100:100::1 is the IPv6 address used
by the client that resides in that CPE.  When the
NAT64 receives a packet from this client,
it applies the subscriber-mask-v6 (e.g., 56) on
the source IPv6 address to compute the associated
prefix for this client (2001:db8:100:100::/56).
Then, the NAT64 enforces policies based on that
prefix (2001:db8:100:100::/56), not on the exact
source IPv6 address.

children.name: subscriber-match
children.description:
IP prefix match.
A subscriber is identified by a subnet.

children.name: match-id
children.description: An identifier of the subscriber match.

children.name: subnet
children.description:
The IP address subnets that match
should be translated.  For example, all addresses
that belong to the 192.0.2.0/24 prefix must
be processed by the NAT.

children.name: address-allocation-type
children.description: Specifies how external IP addresses are allocated.

children.name: port-allocation-type
children.description: Indicates the type of port allocation.

children.name: mapping-type
children.description: Indicates the type of NAT mapping.

children.name: filtering-type
children.description: Indicates the type of NAT filtering.

children.name: fragment-behavior
children.description:
The fragment behavior instructs the NAT about the
behavior to follow to translate fragments received
on the external interface of the NAT.

children.name: port-quota
children.description:
Configures a port quota to be assigned per subscriber.
It corresponds to the maximum number of ports to be
used by a subscriber.

children.name: port-limit
children.description:
Configures a port quota to be assigned per subscriber.
It corresponds to the maximum number of ports to be
used by a subscriber.
children.reference: REQ-4 of RFC 6888

children.name: quota-type
children.description:
Indicates whether the port quota applies to
all protocols (0) or to a specific protocol.

children.name: port-set
children.description: Manages port-set assignments.

children.name: port-set-size
children.description: Indicates the size of assigned port sets.

children.name: port-set-timeout
children.description: inactivity timeout for port sets.

children.name: timers
children.description: Configure values of various timeouts.

children.name: udp-timeout
children.description:
UDP inactivity timeout.  That is the time a mapping
will stay active without packets traversing the NAT.
children.reference:
RFC 4787: Network Address Translation (NAT)
          Behavioral Requirements for Unicast UDP

children.name: tcp-idle-timeout
children.description: TCP idle timeout should be 2 hours and 4 minutes.
children.reference: RFC 5382: NAT Behavioral Requirements for TCP

children.name: tcp-trans-open-timeout
children.description:
The value of the transitory open connection
idle-timeout.

A NAT should provide different configurable
parameters for configuring the open and
closing idle timeouts.

To accommodate deployments that consider
a partially open timeout of 4 minutes as being
excessive from a security standpoint, a NAT may
allow the configured timeout to be less than
4 minutes.

However, a minimum default transitory connection
idle-timeout of 4 minutes is recommended.
children.reference: Section 2.1 of RFC 7857

children.name: tcp-trans-close-timeout
children.description:
The value of the transitory close connection
idle-timeout.

A NAT should provide different configurable
parameters for configuring the open and
closing idle timeouts.
children.reference: Section 2.1 of RFC 7857

children.name: tcp-in-syn-timeout
children.description:
A NAT must not respond to an unsolicited
inbound SYN packet for at least 6 seconds
after the packet is received.  If during
this interval the NAT receives and translates
an outbound SYN for the connection the NAT
must silently drop the original unsolicited
inbound SYN packet.
children.reference: RFC 5382 NAT Behavioral Requirements for TCP

children.name: fragment-min-timeout
children.description:
As long as the NAT has available resources,
the NAT allows the fragments to arrive
over the fragment-min-timeout interval.
The default value is inspired from RFC 6146.

children.name: icmp-timeout
children.description:
An ICMP Query session timer must not expire
in less than 60 seconds.  It is recommended
that the ICMP Query session timer be made
configurable
children.reference: RFC 5508: NAT Behavioral Requirements for ICMP

children.name: per-port-timeout
children.description:
Some NATs are configurable with short timeouts
for some ports, e.g., as 10 seconds on
port 53 (DNS) and 123 (NTP), and longer timeouts
on other ports.

children.name: port-number
children.description: A port number.

children.name: protocol
children.description:
The upper-layer protocol associated with this port.

Values are taken from the IANA Protocol Numbers
registry.

If no protocol is indicated, it means 'any
protocol'.

children.name: timeout
children.description: Timeout for this port number

children.name: hold-down-timeout
children.description:
Hold-down timer.

Ports in the hold-down pool are not reassigned until
hold-down-timeout expires.

The length of time and the maximum number of ports in
this state must be configurable by the administrator.

This is necessary in order to prevent collisions
between old and new mappings and sessions.  It ensures
that all established sessions are broken instead of
redirected to a different peer.
children.reference: REQ-8 of RFC 6888

children.name: hold-down-max
children.description: Maximum ports in the hold-down port pool.
children.reference: REQ-8 of RFC 6888

children.name: fragments-limit
children.description:
Limits the number of out-of-order fragments that can
be handled.
children.reference: Section 11 of RFC 4787

children.name: algs
children.description:
Features related to the Application Layer
Gateway (ALG).

children.name: name
children.description: The name of the ALG.

children.name: transport-protocol
children.description:
The transport protocol used by the ALG
(e.g., TCP and UDP).

children.name: dst-transport-port
children.description:
The destination port number(s) used by the ALG.
For example,
  - 21 for the FTP ALG
  - 53 for the DNS ALG.

children.name: start-port-number
children.description: Beginning of the port range.
children.reference: Section 3.2.9 of RFC 8045

children.name: end-port-number
children.description: End of the port range.
children.reference: Section 3.2.10 of RFC 8045

children.name: src-transport-port
children.description: The source port number(s) used by the ALG.

children.name: start-port-number
children.description: Beginning of the port range.
children.reference: Section 3.2.9 of RFC 8045

children.name: end-port-number
children.description: End of the port range.
children.reference: Section 3.2.10 of RFC 8045

children.name: status
children.description: Enable/disable the ALG.

children.name: all-algs-enable
children.description:
Disable/enable all ALGs.

When specified, this parameter overrides the one
that may be indicated, eventually, by the 'status'
of an individual ALG.

children.name: notify-pool-usage
children.description:
Notification of pool usage when certain criteria
are met.

children.name: pool-id
children.description:
Pool-ID for which the notification criteria
is defined

children.name: low-threshold
children.description:
Notification must be generated when the defined low
threshold is reached.

For example, if a notification is required when the
pool utilization reaches below 10%, this
configuration parameter must be set to 10.

0% indicates that low-threshold notification is
disabled.

children.name: high-threshold
children.description:
Notification must be generated when the defined high
threshold is reached.

For example, if a notification is required when the
pool utilization reaches 90%, this configuration
parameter must be set to 90.

Setting the same value as low-threshold is equivalent
to disabling high-threshold notification.

children.name: notify-interval
children.description:
Minimum number of seconds between successive
notifications for this pool.
children.reference:
RFC 7659: Definitions of Managed Objects for
          Network Address Translators (NATs)

children.name: external-realm
children.description: Identifies the external realm of the NAT instance.

children.name: realm-type
children.description: Can be an interface, VRF instance, etc.

children.name: interface
children.description: External interface.

children.name: external-interface
children.description: Name of the external interface.

children.name: max-softwires-per-subscriber
children.description:
Configures the maximum softwires per subscriber feature.

A subscriber is uniquely identified by means
of a subscriber-mask (subscriber-mask-v6).

This policy aims to prevent a misbehaving subscriber from
mounting several DS-Lite softwires that would consume
additional AFTR resources (e.g., get more external ports
if the quota was enforced on a per-softwire basis and
consume extra processing due to a large number of active
softwires).
children.reference: Section 4 of RFC 7785

children.name: state-migrate
children.description:
State migration is enabled by default.

In the event a new IPv6 address is assigned to the B4 element,
the AFTR should migrate existing state to be bound to the new
IPv6 address.  This operation ensures that traffic destined to
the previous B4's IPv6 address will be redirected to the newer
B4's IPv6 address.  The destination IPv6 address for tunneling
return traffic from the AFTR should be the last seen as the
B4's IPv6 source address from the user device (e.g., CPE).

The AFTR uses the subscriber-mask-v6 to determine whether two
IPv6 addresses belong to the same CPE (e.g., if the
subscriber-mask-v6 is set to 56, the AFTR concludes that
2001:db8:100:100::1 and 2001:db8:100:100::2 belong to the same
CPE assigned with 2001:db8:100:100::/56).
children.reference:
RFC 7785: Recommendations for Prefix Binding in the Context
          of Softwire Dual-Stack Lite

children.name: b4-address-change-limit
children.description:
Minimum number of seconds between a successive B4's IPv6
address change from the same prefix.

Changing the source B4's IPv6 address may be used as an attack
vector.  Packets with a new B4's IPv6 address from the same
prefix should be rate-limited.

It is recommended that this rate limit be set to 30 minutes;
other values can be set on a per-deployment basis.
children.reference:
RFC 7785: Recommendations for Prefix Binding in the Context
          of Softwire Dual-Stack Lite

children.name: mss-clamping
children.description: MSS rewriting configuration to avoid IPv6 fragmentation.

children.name: enable
children.description: Enable/disable MSS rewriting feature.

children.name: mss-value
children.description: Sets the MSS value to be used for MSS rewriting.

children.name: mapping-limits
children.description:
Information about the configuration parameters that
limits the mappings based upon various criteria.

children.name: limit-subscribers
children.description:
Maximum number of subscribers that can be serviced
by a NAT instance.

A subscriber is identified by a given prefix.
children.reference:
RFC 7659: Definitions of Managed Objects for
          Network Address Translators (NATs)

children.name: limit-address-mappings
children.description:
Maximum number of address mappings that can be
handled by a NAT instance.

When this limit is reached, packets that would
normally trigger translation will be dropped.
children.reference:
RFC 7659: Definitions of Managed Objects for
          Network Address Translators (NATs)

children.name: limit-port-mappings
children.description:
Maximum number of port mappings that can be handled
by a NAT instance.

When this limit is reached, packets that would
normally trigger translation will be dropped.
children.reference:
RFC 7659: Definitions of Managed Objects for
          Network Address Translators (NATs)

children.name: limit-per-protocol
children.description: Configure limits per transport protocol

children.name: protocol-id
children.description:
The upper-layer protocol.

Values are taken from the IANA Protocol Numbers
registry.

For example, this field contains 6 for TCP,
17 for UDP, 33 for DCCP, or 132 for SCTP.

children.name: limit
children.description:
Maximum number of protocol-specific NAT mappings
per instance.

children.name: connection-limits
children.description:
Information about the configuration parameters that
rate-limit the translation based upon various criteria.

children.name: limit-per-subscriber
children.description:
Rate-limit the number of new mappings and sessions
per subscriber.

children.name: limit-per-instance
children.description:
Rate-limit the number of new mappings and sessions
per instance.

children.name: limit-per-protocol
children.description: Configure limits per transport protocol

children.name: protocol-id
children.description:
The upper-layer protocol.

Values are taken from the IANA Protocol Numbers
registry.

For example, this field contains 6 for TCP,
17 for UDP, 33 for DCCP, or 132 for SCTP.

children.name: limit
children.description:
Limit the number of protocol-specific mappings
and sessions per instance.

children.name: notification-limits
children.description: Sets notification limits.

children.name: notify-interval
children.description:
Minimum number of seconds between successive
notifications for this NAT instance.
children.reference:
RFC 7659: Definitions of Managed Objects for
          Network Address Translators (NATs)

children.name: notify-addresses-usage
children.description:
Notification of address mappings usage over
the whole NAT instance.

Notification must be generated when the defined
threshold is reached.

For example, if a notification is required when
the address mappings utilization reaches 90%,
this configuration parameter must be set
to 90.

children.name: notify-ports-usage
children.description:
Notification of port mappings usage over the
whole NAT instance.

Notification must be generated when the defined
threshold is reached.

For example, if a notification is required when
the port mappings utilization reaches 90%, this
configuration parameter must be set to 90.

children.name: notify-subscribers-limit
children.description:
Notification of active subscribers per NAT
instance.

Notification must be generated when the defined
threshold is reached.

children.name: mapping-table
children.description:
NAT mapping table.  Applicable for functions that maintain
static and/or dynamic mappings, such as NAT44, Destination
NAT, NAT64, or CLAT.

children.name: mapping-entry
children.description: NAT mapping entry.

children.name: index
children.description:
A unique identifier of a mapping entry.  This identifier
can be automatically assigned by the NAT instance or be
explicitly configured.

children.name: type
children.description:
Indicates the type of a mapping entry.  For example,
a mapping can be: static, implicit dynamic,
or explicit dynamic.

children.name: transport-protocol
children.description:
The upper-layer protocol associated with this mapping.
Values are taken from the IANA Protocol Numbers registry:
<https://www.iana.org/assignments/protocol-numbers/>.

For example, this field contains 6 for TCP,
17 for UDP, 33 for DCCP, or 132 for SCTP.

If this leaf is not instantiated, then the mapping
applies to any protocol.

children.name: internal-src-address
children.description:
Corresponds to the source IPv4/IPv6 address/prefix
of the packet received on an internal interface.

children.name: internal-src-port
children.description:
Corresponds to the source port of the packet received
on an internal interface.

It is also used to indicate the internal source ICMP
identifier.

As a reminder, all the ICMP Query messages contain
an 'Identifier' field, which is referred to in this
document as the 'ICMP Identifier'.

children.name: start-port-number
children.description: Beginning of the port range.
children.reference: Section 3.2.9 of RFC 8045

children.name: end-port-number
children.description: End of the port range.
children.reference: Section 3.2.10 of RFC 8045

children.name: external-src-address
children.description:
Source IP address/prefix of the packet sent on an
external interface of the NAT.

children.name: external-src-port
children.description:
Source port of the packet sent on an external
interface of the NAT.

It is also used to indicate the external source ICMP
identifier.

children.name: start-port-number
children.description: Beginning of the port range.
children.reference: Section 3.2.9 of RFC 8045

children.name: end-port-number
children.description: End of the port range.
children.reference: Section 3.2.10 of RFC 8045

children.name: internal-dst-address
children.description:
Corresponds to the destination IP address/prefix
of the packet received on an internal interface
of the NAT.

For example, some NAT implementations support
the translation of both source and destination
addresses and port numbers, sometimes referred to
as 'Twice NAT'.

children.name: internal-dst-port
children.description:
Corresponds to the destination port of the
IP packet received on the internal interface.

It is also used to include the internal
destination ICMP identifier.

children.name: start-port-number
children.description: Beginning of the port range.
children.reference: Section 3.2.9 of RFC 8045

children.name: end-port-number
children.description: End of the port range.
children.reference: Section 3.2.10 of RFC 8045

children.name: external-dst-address
children.description:
Corresponds to the destination IP address/prefix
of the packet sent on an external interface
of the NAT.

children.name: external-dst-port
children.description:
Corresponds to the destination port number of
the packet sent on the external interface
of the NAT.

It is also used to include the external
destination ICMP identifier.

children.name: start-port-number
children.description: Beginning of the port range.
children.reference: Section 3.2.9 of RFC 8045

children.name: end-port-number
children.description: End of the port range.
children.reference: Section 3.2.10 of RFC 8045

children.name: lifetime
children.description:
When specified, it is used to track the connection that is
fully formed (e.g., once the three-way handshake
TCP is completed) or the duration for maintaining
an explicit mapping alive.  The mapping entry will be
removed by the NAT instance once this lifetime is expired.

When reported in a get operation, the lifetime indicates
the remaining validity lifetime.

Static mappings may not be associated with a
lifetime.  If no lifetime is associated with a
static mapping, an explicit action is required to
remove that mapping.

children.name: b4-ipv6-address
children.description:
Records the IPv6 address used by a B4 element and the last
time that address changed.

children.name: address
children.description: Corresponds to the IPv6 address used by a B4 element.
children.reference:
RFC 6333: Dual-Stack Lite Broadband Deployments Following
          IPv4 Exhaustion

children.name: last-address-change
children.description: Records the last time that the address changed.

children.name: v6-dscp
children.description: DSCP value used at the softwire level (i.e., IPv6 header).

children.name: internal-v4-dscp
children.description: DSCP value of the encapsulated IPv4 packet.

children.name: external-v4-dscp
children.description:
DSCP value of the translated IPv4 packet as marked by
the AFTR.

children.name: statistics
children.description: Statistics related to the NAT instance.

children.name: discontinuity-time
children.description:
The time on the most recent occasion at which the NAT
instance suffered a discontinuity.  This must be
initialized when the NAT instance is configured
or rebooted.

children.name: traffic-statistics
children.description: Generic traffic statistics.

children.name: sent-packets
children.description: Number of packets sent.

children.name: sent-bytes
children.description: Counter for sent traffic in bytes.

children.name: rcvd-packets
children.description: Number of received packets.

children.name: rcvd-bytes
children.description: Counter for received traffic in bytes.

children.name: dropped-packets
children.description: Number of dropped packets.

children.name: dropped-bytes
children.description: Counter for dropped traffic in bytes.

children.name: dropped-fragments
children.description: Number of dropped fragments on the external realm.

children.name: dropped-address-limit-packets
children.description:
Number of dropped packets because an address limit
 is reached.

children.name: dropped-address-limit-bytes
children.description:
Counter of dropped packets because an address limit
 is reached, in bytes.

children.name: dropped-address-packets
children.description:
Number of dropped packets because no address is
available for allocation.

children.name: dropped-address-bytes
children.description:
Counter of dropped packets because no address is
available for allocation, in bytes.

children.name: dropped-port-limit-packets
children.description:
Number of dropped packets because a port limit
is reached.

children.name: dropped-port-limit-bytes
children.description:
Counter of dropped packets because a port limit
is reached, in bytes.

children.name: dropped-port-packets
children.description:
Number of dropped packets because no port is
available for allocation.

children.name: dropped-port-bytes
children.description:
Counter of dropped packets because no port is
available for allocation, in bytes.

children.name: dropped-subscriber-limit-packets
children.description:
Number of dropped packets because the subscriber
limit per instance is reached.

children.name: dropped-subscriber-limit-bytes
children.description:
Counter of dropped packets because the subscriber
 limit per instance is reached, in bytes.

children.name: mappings-statistics
children.description: Mappings statistics.

children.name: total-active-subscribers
children.description:
Total number of active subscribers (that is,
subscribers for which the NAT maintains active
mappings).

A subscriber is identified by a subnet,
subscriber-mask, etc.

children.name: total-address-mappings
children.description:
Total number of address mappings present at a given
time.  It includes both static and dynamic mappings.
children.reference: Section 3.3.8 of RFC 7659

children.name: total-port-mappings
children.description:
Total number of NAT port mappings present at
a given time.  It includes both static and dynamic
mappings.
children.reference: Section 3.3.9 of RFC 7659

children.name: total-per-protocol
children.description: Total mappings for each enabled/supported protocol.

children.name: protocol-id
children.description:
The upper-layer protocol.
For example, this field contains 6 for TCP,
17 for UDP, 33 for DCCP, or 132 for SCTP.

children.name: total
children.description:
Total number of a protocol-specific mappings present
at a given time.  The protocol is identified by
protocol-id.

children.name: active-softwires
children.description:
The number of currently active softwires on the AFTR
instance.

children.name: pools-stats
children.description:
Statistics related to address/prefix pools
usage

children.name: addresses-allocated
children.description: Number of all allocated addresses.

children.name: addresses-free
children.description:
Number of unallocated addresses of all pools at
a given time.  The sum of unallocated and allocated
addresses is the total number of addresses of
the pools.

children.name: ports-stats
children.description: Statistics related to port numbers usage.

children.name: ports-allocated
children.description: Number of allocated ports from all pools.

children.name: ports-free
children.description: Number of unallocated addresses from all pools.

children.name: per-pool-stats
children.description: Statistics related to address/prefix pool usage

children.name: pool-id
children.description:
Unique identifier that represents a pool of
addresses/prefixes.

children.name: discontinuity-time
children.description:
The time on the most recent occasion at which this
pool counter suffered a discontinuity.  This must
be initialized when the address pool is
configured.

children.name: pool-stats
children.description: Statistics related to address/prefix pool usage

children.name: addresses-allocated
children.description: Number of allocated addresses from this pool.

children.name: addresses-free
children.description: Number of unallocated addresses in this pool.

children.name: port-stats
children.description: Statistics related to port numbers usage.

children.name: ports-allocated
children.description: Number of allocated ports from this pool.

children.name: ports-free
children.description: Number of unallocated addresses from this pool.

children.name: nat-pool-event
children.description:
Notifications must be generated when the defined high/low
threshold is reached.  Related configuration parameters
must be provided to trigger the notifications.

children.name: id
children.description: NAT instance identifier.

children.name: policy-id
children.description: Policy identifier.

children.name: pool-id
children.description: Pool Identifier.

children.name: notify-pool-threshold
children.description:
A threshold (high threshold or low threshold) has
been fired.

children.name: nat-instance-event
children.description:
Notifications must be generated when notify-addresses-usage
and/or notify-ports-usage thresholds are reached.

children.name: id
children.description: NAT instance identifier.

children.name: notify-subscribers-threshold
children.description: The notify-subscribers-limit threshold has been fired.

children.name: notify-addresses-threshold
children.description: The notify-addresses-usage threshold has been fired.

children.name: notify-ports-threshold
children.description: The notify-ports-usage threshold has been fired.

modules.name: ietf-netconf
modules.description:
NETCONF Protocol Data Types and Protocol Operations.

modules.contact:

WG List:  <netconf@ietf.org>

children.name: get-config
children.description: Retrieve all or part of a specified configuration.
children.reference: RFC 6241, Section 7.1

children.name: source
children.description: Particular configuration to retrieve.

children.name: config-source
children.description: The configuration to retrieve.

children.name: candidate
children.description: The candidate configuration is the config source.

children.name: running
children.description: The running configuration is the config source.

children.name: startup
children.description:
The startup configuration is the config source.
This is optional-to-implement on the server because
not all servers will support filtering for this
datastore.

children.name: filter
children.description: Subtree or XPath filter to use.

children.name: with-defaults
children.description: The explicit defaults processing mode requested.
children.reference: RFC 6243; Section 4.5.1

children.name: data
children.description:
Copy of the source datastore subset that matched
the filter criteria (if any).  An empty data container
indicates that the request did not produce any results.

children.name: edit-config
children.description:
The <edit-config> operation loads all or part of a specified
configuration to the specified target configuration.
children.reference: RFC 6241, Section 7.2

children.name: target
children.description: Particular configuration to edit.

children.name: config-target
children.description: The configuration target.

children.name: candidate
children.description: The candidate configuration is the config target.

children.name: running
children.description: The running configuration is the config source.

children.name: default-operation
children.description: The default operation to use.

children.name: test-option
children.description: The test option to use.

children.name: error-option
children.description: The error option to use.

children.name: edit-content
children.description: The content for the edit operation.

children.name: config
children.description: Inline Config content.

children.name: url
children.description: URL-based config content.

children.name: copy-config
children.description:
Create or replace an entire configuration datastore with the
contents of another complete configuration datastore.
children.reference: RFC 6241, Section 7.3

children.name: target
children.description: Particular configuration to copy to.

children.name: config-target
children.description: The configuration target of the copy operation.

children.name: candidate
children.description: The candidate configuration is the config target.

children.name: running
children.description:
The running configuration is the config target.
This is optional-to-implement on the server.

children.name: startup
children.description: The startup configuration is the config target.

children.name: url
children.description: The URL-based configuration is the config target.

children.name: source
children.description: Particular configuration to copy from.

children.name: config-source
children.description: The configuration source for the copy operation.

children.name: candidate
children.description: The candidate configuration is the config source.

children.name: running
children.description: The running configuration is the config source.

children.name: startup
children.description: The startup configuration is the config source.

children.name: url
children.description: The URL-based configuration is the config source.

children.name: config
children.description:
Inline Config content: <config> element.  Represents
an entire configuration datastore, not
a subset of the running datastore.

children.name: with-defaults
children.description: The explicit defaults processing mode requested.
children.reference: RFC 6243; Section 4.5.1

children.name: delete-config
children.description: Delete a configuration datastore.
children.reference: RFC 6241, Section 7.4

children.name: target
children.description: Particular configuration to delete.

children.name: config-target
children.description: The configuration target to delete.

children.name: startup
children.description: The startup configuration is the config target.

children.name: url
children.description: The URL-based configuration is the config target.

children.name: lock
children.description:
The lock operation allows the client to lock the configuration
system of a device.
children.reference: RFC 6241, Section 7.5

children.name: target
children.description: Particular configuration to lock.

children.name: config-target
children.description: The configuration target to lock.

children.name: candidate
children.description: The candidate configuration is the config target.

children.name: running
children.description: The running configuration is the config target.

children.name: startup
children.description: The startup configuration is the config target.

children.name: datastore
children.description:
Datastore to lock.

The <lock> operation is only supported on writable
datastores.

If the <lock> operation is not supported by the server on
the specified target datastore, then the server MUST return
an <rpc-error> element with an <error-tag> value of
'invalid-value'.

children.name: unlock
children.description:
The unlock operation is used to release a configuration lock,
previously obtained with the 'lock' operation.
children.reference: RFC 6241, Section 7.6

children.name: target
children.description: Particular configuration to unlock.

children.name: config-target
children.description: The configuration target to unlock.

children.name: candidate
children.description: The candidate configuration is the config target.

children.name: running
children.description: The running configuration is the config target.

children.name: startup
children.description: The startup configuration is the config target.

children.name: datastore
children.description:
Datastore to unlock.

The <unlock> operation is only supported on writable
datastores.

If the <unlock> operation is not supported by the server on
the specified target datastore, then the server MUST return
an <rpc-error> element with an <error-tag> value of
'invalid-value'.

children.name: get
children.description: Retrieve running configuration and device state information.
children.reference: RFC 6241, Section 7.7

children.name: filter
children.description:
This parameter specifies the portion of the system
configuration and state data to retrieve.

children.name: with-defaults
children.description: The explicit defaults processing mode requested.
children.reference: RFC 6243; Section 4.5.1

children.name: data
children.description:
Copy of the running datastore subset and/or state
data that matched the filter criteria (if any).
An empty data container indicates that the request did not
produce any results.

children.name: close-session
children.description: Request graceful termination of a NETCONF session.
children.reference: RFC 6241, Section 7.8

children.name: kill-session
children.description: Force the termination of a NETCONF session.
children.reference: RFC 6241, Section 7.9

children.name: session-id
children.description: Particular session to kill.

children.name: commit
children.description:
Commit the candidate configuration as the device's new
current configuration.
children.reference: RFC 6241, Section 8.3.4.1

children.name: confirmed
children.description: Requests a confirmed commit.
children.reference: RFC 6241, Section 8.3.4.1

children.name: confirm-timeout
children.description: The timeout interval for a confirmed commit.
children.reference: RFC 6241, Section 8.3.4.1

children.name: persist
children.description:
This parameter is used to make a confirmed commit
persistent.  A persistent confirmed commit is not aborted
if the NETCONF session terminates.  The only way to abort
a persistent confirmed commit is to let the timer expire,
or to use the <cancel-commit> operation.

The value of this parameter is a token that must be given
in the 'persist-id' parameter of <commit> or
<cancel-commit> operations in order to confirm or cancel
the persistent confirmed commit.

The token should be a random string.
children.reference: RFC 6241, Section 8.3.4.1

children.name: persist-id
children.description:
This parameter is given in order to commit a persistent
confirmed commit.  The value must be equal to the value
given in the 'persist' parameter to the <commit> operation.
If it does not match, the operation fails with an
'invalid-value' error.
children.reference: RFC 6241, Section 8.3.4.1

children.name: discard-changes
children.description:
Revert the candidate configuration to the current
running configuration.
children.reference: RFC 6241, Section 8.3.4.2

children.name: cancel-commit
children.description:
This operation is used to cancel an ongoing confirmed commit.
If the confirmed commit is persistent, the parameter
'persist-id' must be given, and it must match the value of the
'persist' parameter.
children.reference: RFC 6241, Section 8.4.4.1

children.name: persist-id
children.description:
This parameter is given in order to cancel a persistent
confirmed commit.  The value must be equal to the value
given in the 'persist' parameter to the <commit> operation.
If it does not match, the operation fails with an
'invalid-value' error.

children.name: validate
children.description: Validates the contents of the specified configuration.
children.reference: RFC 6241, Section 8.6.4.1

children.name: source
children.description: Particular configuration to validate.

children.name: config-source
children.description: The configuration source to validate.

children.name: candidate
children.description: The candidate configuration is the config source.

children.name: running
children.description: The running configuration is the config source.

children.name: startup
children.description: The startup configuration is the config source.

children.name: url
children.description: The URL-based configuration is the config source.

children.name: config
children.description:
Inline Config content: <config> element.  Represents
an entire configuration datastore, not
a subset of the running datastore.

children.name: datastore
children.description:
Datastore to validate.

The <validate> operation is supported only on configuration
datastores.

If the <validate> operation is not supported by the server
on the specified target datastore, then the server MUST
return an <rpc-error> element with an <error-tag> value of
'invalid-value'.

modules.description:
Network Configuration Access Control Model.

modules.organization: IETF NETCONF (Network Configuration) Working Group
modules.contact:
WG Web:   <https://datatracker.ietf.org/wg/netconf/>
WG List:  <mailto:netconf@ietf.org>

Author:   Andy Bierman
          <mailto:andy@yumaworks.com>

Author:   Martin Bjorklund
          <mailto:mbj@tail-f.com>

children.name: nacm
children.description: Parameters for NETCONF access control model.

children.name: enable-nacm
children.description:
Enables or disables all NETCONF access control
enforcement.  If 'true', then enforcement
is enabled.  If 'false', then enforcement
is disabled.

children.name: read-default
children.description:
Controls whether read access is granted if
no appropriate rule is found for a
particular read request.

children.name: write-default
children.description:
Controls whether create, update, or delete access
is granted if no appropriate rule is found for a
particular write request.

children.name: exec-default
children.description:
Controls whether exec access is granted if no appropriate
rule is found for a particular protocol operation request.

children.name: enable-external-groups
children.description:
Controls whether the server uses the groups reported by the
NETCONF transport layer when it assigns the user to a set of
NACM groups.  If this leaf has the value 'false', any group
names reported by the transport layer are ignored by the
server.

children.name: denied-operations
children.description:
Number of times since the server last restarted that a
protocol operation request was denied.

children.name: denied-data-writes
children.description:
Number of times since the server last restarted that a
protocol operation request to alter
a configuration datastore was denied.

children.name: denied-notifications
children.description:
Number of times since the server last restarted that
a notification was dropped for a subscription because
access to the event type was denied.

children.name: groups
children.description: NETCONF access control groups.

children.name: group
children.description:
One NACM group entry.  This list will only contain
configured entries, not any entries learned from
any transport protocols.

children.name: name
children.description: Group name associated with this entry.

children.name: user-name
children.description:
Each entry identifies the username of
a member of the group associated with
this entry.

children.name: rule-list
children.description: An ordered collection of access control rules.

children.name: name
children.description: Arbitrary name assigned to the rule-list.

children.name: group
children.description:
List of administrative groups that will be
assigned the associated access rights
defined by the 'rule' list.

The string '*' indicates that all groups apply to the
entry.

children.name: rule
children.description:
One access control rule.

Rules are processed in user-defined order until a match is
found.  A rule matches if 'module-name', 'rule-type', and
'access-operations' match the request.  If a rule
matches, the 'action' leaf determines whether or not
access is granted.

children.name: name
children.description: Arbitrary name assigned to the rule.

children.name: module-name
children.description:
Name of the module associated with this rule.

This leaf matches if it has the value '*' or if the
object being accessed is defined in the module with the
specified module name.

children.name: rule-type
children.description:
This choice matches if all leafs present in the rule
match the request.  If no leafs are present, the
choice matches all requests.

children.name: rpc-name
children.description:
This leaf matches if it has the value '*' or if
its value equals the requested protocol operation
name.

children.name: notification-name
children.description:
This leaf matches if it has the value '*' or if its
value equals the requested notification name.

children.name: path
children.description:
Data node instance-identifier associated with the
data node, action, or notification controlled by
this rule.

Configuration data or state data
instance-identifiers start with a top-level
data node.  A complete instance-identifier is
required for this type of path value.

The special value '/' refers to all possible
datastore contents.

children.name: access-operations
children.description:
Access operations associated with this rule.

This leaf matches if it has the value '*' or if the
bit corresponding to the requested operation is set.

children.name: action
children.description:
The access control action associated with the
rule.  If a rule has been determined to match a
particular request, then this object is used
to determine whether to permit or deny the
request.

children.name: comment
children.description: A textual description of the access rule.

modules.name: ietf-netconf-monitoring
modules.description:
NETCONF Monitoring Module.
All elements in this module are read-only.

Copyright (c) 2010 IETF Trust and the persons identified as
authors of the code. All rights reserved.

Redistribution and use in source and binary forms, with or
without modification, is permitted pursuant to, and subject
to the license terms contained in, the Simplified BSD
License set forth in Section 4.c of the IETF Trust's
Legal Provisions Relating to IETF Documents
(http://trustee.ietf.org/license-info).

This version of this YANG module is part of RFC 6022; see
the RFC itself for full legal notices.
modules.organization: IETF NETCONF (Network Configuration) Working Group
modules.contact:
WG Web:   <http://tools.ietf.org/wg/netconf/>
WG List:  <mailto:netconf@ietf.org>

WG Chair: Mehmet Ersue
          <mailto:mehmet.ersue@nsn.com>

WG Chair: Bert Wijnen
          <mailto:bertietf@bwijnen.net>

Editor:   Mark Scott
          <mailto:mark.scott@ericsson.com>

Editor:   Martin Bjorklund
          <mailto:mbj@tail-f.com>

children.name: netconf-state
children.description:
The netconf-state container is the root of the monitoring
data model.

children.name: capabilities
children.description:
Contains the list of NETCONF capabilities supported by the
server.

children.name: capability
children.description: List of NETCONF capabilities supported by the server.

children.name: datastores
children.description: Contains the list of NETCONF configuration datastores.

children.name: datastore
children.description:
List of NETCONF configuration datastores supported by
the NETCONF server and related information.

children.name: name
children.description: Name of the datastore associated with this list entry.

children.name: locks
children.description:
The NETCONF <lock> and <partial-lock> operations allow
a client to lock specific resources in a datastore.  The
NETCONF server will prevent changes to the locked
resources by all sessions except the one that acquired
the lock(s).

Monitoring information is provided for each datastore
entry including details such as the session that acquired
the lock, the type of lock (global or partial) and the
list of locked resources.  Multiple locks per datastore
are supported.

children.name: lock-type
children.description:
Indicates if a global lock or a set of partial locks
are set.

children.name: global-lock
children.description: Present if the global lock is set.

children.name: locked-by-session
children.description:
The session ID of the session that has locked
this resource.  Both a global lock and a partial
lock MUST contain the NETCONF session-id.

If the lock is held by a session that is not managed
by the NETCONF server (e.g., a CLI session), a session
id of 0 (zero) is reported.
children.reference: RFC 4741: NETCONF Configuration Protocol

children.name: locked-time
children.description:
The date and time of when the resource was
locked.

children.name: partial-lock
children.description: List of partial locks.
children.reference:
RFC 5717: Partial Lock Remote Procedure Call (RPC) for
          NETCONF

children.name: lock-id
children.description:
This is the lock id returned in the <partial-lock>
response.

children.name: locked-by-session
children.description:
The session ID of the session that has locked
this resource.  Both a global lock and a partial
lock MUST contain the NETCONF session-id.

If the lock is held by a session that is not managed
by the NETCONF server (e.g., a CLI session), a session
id of 0 (zero) is reported.
children.reference: RFC 4741: NETCONF Configuration Protocol

children.name: locked-time
children.description:
The date and time of when the resource was
locked.

children.name: select
children.description:
The xpath expression that was used to request
the lock.  The select expression indicates the
original intended scope of the lock.

children.name: locked-node
children.description:
The list of instance-identifiers (i.e., the
locked nodes).

The scope of the partial lock is defined by the list
of locked nodes.

children.name: schemas
children.description:
Contains the list of data model schemas supported by the
server.

children.name: schema
children.description: List of data model schemas supported by the server.

children.name: identifier
children.description:
Identifier to uniquely reference the schema.  The
identifier is used in the <get-schema> operation and may
be used for other purposes such as file retrieval.

For modeling languages that support or require a data
model name (e.g., YANG module name) the identifier MUST
match that name.  For YANG data models, the identifier is
the name of the module or submodule.  In other cases, an
identifier such as a filename MAY be used instead.

children.name: version
children.description:
Version of the schema supported.  Multiple versions MAY be
supported simultaneously by a NETCONF server.  Each
version MUST be reported individually in the schema list,
i.e., with same identifier, possibly different location,
but different version.

For YANG data models, version is the value of the most
recent YANG 'revision' statement in the module or
submodule, or the empty string if no 'revision' statement
is present.

children.name: format
children.description:
The data modeling language the schema is written
in (currently xsd, yang, yin, rng, or rnc).
For YANG data models, 'yang' format MUST be supported and
'yin' format MAY also be provided.

children.name: namespace
children.description:
The XML namespace defined by the data model.

For YANG data models, this is the module's namespace.
If the list entry describes a submodule, this field
contains the namespace of the module to which the
submodule belongs.

children.name: location
children.description:
One or more locations from which the schema can be
retrieved.  This list SHOULD contain at least one
entry per schema.

A schema entry may be located on a remote file system
(e.g., reference to file system for ftp retrieval) or
retrieved directly from a server supporting the
<get-schema> operation (denoted by the value 'NETCONF').

children.name: sessions
children.description:
The sessions container includes session-specific data for
NETCONF management sessions.  The session list MUST include
all currently active NETCONF sessions.

children.name: session
children.description:
All NETCONF sessions managed by the NETCONF server
MUST be reported in this list.

children.name: session-id
children.description:
Unique identifier for the session.  This value is the
NETCONF session identifier, as defined in RFC 4741.
children.reference: RFC 4741: NETCONF Configuration Protocol

children.name: transport
children.description:
Identifies the transport for each session, e.g.,
'netconf-ssh', 'netconf-soap', etc.

children.name: username
children.description:
The username is the client identity that was authenticated
by the NETCONF transport protocol.  The algorithm used to
derive the username is NETCONF transport protocol specific
and in addition specific to the authentication mechanism
used by the NETCONF transport protocol.

children.name: source-host
children.description:
Host identifier of the NETCONF client.  The value
returned is implementation specific (e.g., hostname,
IPv4 address, IPv6 address)

children.name: login-time
children.description: Time at the server at which the session was established.

children.name: in-rpcs
children.description: Number of correct <rpc> messages received.

children.name: in-bad-rpcs
children.description:
Number of messages received when an <rpc> message was expected,
that were not correct <rpc> messages.  This includes XML parse
errors and errors on the rpc layer.

children.name: out-rpc-errors
children.description:
Number of <rpc-reply> messages sent that contained an
<rpc-error> element.

children.name: out-notifications
children.description: Number of <notification> messages sent.

children.name: statistics
children.description: Statistical data pertaining to the NETCONF server.

children.name: netconf-start-time
children.description:
Date and time at which the management subsystem was
started.

children.name: in-bad-hellos
children.description:
Number of sessions silently dropped because an
invalid <hello> message was received.  This includes <hello>
messages with a 'session-id' attribute, bad namespace, and
bad capability declarations.

children.name: in-sessions
children.description:
Number of sessions started.  This counter is incremented
when a <hello> message with a <session-id> is sent.

'in-sessions' - 'in-bad-hellos' =
   'number of correctly started netconf sessions'

children.name: dropped-sessions
children.description:
Number of sessions that were abnormally terminated, e.g.,
due to idle timeout or transport close.  This counter is not
incremented when a session is properly closed by a
<close-session> operation, or killed by a <kill-session>
operation.

children.name: in-rpcs
children.description: Number of correct <rpc> messages received.

children.name: in-bad-rpcs
children.description:
Number of messages received when an <rpc> message was expected,
that were not correct <rpc> messages.  This includes XML parse
errors and errors on the rpc layer.

children.name: out-rpc-errors
children.description:
Number of <rpc-reply> messages sent that contained an
<rpc-error> element.

children.name: out-notifications
children.description: Number of <notification> messages sent.

children.name: get-schema
children.description:
This operation is used to retrieve a schema from the
NETCONF server.

Positive Response:
  The NETCONF server returns the requested schema.

Negative Response:
  If requested schema does not exist, the <error-tag> is
  'invalid-value'.

  If more than one schema matches the requested parameters, the
  <error-tag> is 'operation-failed', and <error-app-tag> is
  'data-not-unique'.

children.name: identifier
children.description: Identifier for the schema list entry.

children.name: version
children.description:
Version of the schema requested.  If this parameter is not
present, and more than one version of the schema exists on
the server, a 'data-not-unique' error is returned, as
described above.

children.name: format
children.description:
The data modeling language of the schema.  If this
parameter is not present, and more than one formats of
the schema exists on the server, a 'data-not-unique' error
is returned, as described above.

children.name: data
children.description: Contains the schema content.

modules.name: ietf-netconf-nmda
modules.description:
This YANG module defines a set of NETCONF operations to support
the Network Management Datastore Architecture (NMDA).

The key words 'MUST', 'MUST NOT', 'REQUIRED', 'SHALL', 'SHALL
NOT', 'SHOULD', 'SHOULD NOT', 'RECOMMENDED', 'NOT RECOMMENDED',
'MAY', and 'OPTIONAL' in this document are to be interpreted as
described in BCP 14 (RFC 2119) (RFC 8174) when, and only when,
they appear in all capitals, as shown here.

Copyright (c) 2019 IETF Trust and the persons identified as
authors of the code.  All rights reserved.

Redistribution and use in source and binary forms, with or
without modification, is permitted pursuant to, and subject to
the license terms contained in, the Simplified BSD License set
forth in Section 4.c of the IETF Trust's Legal Provisions
Relating to IETF Documents
(https://trustee.ietf.org/license-info).

This version of this YANG module is part of RFC 8526; see
the RFC itself for full legal notices.

modules.contact:
WG Web:   <https://datatracker.ietf.org/wg/netconf/>

WG List:  <mailto:netconf@ietf.org>

          <mailto:mbj@tail-f.com>

Author:   Juergen Schoenwaelder
          <mailto:j.schoenwaelder@jacobs-university.de>

Author:   Phil Shafer
          <mailto:phil@juniper.net>

Author:   Kent Watsen
          <mailto:kent+ietf@watsen.net>

Author:   Robert Wilton
          <mailto:rwilton@cisco.com>

children.name: get-data
children.description:
Retrieve data from an NMDA datastore.  The content returned
by get-data must satisfy all filters, i.e., the filter
criteria are logically ANDed.

Any ancestor nodes (including list keys) of nodes selected by
the filters are included in the response.

The 'with-origin' parameter is only valid for an operational
datastore.  If 'with-origin' is used with an invalid
datastore, then the server MUST return an <rpc-error> element
with an <error-tag> value of 'invalid-value'.

The 'with-defaults' parameter only applies to the operational
datastore if the NETCONF :with-defaults and
:with-operational-defaults capabilities are both advertised.
If the 'with-defaults' parameter is present in a request for
which it is not supported, then the server MUST return an
<rpc-error> element with an <error-tag> value of
'invalid-value'.

children.name: datastore
children.description:
Datastore from which to retrieve data.

If the datastore is not supported by the server, then the
server MUST return an <rpc-error> element with an
<error-tag> value of 'invalid-value'.

children.name: filter-spec
children.description: The content filter specification for this request.

children.name: subtree-filter
children.description:
This parameter identifies the portions of the
target datastore to retrieve.
children.reference:
RFC 6241: Network Configuration Protocol (NETCONF),
          Section 6

children.name: xpath-filter
children.description:
This parameter contains an XPath expression identifying
the portions of the target datastore to retrieve.

If the expression returns a node-set, all nodes in the
node-set are selected by the filter.  Otherwise, if the
expression does not return a node-set, then the
<get-data> operation fails.

The expression is evaluated in the following XPath
context:

  o  The set of namespace declarations are those in
     scope on the 'xpath-filter' leaf element.

  o  The set of variable bindings is empty.

  o  The function library is the core function library,
     and the XPath functions are defined in Section 10
     of RFC 7950.

  o  The context node is the root node of the target
     datastore.

children.name: config-filter
children.description:
Filter for nodes with the given value for their 'config'
property.  When this leaf is set to 'true', only 'config
true' nodes are selected, and when set to 'false', only
'config false' nodes are selected.  If this leaf is not
present, no nodes are filtered.

children.name: origin-filters
children.description:
Filters configuration nodes based on the 'origin'
annotation.  Configuration nodes that do not have an
'origin' annotation are treated as if they have the
'origin' annotation 'or:unknown'.

System state nodes are not affected by origin-filters and
thus not filtered.  Note that system state nodes can be
filtered with the 'config-filter' leaf.

children.name: origin-filter
children.description:
Filter based on the 'origin' annotation.  A
configuration node matches the filter if its 'origin'
annotation is derived from or equal to any of the given
filter values.

children.name: negated-origin-filter
children.description:
Filter based on the 'origin' annotation.  A
configuration node matches the filter if its 'origin'
annotation is neither derived from nor equal to any of
the given filter values.

children.name: max-depth
children.description:
For each node selected by the filters, this parameter
selects how many conceptual subtree levels should be
returned in the reply.  If the depth is 1, the reply
includes just the selected nodes but no children.  If the
depth is 'unbounded', all descendant nodes are included.

children.name: with-origin
children.description:
If this parameter is present, the server will return
the 'origin' annotation for the nodes that have one.

children.name: with-defaults
children.description: The explicit defaults processing mode requested.
children.reference: RFC 6243; Section 4.5.1

children.name: data
children.description:
Copy of the source datastore subset that matched
the filter criteria (if any).  An empty data
container indicates that the request did not
produce any results.

children.name: edit-data
children.description:
Edit data in an NMDA datastore.

If an error condition occurs such that an error severity
<rpc-error> element is generated, the server will stop
processing the <edit-data> operation and restore the
specified configuration to its complete state at
the start of this <edit-data> operation.

children.name: datastore
children.description:
Datastore that is the target of the <edit-data> operation.

If the target datastore is not writable, or is not
supported by the server, then the server MUST return an
<rpc-error> element with an <error-tag> value of
'invalid-value'.

children.name: default-operation
children.description: The default operation to use.

children.name: edit-content
children.description: The content for the edit operation.

children.name: config
children.description: Inline config content.

children.name: url
children.description: URL-based config content.

modules.name: ietf-netconf-notifications
modules.description:
This module defines a YANG data model for use with the
NETCONF protocol that allows the NETCONF client to
receive common NETCONF base event notifications.

Copyright (c) 2012 IETF Trust and the persons identified as
the document authors.  All rights reserved.

Redistribution and use in source and binary forms, with or
without modification, is permitted pursuant to, and subject
to the license terms contained in, the Simplified BSD License
set forth in Section 4.c of the IETF Trust's Legal Provisions
Relating to IETF Documents
(http://trustee.ietf.org/license-info).

This version of this YANG module is part of RFC 6470; see
the RFC itself for full legal notices.

children.name: netconf-config-change
children.description:
Generated when the NETCONF server detects that the
<running> or <startup> configuration datastore
has been changed by a management session.
The notification summarizes the edits that
have been detected.

The server MAY choose to also generate this
notification while loading a datastore during the
boot process for the device.

children.name: changed-by
children.description:
Indicates the source of the change.
If caused by internal action, then the
empty leaf 'server' will be present.
If caused by a management session, then
the name, remote host address, and session ID
of the session that made the change will be reported.

children.name: server
children.description:
If present, the change was caused
by the server.

children.name: username
children.description: Name of the user for the session.

children.name: session-id
children.description:
Identifier of the session.
A NETCONF session MUST be identified by a non-zero value.
A non-NETCONF session MAY be identified by the value zero.

children.name: source-host
children.description: Address of the remote host for the session.

children.name: datastore
children.description: Indicates which configuration datastore has changed.

children.name: edit
children.description:
An edit record SHOULD be present for each distinct
edit operation that the server has detected on
the target datastore.  This list MAY be omitted
if the detailed edit operations are not known.
The server MAY report entries in this list for
changes not made by a NETCONF session (e.g., CLI).

children.name: target
children.description:
Topmost node associated with the configuration change.
A server SHOULD set this object to the node within
the datastore that is being altered.  A server MAY
set this object to one of the ancestors of the actual
node that was changed, or omit this object, if the
exact node is not known.

children.name: operation
children.description:
Type of edit operation performed.
A server MUST set this object to the NETCONF edit
operation performed on the target datastore.

children.name: netconf-capability-change
children.description:
Generated when the NETCONF server detects that
the server capabilities have changed.
Indicates which capabilities have been added, deleted,
and/or modified.  The manner in which a server
capability is changed is outside the scope of this
document.

children.name: changed-by
children.description:
Indicates the source of the change.
If caused by internal action, then the
empty leaf 'server' will be present.
If caused by a management session, then
the name, remote host address, and session ID
of the session that made the change will be reported.

children.name: server
children.description:
If present, the change was caused
by the server.

children.name: username
children.description: Name of the user for the session.

children.name: session-id
children.description:
Identifier of the session.
A NETCONF session MUST be identified by a non-zero value.
A non-NETCONF session MAY be identified by the value zero.

children.name: source-host
children.description: Address of the remote host for the session.

children.name: added-capability
children.description: List of capabilities that have just been added.

children.name: deleted-capability
children.description: List of capabilities that have just been deleted.

children.name: modified-capability
children.description:
List of capabilities that have just been modified.
A capability is considered to be modified if the
base URI for the capability has not changed, but
one or more of the parameters encoded at the end of
the capability URI have changed.
The new modified value of the complete URI is returned.

children.name: netconf-session-start
children.description:
Generated when a NETCONF server detects that a
NETCONF session has started.  A server MAY generate
this event for non-NETCONF management sessions.
Indicates the identity of the user that started
the session.

children.name: username
children.description: Name of the user for the session.

children.name: session-id
children.description:
Identifier of the session.
A NETCONF session MUST be identified by a non-zero value.
A non-NETCONF session MAY be identified by the value zero.

children.name: source-host
children.description: Address of the remote host for the session.

children.name: netconf-session-end
children.description:
Generated when a NETCONF server detects that a
NETCONF session has terminated.
A server MAY optionally generate this event for
non-NETCONF management sessions.  Indicates the
identity of the user that owned the session,
and why the session was terminated.

children.name: username
children.description: Name of the user for the session.

children.name: session-id
children.description:
Identifier of the session.
A NETCONF session MUST be identified by a non-zero value.
A non-NETCONF session MAY be identified by the value zero.

children.name: source-host
children.description: Address of the remote host for the session.

children.name: killed-by
children.description:
The ID of the session that directly caused this session
to be abnormally terminated.  If this session was abnormally
terminated by a non-NETCONF session unknown to the server,
then this leaf will not be present.

children.name: termination-reason
children.description: Reason the session was terminated.

children.name: netconf-confirmed-commit
children.description:
Generated when a NETCONF server detects that a
confirmed-commit event has occurred.  Indicates the event
and the current state of the confirmed-commit procedure
in progress.
children.reference: RFC 6241, Section 8.4

children.name: username
children.description: Name of the user for the session.

children.name: session-id
children.description:
Identifier of the session.
A NETCONF session MUST be identified by a non-zero value.
A non-NETCONF session MAY be identified by the value zero.

children.name: source-host
children.description: Address of the remote host for the session.

children.name: confirm-event
children.description: Indicates the event that caused the notification.

children.name: timeout
children.description:
The configured timeout value if the event type
is 'start' or 'extend'.  This value represents
the approximate number of seconds from the event
time when the 'timeout' event might occur.
