children.name: networks
children.description: Serves as a top-level container for a list of networks.

children.name: network
children.description:
Describes a network.
A network typically contains an inventory of nodes,
topological information (augmented through the
network-topology data model), and layering information.

children.name: network-id
children.description: Identifies a network.

children.name: network-types
children.description:
Serves as an augmentation target.
The network type is indicated through corresponding
presence containers augmented into this container.

children.name: l3-unicast-topology
children.description:
The presence of the container node indicates L3 Unicast
topology

children.name: supporting-network
children.description:
An underlay network, used to represent layered network
topologies.

children.name: network-ref
children.description: References the underlay network.

children.name: node
children.description: The inventory of nodes of this network.

children.name: node-id
children.description:
Uniquely identifies a node within the containing
network.

children.name: supporting-node
children.description:
Represents another node that is in an underlay network
and that supports this node.  Used to represent layering
structure.

children.name: network-ref
children.description:
References the underlay network of which the
underlay node is a part.

children.name: node-ref
children.description: References the underlay node itself.

children.name: termination-point
children.description:
A termination point can terminate a link.
Depending on the type of topology, a termination point
could, for example, refer to a port or an interface.

children.name: tp-id
children.description: Termination point identifier.

children.name: supporting-termination-point
children.description:
This list identifies any termination points on which a
given termination point depends or onto which it maps.
Those termination points will themselves be contained
in a supporting node.  This dependency information can be
inferred from the dependencies between links.  Therefore,
this item is not separately configurable.  Hence, no
corresponding constraint needs to be articulated.
The corresponding information is simply provided by the
implementing system.

children.name: network-ref
children.description:
This leaf identifies in which topology the
supporting termination point is present.

children.name: node-ref
children.description:
This leaf identifies in which node the supporting
termination point is present.

children.name: tp-ref
children.description:
Reference to the underlay node (the underlay node must
be in a different topology).

children.name: l3-termination-point-attributes
children.description: Contains termination point attributes

children.name: termination-point-type
children.description: Indicates the termination point type

children.name: ip-address
children.description: IPv4 or IPv6 address.

children.name: unnumbered-id
children.description:
Unnumbered interface identifier.
The identifier will correspond to the ifIndex value
of the interface, i.e., the ifIndex value of the
ifEntry that represents the interface in
implementations where the Interfaces Group MIB
(RFC 2863) is supported.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB

children.name: interface-name
children.description:
Name of the interface.  The name can (but does not
have to) correspond to an interface reference of a
containing node's interface, i.e., the path name of a
corresponding interface data node on the containing
node reminiscent of data type interface-ref defined
in RFC 8343. It should be noted that data type
interface-ref of RFC 8343 cannot be used directly,

as this data type is used to reference an interface
in a datastore of a single node in the network, not
to uniquely reference interfaces across a network.
children.reference: RFC 8343: A YANG Data Model for Interface Management

children.name: l3-node-attributes
children.description: Contains node attributes

children.name: name
children.description: Node name

children.name: flag
children.description: Node flags

children.name: router-id
children.description: Router-id for the node

children.name: prefix
children.description: A list of prefixes along with their attributes

children.name: prefix
children.description: IP prefix value

children.name: metric
children.description: Prefix metric

children.name: flag
children.description: Prefix flags

children.name: link
children.description:
A network link connects a local (source) node and
a remote (destination) node via a set of the respective
node's termination points.  It is possible to have several
links between the same source and destination nodes.
Likewise, a link could potentially be re-homed between
termination points.  Therefore, in order to ensure that we
would always know to distinguish between links, every link
is identified by a dedicated link identifier.  Note that a
link models a point-to-point link, not a multipoint link.

children.name: link-id
children.description:
The identifier of a link in the topology.
A link is specific to a topology to which it belongs.

children.name: source
children.description:
This container holds the logical source of a particular
link.

children.name: source-node
children.description: Source node identifier.  Must be in the same topology.

children.name: source-tp
children.description:
This termination point is located within the source node
and terminates the link.

children.name: destination
children.description:
This container holds the logical destination of a
particular link.

children.name: dest-node
children.description:
Destination node identifier.  Must be in the same
network.

children.name: dest-tp
children.description:
This termination point is located within the
destination node and terminates the link.

children.name: supporting-link
children.description: Identifies the link or links on which this link depends.

children.name: network-ref
children.description:
This leaf identifies in which underlay topology
the supporting link is present.

children.name: link-ref
children.description:
This leaf identifies a link that is a part
of this link's underlay.  Reference loops in which
a link identifies itself as its underlay, either
directly or transitively, are not allowed.

children.name: l3-link-attributes
children.description: Contains link attributes

children.name: name
children.description: Link Name

modules.name: ietf-network-instance
modules.description:
This module is used to support multiple network instances
within a single physical or virtual device.  Network
instances are commonly known as VRFs (VPN Routing and
Forwarding) and VSIs (Virtual Switching Instances).

The key words 'MUST', 'MUST NOT', 'REQUIRED', 'SHALL',
'SHALL NOT', 'SHOULD', 'SHOULD NOT', 'RECOMMENDED',
'NOT RECOMMENDED', 'MAY', and 'OPTIONAL' in this document
are to be interpreted as described in BCP 14 (RFC 2119)
(RFC 8174) when, and only when, they appear in all capitals,
 as shown here.

authors of the code.  All rights reserved.

without modification, is permitted pursuant to, and subject
to the license terms contained in, the Simplified BSD
License set forth in Section 4.c of the IETF Trust's Legal
Provisions Relating to IETF Documents
(https://trustee.ietf.org/license-info).

the RFC itself for full legal notices.

Network instances, each of which consists of
VRFs and/or VSIs.

device-scoped identifier for the network
instance.

children.name: enabled
children.description:
Flag indicating whether or not the network
instance is enabled.

children.name: description
children.description:
Description of the network instance
and its intended purpose.

children.name: ni-type
children.description:
This node serves as an anchor point for different types
of network instances.  Each 'case' is expected to
differ in terms of the information needed in the
parent/core to support the NI and may differ in their
mounted-schema definition.  When the mounted schema is
not expected to be the same for a specific type of NI,
a mount point should be defined.

children.name: root-type
children.description: Well-known mount points.

children.name: vrf-root
children.description: Container for mount point.

children.name: vsi-root
children.description: Container for mount point.

children.name: vv-root
children.description: Container for mount point.

children.name: bind-ni-name-failed
children.description:
Indicates an error in the association of an interface to an
NI.  Only generated after success is initially returned when
bind-ni-name is set.

Note: Some errors may need to be reported for multiple
associations, e.g., a single error may need to be reported
for an IPv4 and an IPv6 bind-ni-name.

At least one container with a bind-ni-name leaf MUST be
included in this notification.

children.name: name
children.description:
Contains the interface name associated with the
failure.

children.name: interface
children.description: Generic interface type.

children.name: bind-ni-name
children.description:
Contains the bind-ni-name associated with the
failure.

children.name: ipv4
children.description: IPv4 interface type.

children.name: bind-ni-name
children.description:
Contains the bind-ni-name associated with the
failure.

children.name: ipv6
children.description: IPv6 interface type.

children.name: bind-ni-name
children.description:
Contains the bind-ni-name associated with the
failure.

children.name: error-info
children.description:
Optionally, indicates the source of the assignment
failure.

modules.name: ietf-network-state
modules.description:
This module defines a common base data model for a collection
of nodes in a network.  Node definitions are further used
in network topologies and inventories.  It represents
information that either (1) is learned and automatically
populated or (2) results from applying network information
that has been configured per the 'ietf-network' data model,
mirroring the corresponding data nodes in this data model.

The data model mirrors 'ietf-network' but contains only
read-only state data.  The data model is not needed when the
underlying implementation infrastructure supports the Network
Management Datastore Architecture (NMDA).

children.name: networks
children.description: Serves as a top-level container for a list of networks.

children.name: network
children.description:
Describes a network.
A network typically contains an inventory of nodes,
topological information (augmented through the
network-topology data model), and layering information.

children.name: network-types
children.description:
Serves as an augmentation target.
The network type is indicated through corresponding
presence containers augmented into this container.

children.name: l3-unicast-topology
children.description:
The presence of the container node indicates L3 Unicast
topology

children.name: network-id
children.description: Identifies a network.

children.name: supporting-network
children.description:
An underlay network, used to represent layered network
topologies.

children.name: network-ref
children.description: References the underlay network.

children.name: node
children.description: The inventory of nodes of this network.

children.name: node-id
children.description:
Uniquely identifies a node within the containing
network.

children.name: supporting-node
children.description:
Represents another node that is in an underlay network
and that supports this node.  Used to represent layering
structure.

children.name: network-ref
children.description:
References the underlay network of which the
underlay node is a part.

children.name: node-ref
children.description: References the underlay node itself.

children.name: termination-point
children.description:
A termination point can terminate a link.
Depending on the type of topology, a termination point
could, for example, refer to a port or an interface.

children.name: tp-id
children.description: Termination point identifier.

children.name: supporting-termination-point
children.description:
This list identifies any termination points on which a
given termination point depends or onto which it maps.
Those termination points will themselves be contained
in a supporting node.  This dependency information can be
inferred from the dependencies between links.  Therefore,
this item is not separately configurable.  Hence, no
corresponding constraint needs to be articulated.
The corresponding information is simply provided by the
implementing system.

children.name: network-ref
children.description:
This leaf identifies in which topology the
supporting termination point is present.

children.name: node-ref
children.description:
This leaf identifies in which node the supporting
termination point is present.

children.name: tp-ref
children.description:
Reference to the underlay node (the underlay node must
be in a different topology).

children.name: l3-termination-point-attributes
children.description: Contains termination point attributes

children.name: termination-point-type
children.description: Indicates the termination point type

children.name: ip-address
children.description: IPv4 or IPv6 address.

children.name: unnumbered-id
children.description:
Unnumbered interface identifier.
The identifier will correspond to the ifIndex value
of the interface, i.e., the ifIndex value of the
ifEntry that represents the interface in
implementations where the Interfaces Group MIB
(RFC 2863) is supported.
children.reference: RFC 2863: The Interfaces Group MIB

children.name: interface-name
children.description:
Name of the interface.  The name can (but does not
have to) correspond to an interface reference of a
containing node's interface, i.e., the path name of a
corresponding interface data node on the containing
node reminiscent of data type interface-ref defined
in RFC 8343. It should be noted that data type
interface-ref of RFC 8343 cannot be used directly,

as this data type is used to reference an interface
in a datastore of a single node in the network, not
to uniquely reference interfaces across a network.
children.reference: RFC 8343: A YANG Data Model for Interface Management

children.name: l3-node-attributes
children.description: Contains node attributes

children.name: name
children.description: Node name

children.name: flag
children.description: Node flags

children.name: router-id
children.description: Router-id for the node

children.name: prefix
children.description: A list of prefixes along with their attributes

children.name: prefix
children.description: IP prefix value

children.name: metric
children.description: Prefix metric

children.name: flag
children.description: Prefix flags

children.name: link
children.description:
A network link connects a local (source) node and
a remote (destination) node via a set of the respective
node's termination points.  It is possible to have several
links between the same source and destination nodes.
Likewise, a link could potentially be re-homed between
termination points.  Therefore, in order to ensure that we
would always know to distinguish between links, every link
is identified by a dedicated link identifier.  Note that a
link models a point-to-point link, not a multipoint link.

children.name: source
children.description:
This container holds the logical source of a particular
link.

children.name: source-node
children.description: Source node identifier.  Must be in the same topology.

children.name: source-tp
children.description:
This termination point is located within the source node
and terminates the link.

children.name: destination
children.description:
This container holds the logical destination of a
particular link.

children.name: dest-node
children.description:
Destination node identifier.  Must be in the same
network.

children.name: dest-tp
children.description:
This termination point is located within the
destination node and terminates the link.

children.name: link-id
children.description:
The identifier of a link in the topology.
A link is specific to a topology to which it belongs.

children.name: supporting-link
children.description: Identifies the link or links on which this link depends.

children.name: network-ref
children.description:
This leaf identifies in which underlay topology
the supporting link is present.

children.name: link-ref
children.description:
This leaf identifies a link that is a part
of this link's underlay.  Reference loops in which
a link identifies itself as its underlay, either
directly or transitively, are not allowed.

children.name: l3-link-attributes
children.description: Contains link attributes

children.name: name
children.description: Link Name

children.name: flag
children.description: Link flags

children.name: metric1
children.description: Link Metric 1

children.name: metric2
children.description: Link Metric 2

children.name: l3-topology-attributes
children.description: Contains topology attributes

children.name: name
children.description: Name of the topology

children.name: flag
children.description: Topology flags

modules.name: ietf-network-topology-state
modules.description:
This module defines a common base data model for network
topology state, representing topology that either (1) is learned
or (2) results from applying topology that has been configured
per the 'ietf-network-topology' data model, mirroring the
corresponding data nodes in this data model.  It augments the
base network state data model with links to connect nodes, as
well as termination points to terminate links on nodes.

The data model mirrors 'ietf-network-topology' but contains only
read-only state data.  The data model is not needed when the
underlying implementation infrastructure supports the Network
Management Datastore Architecture (NMDA).

children.name: capabilities
children.description: Contains a list of protocol capability URIs.

children.name: capability
children.description: A RESTCONF protocol capability URI.

children.name: streams
children.description:
Container representing the notification event streams
supported by the server.
children.reference: RFC 5277, Section 3.4, <streams> element.

children.name: stream
children.description:
Each entry describes an event stream supported by
the server.

children.name: name
children.description: The stream name.
children.reference: RFC 5277, Section 3.4, <name> element.

children.name: description
children.description: Description of stream content.
children.reference: RFC 5277, Section 3.4, <description> element.

children.name: replay-support
children.description:
Indicates if replay buffer is supported for this stream.
If 'true', then the server MUST support the 'start-time'
and 'stop-time' query parameters for this stream.
children.reference: RFC 5277, Section 3.4, <replaySupport> element.

children.name: replay-log-creation-time
children.description:
Indicates the time the replay log for this stream
was created.
children.reference:
RFC 5277, Section 3.4, <replayLogCreationTime>
element.

children.name: access
children.description:
The server will create an entry in this list for each
encoding format that is supported for this stream.
The media type 'text/event-stream' is expected
for all event streams.  This list identifies the
subtypes supported for this stream.

children.name: encoding
children.description:
This is the secondary encoding format within the
'text/event-stream' encoding used by all streams.
The type 'xml' is supported for XML encoding.
The type 'json' is supported for JSON encoding.

children.name: location
children.description:
Contains a URL that represents the entry point
for establishing notification delivery via
server-sent events.

some routing protocols identifying a router.

children.name: interfaces
children.description: Network-layer interfaces used for routing.

network-layer interface.

instance.

instance.

children.name: static-routes

Support for the 'static' pseudo-protocol.

Address-family-specific modules augment this node with
their lists of routes.

Support for a 'static' pseudo-protocol instance
consists of a list of routes.

children.name: destination-prefix

children.name: description

augments from other modules.

children.name: simple-next-hop
children.description:

next-hop address and/or outgoing interface.

Modules for address families MUST augment this case with a
leaf containing a next-hop address of that address
family.

children.name: outgoing-interface

children.name: next-hop-address

children.name: special-next-hop

children.name: next-hop-list

Modules for address families MUST augment this list
with a leaf containing a next-hop address of that
address family.

children.name: index
children.description:
A user-specified identifier utilized to uniquely
reference the next-hop entry in the next-hop list.
The value of this index has no semantic meaning
other than for referencing the entry.

children.name: outgoing-interface
children.description: Name of the outgoing interface.

children.name: next-hop-address

children.name: ipv6

children.name: description

children.name: next-hop

augments from other modules.

This case represents a simple next hop consisting of the
next-hop address and/or outgoing interface.

family.

children.name: outgoing-interface

children.name: next-hop-address
children.description: IPv6 address of the next hop.

children.name: special-next-hop
children.description: Options for special next hops.

children.name: next-hop-list

children.name: next-hop
children.description:
An entry in a next-hop list.

with a leaf containing a next-hop address of that
address family.

children.name: index
children.description:
A user-specified identifier utilized to uniquely
reference the next-hop entry in the next-hop list.
The value of this index has no semantic meaning
other than for referencing the entry.

children.name: outgoing-interface
children.description: Name of the outgoing interface.

children.name: next-hop-address
children.description: IPv6 address of the next hop.

children.name: ribs
children.description: Support for RIBs.

children.name: rib
children.description:
Each entry contains a configuration for a RIB identified
by the 'name' key.

Entries having the same key as a system-controlled entry
in the list '/routing/ribs/rib' are used for
configuring parameters of that entry.  Other entries
define additional user-controlled RIBs.

children.name: name
children.description:
The name of the RIB.

For system-controlled entries, the value of this leaf
must be the same as the name of the corresponding entry
in the operational state.

For user-controlled entries, an arbitrary name can be
used.

children.name: address-family
children.description: Address family.

children.name: default-rib
children.description:
This flag has the value of 'true' if and only if the RIB
is the default RIB for the given address family.

By default, control-plane protocols place their routes
in the default RIBs.

children.name: routes
children.description: Current contents of the RIB.

children.name: route
children.description:
A RIB route entry.  This data node MUST be augmented
with information specific to routes of each address
family.

children.name: route-preference
children.description:
This route attribute, also known as 'administrative
distance', allows for selecting the preferred route
among routes with the same destination prefix.  A
smaller value indicates a route that is
more preferred.

children.name: next-hop
children.description: Route's next-hop attribute.

children.name: next-hop-options
children.description:
Options for next hops.

It is expected that further cases will be added through
augments from other modules, e.g., for recursive
next hops.

children.name: simple-next-hop
children.description:
This case represents a simple next hop consisting of the
next-hop address and/or outgoing interface.

Modules for address families MUST augment this case with a
leaf containing a next-hop address of that address
family.

children.name: next-hop-address
children.description: IPv4 address of the next hop.

children.name: next-hop-address
children.description: IPv6 address of the next hop.

children.name: special-next-hop
children.description: Options for special next hops.

children.name: next-hop-list
children.description: Container for multiple next hops.

children.name: next-hop
children.description:

Modules for address families MUST augment this list
with a leaf containing a next-hop address of that
address family.

children.description: IPv6 address of the next hop.

children.name: source-protocol
children.description:

originated.

children.name: active
children.description:
The presence of this leaf indicates that the route is
preferred among all routes in the same RIB that have the
same destination prefix.

children.name: last-updated
children.description:

children.name: snmp
children.description:
Top-level container for SNMP-related configuration and
status objects.

children.name: engine
children.description: Configuration of the SNMP engine.

children.name: enabled
children.description: Enables the SNMP engine.

children.name: listen
children.description:
Configuration of the transport endpoints on which the
engine listens.

children.name: name
children.description: An arbitrary name for the list entry.

children.name: transport
children.description:
The transport-protocol-specific parameters for this
endpoint.  Submodules providing configuration for
additional transports are expected to augment this
choice.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine
listens.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 162.

children.name: tls
children.description:
A list of IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and ports to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over TLS.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over TLS.

children.name: port
children.description:
The TCP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over TLS.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.name: dtls
children.description:
A list of IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and ports to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over DTLS.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over DTLS.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over DTLS.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.name: ssh
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address and port to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over SSH.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over SSH.

children.name: port
children.description:
The TCP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over SSH.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 5161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 5162.

children.name: version
children.description: SNMP version used by the engine.

children.name: engine-id
children.description:
The local SNMP engine's administratively assigned unique
identifier.

If this leaf is not set, the device automatically
calculates an engine ID, as described in RFC 3411.  A
server MAY initialize this leaf with the automatically
created value.
children.reference:
RFC 3411: An Architecture for Describing Simple Network
  Management Protocol (SNMP) Management
  Frameworks.
  SNMP-FRAMEWORK-MIB.snmpEngineID

children.name: enable-authen-traps
children.description:
Indicates whether the SNMP entity is permitted to
generate authenticationFailure traps.
children.reference:
RFC 3418: Management Information Base (MIB) for the
  Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)
  SNMPv2-MIB.snmpEnableAuthenTraps

children.name: target
children.description: List of targets.
children.reference:
RFC 3413: Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)
  Applications.
  SNMP-TARGET-MIB.snmpTargetAddrTable

children.name: name
children.description: Identifies the target.
children.reference:
RFC 3413: Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)
  Applications.
  SNMP-TARGET-MIB.snmpTargetAddrName

children.name: transport
children.description:
Transport address of the target.

The snmpTargetAddrTDomain and snmpTargetAddrTAddress
objects are mapped to transport-specific YANG nodes.  Each
transport is configured as a separate case in this
choice.  Submodules providing configuration for additional
transports are expected to augment this choice.
children.reference:
RFC 3413: Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)
  Applications.
  SNMP-TARGET-MIB.snmpTargetAddrTDomain
  SNMP-TARGET-MIB.snmpTargetAddrTAddress

children.name: udp
children.reference:
RFC 3417: Transport Mappings for the Simple Network
  Management Protocol (SNMP).
  SNMPv2-TM.snmpUDPDomain
RFC 3419: Textual Conventions for Transport Addresses.
  TRANSPORT-ADDRESS-MIB.transportDomainUdpIpv4
  TRANSPORT-ADDRESS-MIB.transportDomainUdpIpv4z
  TRANSPORT-ADDRESS-MIB.transportDomainUdpIpv6
  TRANSPORT-ADDRESS-MIB.transportDomainUdpIpv6z

children.name: ip
children.reference:
RFC 3413: Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP).
  SNMP-TARGET-MIB.snmpTargetAddrTAddress

children.name: port
children.description: UDP port number.
children.reference:
RFC 3413: Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP).
  SNMP-TARGET-MIB.snmpTargetAddrTAddress

children.name: prefix-length
children.description:
The value of this leaf must match the value of
../snmp:ip.  If ../snmp:ip contains an IPv4 address,
this leaf must be less than or equal to 32.  If it
contains an IPv6 address, it must be less than or
equal to 128.

Note that the prefix-length is currently only used
by the Community-based Security Model to filter
incoming messages.  Furthermore, the prefix-length
filtering does not cover all possible filters
supported by the corresponding MIB object.

RFC 3584: Coexistence between Version 1, Version 2,

  Network Management Framework.
  SNMP-COMMUNITY-MIB.snmpTargetAddrTMask

children.name: params
children.description:

children.name: v1

Represents snmpTargetParamsMPModel '0',

children.description:

snmpTargetParamsSecurityLevel 'noAuthNoPriv'.

children.reference:

  Applications.

children.name: usm

children.name: cert-to-name
children.description:
This list defines how certificates are mapped to names.
The name is derived by considering each cert-to-name
list entry in order.  The cert-to-name entry's fingerprint
determines whether the list entry is a match:

1) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of the presented certificate, then consider
   the list entry a successful match.

2) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of a locally held copy of a trusted CA
   certificate, and that CA certificate was part of the CA
   certificate chain to the presented certificate, then
   consider the list entry a successful match.

Once a matching cert-to-name list entry has been found, the
map-type is used to determine how the name associated with
the certificate should be determined.  See the map-type
leaf's description for details on determining the name value.
If it is impossible to determine a name from the cert-to-name
list entry's data combined with the data presented in the
certificate, then additional cert-to-name list entries MUST
be searched to look for another potential match.

Security administrators are encouraged to make use of
certificates with subjectAltName fields that can be mapped to
names so that a single root CA certificate can allow all
child certificates' subjectAltName fields to map directly to
a name via a 1:1 transformation.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNEntry

children.name: id
children.description:
The id specifies the order in which the entries in the
cert-to-name list are searched.  Entries with lower
numbers are searched first.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNID

children.name: fingerprint
children.description:
Specifies a value with which the fingerprint of the
full certificate presented by the peer is compared.  If
the fingerprint of the full certificate presented by the
peer does not match the fingerprint configured, then the
entry is skipped, and the search for a match continues.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNFingerprint

children.name: map-type
children.description:
Mappings that use the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData column
need to augment the cert-to-name list with
additional configuration objects corresponding
to the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData value.  Such objects
should use the 'when' statement to make them
conditional based on the map-type.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNMapType

children.name: name
children.description:
Directly specifies the NETCONF username when the
map-type is 'specified'.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNData

children.name: snmp
children.description:
Top-level container for SNMP-related configuration and
status objects.

children.name: engine
children.description: Configuration of the SNMP engine.

children.name: enabled
children.description: Enables the SNMP engine.

children.name: listen
children.description:
Configuration of the transport endpoints on which the
engine listens.

children.name: name
children.description: An arbitrary name for the list entry.

children.name: transport
children.description:
The transport-protocol-specific parameters for this
endpoint.  Submodules providing configuration for
additional transports are expected to augment this
choice.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine
listens.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 162.

children.name: tls
children.description:
A list of IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and ports to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over TLS.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over TLS.

children.name: port
children.description:
The TCP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over TLS.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.name: dtls
children.description:
A list of IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and ports to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over DTLS.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over DTLS.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over DTLS.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.name: ssh
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address and port to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over SSH.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over SSH.

children.name: port
children.description:
The TCP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over SSH.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 5161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 5162.

children.name: version

children.name: cert-to-name
children.description:
This list defines how certificates are mapped to names.
The name is derived by considering each cert-to-name
list entry in order.  The cert-to-name entry's fingerprint
determines whether the list entry is a match:

1) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of the presented certificate, then consider
   the list entry a successful match.

2) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of a locally held copy of a trusted CA
   certificate, and that CA certificate was part of the CA
   certificate chain to the presented certificate, then
   consider the list entry a successful match.

Once a matching cert-to-name list entry has been found, the
map-type is used to determine how the name associated with
the certificate should be determined.  See the map-type
leaf's description for details on determining the name value.
If it is impossible to determine a name from the cert-to-name
list entry's data combined with the data presented in the
certificate, then additional cert-to-name list entries MUST
be searched to look for another potential match.

Security administrators are encouraged to make use of
certificates with subjectAltName fields that can be mapped to
names so that a single root CA certificate can allow all
child certificates' subjectAltName fields to map directly to
a name via a 1:1 transformation.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNEntry

children.name: id
children.description:
The id specifies the order in which the entries in the
cert-to-name list are searched.  Entries with lower
numbers are searched first.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNID

children.name: fingerprint
children.description:
Specifies a value with which the fingerprint of the
full certificate presented by the peer is compared.  If
the fingerprint of the full certificate presented by the
peer does not match the fingerprint configured, then the
entry is skipped, and the search for a match continues.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNFingerprint

children.name: map-type
children.description:
Mappings that use the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData column
need to augment the cert-to-name list with
additional configuration objects corresponding
to the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData value.  Such objects
should use the 'when' statement to make them
conditional based on the map-type.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNMapType

children.name: name
children.description:
Directly specifies the NETCONF username when the
map-type is 'specified'.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNData

children.name: snmp
children.description:
Top-level container for SNMP-related configuration and
status objects.

children.name: engine
children.description: Configuration of the SNMP engine.

children.name: enabled
children.description: Enables the SNMP engine.

children.name: listen
children.description:
Configuration of the transport endpoints on which the
engine listens.

children.name: name
children.description: An arbitrary name for the list entry.

children.name: transport
children.description:
The transport-protocol-specific parameters for this
endpoint.  Submodules providing configuration for
additional transports are expected to augment this
choice.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine
listens.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 162.

children.name: tls
children.description:
A list of IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and ports to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over TLS.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over TLS.

children.name: port
children.description:
The TCP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over TLS.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.name: dtls
children.description:
A list of IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and ports to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over DTLS.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over DTLS.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over DTLS.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.name: ssh
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address and port to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over SSH.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over SSH.

children.name: port
children.description:
The TCP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over SSH.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 5161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 5162.

children.name: version
children.description: SNMP version used by the engine.

children.name: engine-id
children.description:
The local SNMP engine's administratively assigned unique
identifier.

If this leaf is not set, the device automatically
calculates an engine ID, as described in RFC 3411.  A
server MAY initialize this leaf with the automatically
created value.

children.name: prefix-length
children.description:
The value of this leaf must match the value of
../snmp:ip.  If ../snmp:ip contains an IPv4 address,
this leaf must be less than or equal to 32.  If it
contains an IPv6 address, it must be less than or
equal to 128.

Note that the prefix-length is currently only used
by the Community-based Security Model to filter
incoming messages.  Furthermore, the prefix-length
filtering does not cover all possible filters
supported by the corresponding MIB object.

children.name: cert-to-name
children.description:
This list defines how certificates are mapped to names.
The name is derived by considering each cert-to-name
list entry in order.  The cert-to-name entry's fingerprint
determines whether the list entry is a match:

1) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of the presented certificate, then consider
   the list entry a successful match.

2) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of a locally held copy of a trusted CA
   certificate, and that CA certificate was part of the CA
   certificate chain to the presented certificate, then
   consider the list entry a successful match.

Once a matching cert-to-name list entry has been found, the
map-type is used to determine how the name associated with
the certificate should be determined.  See the map-type
leaf's description for details on determining the name value.
If it is impossible to determine a name from the cert-to-name
list entry's data combined with the data presented in the
certificate, then additional cert-to-name list entries MUST
be searched to look for another potential match.

Security administrators are encouraged to make use of
certificates with subjectAltName fields that can be mapped to
names so that a single root CA certificate can allow all
child certificates' subjectAltName fields to map directly to
a name via a 1:1 transformation.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNEntry

children.name: id
children.description:
The id specifies the order in which the entries in the
cert-to-name list are searched.  Entries with lower
numbers are searched first.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNID

children.name: fingerprint
children.description:
Specifies a value with which the fingerprint of the
full certificate presented by the peer is compared.  If
the fingerprint of the full certificate presented by the
peer does not match the fingerprint configured, then the
entry is skipped, and the search for a match continues.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNFingerprint

children.name: map-type
children.description:
Mappings that use the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData column
need to augment the cert-to-name list with
additional configuration objects corresponding
to the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData value.  Such objects
should use the 'when' statement to make them
conditional based on the map-type.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNMapType

children.name: name
children.description:
Directly specifies the NETCONF username when the
map-type is 'specified'.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNData

children.name: snmp
children.description:
Top-level container for SNMP-related configuration and
status objects.

children.name: engine
children.description: Configuration of the SNMP engine.

children.name: enabled
children.description: Enables the SNMP engine.

children.name: listen
children.description:
Configuration of the transport endpoints on which the
engine listens.

children.name: name
children.description: An arbitrary name for the list entry.

children.name: transport
children.description:
The transport-protocol-specific parameters for this
endpoint.  Submodules providing configuration for
additional transports are expected to augment this
choice.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine
listens.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 162.

children.name: tls
children.description:
A list of IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and ports to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over TLS.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over TLS.

children.name: port
children.description:
The TCP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over TLS.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.name: dtls
children.description:
A list of IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and ports to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over DTLS.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over DTLS.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over DTLS.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.name: ssh
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address and port to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over SSH.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over SSH.

children.name: port
children.description:
The TCP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over SSH.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 5161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 5162.

children.name: version
children.description: SNMP version used by the engine.

children.name: engine-id
children.description:
The local SNMP engine's administratively assigned unique
identifier.

If this leaf is not set, the device automatically
calculates an engine ID, as described in RFC 3411.  A
server MAY initialize this leaf with the automatically
created value.

children.name: prefix-length
children.description:
The value of this leaf must match the value of
../snmp:ip.  If ../snmp:ip contains an IPv4 address,
this leaf must be less than or equal to 32.  If it
contains an IPv6 address, it must be less than or
equal to 128.

Note that the prefix-length is currently only used
by the Community-based Security Model to filter
incoming messages.  Furthermore, the prefix-length
filtering does not cover all possible filters
supported by the corresponding MIB object.

children.name: cert-to-name
children.description:
This list defines how certificates are mapped to names.
The name is derived by considering each cert-to-name
list entry in order.  The cert-to-name entry's fingerprint
determines whether the list entry is a match:

1) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of the presented certificate, then consider
   the list entry a successful match.

2) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of a locally held copy of a trusted CA
   certificate, and that CA certificate was part of the CA
   certificate chain to the presented certificate, then
   consider the list entry a successful match.

Once a matching cert-to-name list entry has been found, the
map-type is used to determine how the name associated with
the certificate should be determined.  See the map-type
leaf's description for details on determining the name value.
If it is impossible to determine a name from the cert-to-name
list entry's data combined with the data presented in the
certificate, then additional cert-to-name list entries MUST
be searched to look for another potential match.

Security administrators are encouraged to make use of
certificates with subjectAltName fields that can be mapped to
names so that a single root CA certificate can allow all
child certificates' subjectAltName fields to map directly to
a name via a 1:1 transformation.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNEntry

children.name: id
children.description:
The id specifies the order in which the entries in the
cert-to-name list are searched.  Entries with lower
numbers are searched first.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNID

children.name: fingerprint
children.description:
Specifies a value with which the fingerprint of the
full certificate presented by the peer is compared.  If
the fingerprint of the full certificate presented by the
peer does not match the fingerprint configured, then the
entry is skipped, and the search for a match continues.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNFingerprint

children.name: map-type
children.description:
Mappings that use the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData column
need to augment the cert-to-name list with
additional configuration objects corresponding
to the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData value.  Such objects
should use the 'when' statement to make them
conditional based on the map-type.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNMapType

children.name: name
children.description:
Directly specifies the NETCONF username when the
map-type is 'specified'.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNData

children.description:
Top-level container for SNMP-related configuration and
status objects.

children.name: engine
children.description: Configuration of the SNMP engine.

children.name: enabled
children.description: Enables the SNMP engine.

children.name: listen
children.description:
Configuration of the transport endpoints on which the
engine listens.

children.name: name
children.description: An arbitrary name for the list entry.

children.name: transport
children.description:
The transport-protocol-specific parameters for this
endpoint.  Submodules providing configuration for
additional transports are expected to augment this
choice.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine
listens.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 162.

children.name: tls
children.description:
A list of IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and ports to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over TLS.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over TLS.

children.name: port
children.description:
The TCP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over TLS.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.name: dtls
children.description:
A list of IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and ports to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over DTLS.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over DTLS.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over DTLS.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.name: ssh
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address and port to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over SSH.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over SSH.

children.name: port
children.description:
The TCP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over SSH.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 5161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 5162.

children.name: version
children.description: SNMP version used by the engine.

children.name: engine-id
children.description:
The local SNMP engine's administratively assigned unique
identifier.

If this leaf is not set, the device automatically
calculates an engine ID, as described in RFC 3411.  A
server MAY initialize this leaf with the automatically
created value.
children.reference:
RFC 3411: An Architecture for Describing Simple Network
  Management Protocol (SNMP) Management
  Frameworks.
  SNMP-FRAMEWORK-MIB.snmpEngineID

children.name: enable-authen-traps
children.description:
Indicates whether the SNMP entity is permitted to
generate authenticationFailure traps.

children.name: prefix-length
children.description:
The value of this leaf must match the value of
../snmp:ip.  If ../snmp:ip contains an IPv4 address,
this leaf must be less than or equal to 32.  If it
contains an IPv6 address, it must be less than or
equal to 128.

Note that the prefix-length is currently only used
by the Community-based Security Model to filter
incoming messages.  Furthermore, the prefix-length
filtering does not cover all possible filters
supported by the corresponding MIB object.

notify-filter-profile is represented by one
snmpNotifyFilterProfileEntry.

If an entry in this list is not referred to by any
/snmp/target/notify-filter-profile, the entry is not mapped
to snmpNotifyFilterProfileTable.

children.name: cert-to-name
children.description:
This list defines how certificates are mapped to names.
The name is derived by considering each cert-to-name
list entry in order.  The cert-to-name entry's fingerprint
determines whether the list entry is a match:

1) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of the presented certificate, then consider
   the list entry a successful match.

2) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of a locally held copy of a trusted CA
   certificate, and that CA certificate was part of the CA
   certificate chain to the presented certificate, then
   consider the list entry a successful match.

Once a matching cert-to-name list entry has been found, the
map-type is used to determine how the name associated with
the certificate should be determined.  See the map-type
leaf's description for details on determining the name value.
If it is impossible to determine a name from the cert-to-name
list entry's data combined with the data presented in the
certificate, then additional cert-to-name list entries MUST
be searched to look for another potential match.

Security administrators are encouraged to make use of
certificates with subjectAltName fields that can be mapped to
names so that a single root CA certificate can allow all
child certificates' subjectAltName fields to map directly to
a name via a 1:1 transformation.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNEntry

children.name: id
children.description:
The id specifies the order in which the entries in the
cert-to-name list are searched.  Entries with lower
numbers are searched first.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNID

children.name: fingerprint
children.description:
Specifies a value with which the fingerprint of the
full certificate presented by the peer is compared.  If
the fingerprint of the full certificate presented by the
peer does not match the fingerprint configured, then the
entry is skipped, and the search for a match continues.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNFingerprint

children.name: map-type
children.description:
Mappings that use the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData column
need to augment the cert-to-name list with
additional configuration objects corresponding
to the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData value.  Such objects
should use the 'when' statement to make them
conditional based on the map-type.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNMapType

children.name: name
children.description:
Directly specifies the NETCONF username when the
map-type is 'specified'.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNData

children.name: snmp
children.description:
Top-level container for SNMP-related configuration and
status objects.

children.name: engine
children.description: Configuration of the SNMP engine.

children.name: enabled
children.description: Enables the SNMP engine.

children.name: listen
children.description:
Configuration of the transport endpoints on which the
engine listens.

children.name: name
children.description: An arbitrary name for the list entry.

children.name: transport
children.description:
The transport-protocol-specific parameters for this
endpoint.  Submodules providing configuration for
additional transports are expected to augment this
choice.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine
listens.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 162.

children.name: tls
children.description:
A list of IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and ports to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over TLS.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over TLS.

children.name: port
children.description:
The TCP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over TLS.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.name: dtls
children.description:
A list of IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and ports to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over DTLS.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over DTLS.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over DTLS.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.name: ssh
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address and port to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over SSH.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over SSH.

children.name: port
children.description:
The TCP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over SSH.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 5161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 5162.

children.name: version
children.description: SNMP version used by the engine.

children.name: engine-id
children.description:
The local SNMP engine's administratively assigned unique
identifier.

If this leaf is not set, the device automatically
calculates an engine ID, as described in RFC 3411.  A
server MAY initialize this leaf with the automatically
created value.

children.name: prefix-length
children.description:
The value of this leaf must match the value of
../snmp:ip.  If ../snmp:ip contains an IPv4 address,
this leaf must be less than or equal to 32.  If it
contains an IPv6 address, it must be less than or
equal to 128.

Note that the prefix-length is currently only used
by the Community-based Security Model to filter
incoming messages.  Furthermore, the prefix-length
filtering does not cover all possible filters
supported by the corresponding MIB object.

children.name: cert-to-name
children.description:
This list defines how certificates are mapped to names.
The name is derived by considering each cert-to-name
list entry in order.  The cert-to-name entry's fingerprint
determines whether the list entry is a match:

1) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of the presented certificate, then consider
   the list entry a successful match.

2) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of a locally held copy of a trusted CA
   certificate, and that CA certificate was part of the CA
   certificate chain to the presented certificate, then
   consider the list entry a successful match.

Once a matching cert-to-name list entry has been found, the
map-type is used to determine how the name associated with
the certificate should be determined.  See the map-type
leaf's description for details on determining the name value.
If it is impossible to determine a name from the cert-to-name
list entry's data combined with the data presented in the
certificate, then additional cert-to-name list entries MUST
be searched to look for another potential match.

Security administrators are encouraged to make use of
certificates with subjectAltName fields that can be mapped to
names so that a single root CA certificate can allow all
child certificates' subjectAltName fields to map directly to
a name via a 1:1 transformation.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNEntry

children.name: id
children.description:
The id specifies the order in which the entries in the
cert-to-name list are searched.  Entries with lower
numbers are searched first.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNID

children.name: fingerprint
children.description:
Specifies a value with which the fingerprint of the
full certificate presented by the peer is compared.  If
the fingerprint of the full certificate presented by the
peer does not match the fingerprint configured, then the
entry is skipped, and the search for a match continues.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNFingerprint

children.name: map-type
children.description:
Mappings that use the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData column
need to augment the cert-to-name list with
additional configuration objects corresponding
to the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData value.  Such objects
should use the 'when' statement to make them
conditional based on the map-type.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNMapType

children.description:
Directly specifies the NETCONF username when the

  (SNMP).

children.description:
The transport-protocol-specific parameters for this
endpoint.  Submodules providing configuration for

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine
listens.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 162.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.name: prefix-length
children.description:
The value of this leaf must match the value of
../snmp:ip.  If ../snmp:ip contains an IPv4 address,
this leaf must be less than or equal to 32.  If it
contains an IPv6 address, it must be less than or
equal to 128.

Note that the prefix-length is currently only used
by the Community-based Security Model to filter
incoming messages.  Furthermore, the prefix-length
filtering does not cover all possible filters
supported by the corresponding MIB object.

children.name: cert-to-name
children.description:
This list defines how certificates are mapped to names.
The name is derived by considering each cert-to-name
list entry in order.  The cert-to-name entry's fingerprint
determines whether the list entry is a match:

1) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of the presented certificate, then consider
   the list entry a successful match.

2) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of a locally held copy of a trusted CA
   certificate, and that CA certificate was part of the CA
   certificate chain to the presented certificate, then
   consider the list entry a successful match.

Once a matching cert-to-name list entry has been found, the
map-type is used to determine how the name associated with
the certificate should be determined.  See the map-type
leaf's description for details on determining the name value.
If it is impossible to determine a name from the cert-to-name
list entry's data combined with the data presented in the
certificate, then additional cert-to-name list entries MUST
be searched to look for another potential match.

Security administrators are encouraged to make use of
certificates with subjectAltName fields that can be mapped to
names so that a single root CA certificate can allow all
child certificates' subjectAltName fields to map directly to
a name via a 1:1 transformation.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNEntry

children.name: id
children.description:
The id specifies the order in which the entries in the
cert-to-name list are searched.  Entries with lower
numbers are searched first.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).

children.name: fingerprint
children.description:
Specifies a value with which the fingerprint of the
full certificate presented by the peer is compared.  If
the fingerprint of the full certificate presented by the
peer does not match the fingerprint configured, then the
entry is skipped, and the search for a match continues.

  (SNMP).

children.name: map-type
children.description:
Mappings that use the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData column
need to augment the cert-to-name list with
additional configuration objects corresponding
to the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData value.  Such objects
should use the 'when' statement to make them
conditional based on the map-type.

  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).

children.description:

map-type is 'specified'.

  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).

children.name: snmp
children.description:
Top-level container for SNMP-related configuration and
status objects.

children.name: engine
children.description: Configuration of the SNMP engine.

children.name: enabled
children.description: Enables the SNMP engine.

children.name: listen
children.description:
Configuration of the transport endpoints on which the
engine listens.

children.name: name
children.description: An arbitrary name for the list entry.

children.name: transport
children.description:
The transport-protocol-specific parameters for this
endpoint.  Submodules providing configuration for
additional transports are expected to augment this
choice.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine
listens.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 162.

children.name: tls
children.description:
A list of IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and ports to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over TLS.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over TLS.

children.name: port
children.description:
The TCP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over TLS.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.name: dtls
children.description:
A list of IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and ports to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over DTLS.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over DTLS.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over DTLS.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.name: ssh
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address and port to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over SSH.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over SSH.

children.name: port
children.description:
The TCP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over SSH.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 5161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 5162.

children.name: version
children.description: SNMP version used by the engine.

children.name: engine-id
children.description:
The local SNMP engine's administratively assigned unique
identifier.

If this leaf is not set, the device automatically
calculates an engine ID, as described in RFC 3411.  A
server MAY initialize this leaf with the automatically
created value.

  Frameworks.

children.name: prefix-length
children.description:
The value of this leaf must match the value of
../snmp:ip.  If ../snmp:ip contains an IPv4 address,
this leaf must be less than or equal to 32.  If it
contains an IPv6 address, it must be less than or
equal to 128.

Note that the prefix-length is currently only used
by the Community-based Security Model to filter
incoming messages.  Furthermore, the prefix-length
filtering does not cover all possible filters
supported by the corresponding MIB object.

children.name: cert-to-name
children.description:
This list defines how certificates are mapped to names.
The name is derived by considering each cert-to-name
list entry in order.  The cert-to-name entry's fingerprint
determines whether the list entry is a match:

1) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of the presented certificate, then consider
   the list entry a successful match.

2) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of a locally held copy of a trusted CA
   certificate, and that CA certificate was part of the CA
   certificate chain to the presented certificate, then
   consider the list entry a successful match.

Once a matching cert-to-name list entry has been found, the
map-type is used to determine how the name associated with
the certificate should be determined.  See the map-type
leaf's description for details on determining the name value.
If it is impossible to determine a name from the cert-to-name
list entry's data combined with the data presented in the
certificate, then additional cert-to-name list entries MUST
be searched to look for another potential match.

Security administrators are encouraged to make use of
certificates with subjectAltName fields that can be mapped to
names so that a single root CA certificate can allow all
child certificates' subjectAltName fields to map directly to
a name via a 1:1 transformation.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNEntry

children.name: id
children.description:
The id specifies the order in which the entries in the
cert-to-name list are searched.  Entries with lower
numbers are searched first.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNID

children.name: fingerprint
children.description:
Specifies a value with which the fingerprint of the
full certificate presented by the peer is compared.  If
the fingerprint of the full certificate presented by the
peer does not match the fingerprint configured, then the
entry is skipped, and the search for a match continues.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNFingerprint

children.name: map-type
children.description:
Mappings that use the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData column
need to augment the cert-to-name list with
additional configuration objects corresponding
to the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData value.  Such objects
should use the 'when' statement to make them
conditional based on the map-type.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNMapType

children.name: name
children.description:
Directly specifies the NETCONF username when the
map-type is 'specified'.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNData

children.name: snmp
children.description:

status objects.

children.description: Configuration of the SNMP engine.

children.name: enabled
children.description: Enables the SNMP engine.

children.name: listen
children.description:
Configuration of the transport endpoints on which the
engine listens.

children.name: name
children.description: An arbitrary name for the list entry.

children.name: transport
children.description:
The transport-protocol-specific parameters for this
endpoint.  Submodules providing configuration for
additional transports are expected to augment this
choice.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine
listens.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 162.

children.name: tls
children.description:
A list of IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and ports to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over TLS.

children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over TLS.

children.name: port
children.description:
The TCP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over TLS.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.description:

engine listens for SNMP messages over DTLS.

children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over DTLS.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over DTLS.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.name: ssh
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address and port to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over SSH.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over SSH.

children.name: port
children.description:
