If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 5161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 5162.

children.name: version
children.description: SNMP version used by the engine.

children.name: engine-id
children.description:

If this leaf is not set, the device automatically

children.name: prefix-length
children.description:
The value of this leaf must match the value of
../snmp:ip.  If ../snmp:ip contains an IPv4 address,
this leaf must be less than or equal to 32.  If it
contains an IPv6 address, it must be less than or
equal to 128.

Note that the prefix-length is currently only used
by the Community-based Security Model to filter
incoming messages.  Furthermore, the prefix-length
filtering does not cover all possible filters
supported by the corresponding MIB object.

children.name: cert-to-name
children.description:
This list defines how certificates are mapped to names.
The name is derived by considering each cert-to-name
list entry in order.  The cert-to-name entry's fingerprint
determines whether the list entry is a match:

1) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of the presented certificate, then consider
   the list entry a successful match.

2) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of a locally held copy of a trusted CA
   certificate, and that CA certificate was part of the CA
   certificate chain to the presented certificate, then
   consider the list entry a successful match.

Once a matching cert-to-name list entry has been found, the
map-type is used to determine how the name associated with
the certificate should be determined.  See the map-type
leaf's description for details on determining the name value.
If it is impossible to determine a name from the cert-to-name
list entry's data combined with the data presented in the
certificate, then additional cert-to-name list entries MUST
be searched to look for another potential match.

Security administrators are encouraged to make use of
certificates with subjectAltName fields that can be mapped to
names so that a single root CA certificate can allow all
child certificates' subjectAltName fields to map directly to
a name via a 1:1 transformation.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNEntry

children.name: id
children.description:
The id specifies the order in which the entries in the
cert-to-name list are searched.  Entries with lower
numbers are searched first.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNID

children.name: fingerprint
children.description:
Specifies a value with which the fingerprint of the
full certificate presented by the peer is compared.  If
the fingerprint of the full certificate presented by the
peer does not match the fingerprint configured, then the
entry is skipped, and the search for a match continues.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNFingerprint

children.name: map-type
children.description:
Mappings that use the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData column
need to augment the cert-to-name list with
additional configuration objects corresponding
to the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData value.  Such objects
should use the 'when' statement to make them
conditional based on the map-type.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNMapType

children.name: name
children.description:
Directly specifies the NETCONF username when the
map-type is 'specified'.
children.reference:

  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).

children.name: snmp
children.description:
Top-level container for SNMP-related configuration and
status objects.

children.name: engine
children.description: Configuration of the SNMP engine.

children.name: enabled
children.description: Enables the SNMP engine.

children.name: listen
children.description:
Configuration of the transport endpoints on which the
engine listens.

children.name: name
children.description: An arbitrary name for the list entry.

children.name: transport
children.description:
The transport-protocol-specific parameters for this
endpoint.  Submodules providing configuration for
additional transports are expected to augment this
choice.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine
listens.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 162.

children.name: tls
children.description:
A list of IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and ports to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over TLS.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over TLS.

children.name: port
children.description:
The TCP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over TLS.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.name: dtls
children.description:
A list of IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and ports to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over DTLS.

children.name: ip
children.description:

for SNMP messages over DTLS.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over DTLS.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.name: ssh
children.description:

engine listens for SNMP messages over SSH.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over SSH.

children.name: port
children.description:
The TCP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over SSH.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 5161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 5162.

children.name: version
children.description: SNMP version used by the engine.

children.name: engine-id
children.description:
The local SNMP engine's administratively assigned unique
identifier.

If this leaf is not set, the device automatically
calculates an engine ID, as described in RFC 3411.  A
server MAY initialize this leaf with the automatically
created value.

children.name: cert-to-name
children.description:
This list defines how certificates are mapped to names.
The name is derived by considering each cert-to-name
list entry in order.  The cert-to-name entry's fingerprint
determines whether the list entry is a match:

1) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of the presented certificate, then consider
   the list entry a successful match.

2) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of a locally held copy of a trusted CA
   certificate, and that CA certificate was part of the CA
   certificate chain to the presented certificate, then
   consider the list entry a successful match.

Once a matching cert-to-name list entry has been found, the
map-type is used to determine how the name associated with
the certificate should be determined.  See the map-type
leaf's description for details on determining the name value.
If it is impossible to determine a name from the cert-to-name
list entry's data combined with the data presented in the
certificate, then additional cert-to-name list entries MUST
be searched to look for another potential match.

Security administrators are encouraged to make use of
certificates with subjectAltName fields that can be mapped to
names so that a single root CA certificate can allow all
child certificates' subjectAltName fields to map directly to
a name via a 1:1 transformation.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNEntry

children.name: id
children.description:
The id specifies the order in which the entries in the
cert-to-name list are searched.  Entries with lower
numbers are searched first.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNID

children.name: fingerprint
children.description:
Specifies a value with which the fingerprint of the
full certificate presented by the peer is compared.  If
the fingerprint of the full certificate presented by the
peer does not match the fingerprint configured, then the
entry is skipped, and the search for a match continues.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNFingerprint

children.name: map-type
children.description:
Mappings that use the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData column
need to augment the cert-to-name list with
additional configuration objects corresponding
to the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData value.  Such objects
should use the 'when' statement to make them
conditional based on the map-type.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNMapType

children.name: name
children.description:
Directly specifies the NETCONF username when the
map-type is 'specified'.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNData

children.description:

children.description: An arbitrary name for the list entry.

children.description:
The transport-protocol-specific parameters for this
endpoint.  Submodules providing configuration for
additional transports are expected to augment this
choice.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine
listens.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 162.

children.description:
A list of IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and ports to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over TLS.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over TLS.

children.name: port
children.description:
The TCP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over TLS.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.name: dtls
children.description:
A list of IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and ports to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over DTLS.

children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over DTLS.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over DTLS.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.name: ssh
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address and port to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over SSH.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over SSH.

children.name: port
children.description:
The TCP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over SSH.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 5161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 5162.

children.name: version
children.description: SNMP version used by the engine.

children.name: engine-id
children.description:
The local SNMP engine's administratively assigned unique
identifier.

If this leaf is not set, the device automatically
calculates an engine ID, as described in RFC 3411.  A
server MAY initialize this leaf with the automatically
created value.

children.name: prefix-length
children.description:
The value of this leaf must match the value of
../snmp:ip.  If ../snmp:ip contains an IPv4 address,
this leaf must be less than or equal to 32.  If it
contains an IPv6 address, it must be less than or
equal to 128.

Note that the prefix-length is currently only used
by the Community-based Security Model to filter
incoming messages.  Furthermore, the prefix-length
filtering does not cover all possible filters
supported by the corresponding MIB object.

children.name: cert-to-name
children.description:
This list defines how certificates are mapped to names.
The name is derived by considering each cert-to-name
list entry in order.  The cert-to-name entry's fingerprint
determines whether the list entry is a match:

1) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of the presented certificate, then consider
   the list entry a successful match.

2) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of a locally held copy of a trusted CA
   certificate, and that CA certificate was part of the CA
   certificate chain to the presented certificate, then
   consider the list entry a successful match.

Once a matching cert-to-name list entry has been found, the
map-type is used to determine how the name associated with
the certificate should be determined.  See the map-type
leaf's description for details on determining the name value.
If it is impossible to determine a name from the cert-to-name
list entry's data combined with the data presented in the
certificate, then additional cert-to-name list entries MUST
be searched to look for another potential match.

Security administrators are encouraged to make use of
certificates with subjectAltName fields that can be mapped to
names so that a single root CA certificate can allow all
child certificates' subjectAltName fields to map directly to
a name via a 1:1 transformation.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNEntry

children.name: id
children.description:
The id specifies the order in which the entries in the
cert-to-name list are searched.  Entries with lower
numbers are searched first.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNID

children.name: fingerprint
children.description:
Specifies a value with which the fingerprint of the
full certificate presented by the peer is compared.  If
the fingerprint of the full certificate presented by the
peer does not match the fingerprint configured, then the
entry is skipped, and the search for a match continues.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNFingerprint

children.name: map-type
children.description:
Mappings that use the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData column
need to augment the cert-to-name list with
additional configuration objects corresponding
to the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData value.  Such objects
should use the 'when' statement to make them
conditional based on the map-type.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNMapType

children.name: name
children.description:
Directly specifies the NETCONF username when the
map-type is 'specified'.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNData

children.name: snmp

Top-level container for SNMP-related configuration and
status objects.

children.description: Enables the SNMP engine.

children.description:
Configuration of the transport endpoints on which the
engine listens.

children.name: name
children.description: An arbitrary name for the list entry.

children.name: transport
children.description:
The transport-protocol-specific parameters for this
endpoint.  Submodules providing configuration for
additional transports are expected to augment this
choice.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine
listens.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 162.

children.name: tls
children.description:
A list of IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and ports to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over TLS.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over TLS.

children.name: port
children.description:
The TCP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over TLS.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.description:
A list of IPv4 and IPv6 addresses and ports to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over DTLS.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over DTLS.

children.name: port
children.description:
The UDP port on which the engine listens for SNMP
messages over DTLS.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 10161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 10162.

children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address and port to which the
engine listens for SNMP messages over SSH.

children.name: ip
children.description:
The IPv4 or IPv6 address on which the engine listens
for SNMP messages over SSH.

children.name: port
children.description:

messages over SSH.

If the port is not configured, an engine that
acts as a Command Responder uses port 5161, and
an engine that acts as a Notification Receiver
uses port 5162.

children.name: version
children.description: SNMP version used by the engine.

children.name: engine-id
children.description:

identifier.

If this leaf is not set, the device automatically
calculates an engine ID, as described in RFC 3411.  A
server MAY initialize this leaf with the automatically
created value.

children.name: prefix-length
children.description:
The value of this leaf must match the value of
../snmp:ip.  If ../snmp:ip contains an IPv4 address,
this leaf must be less than or equal to 32.  If it
contains an IPv6 address, it must be less than or
equal to 128.

Note that the prefix-length is currently only used
by the Community-based Security Model to filter
incoming messages.  Furthermore, the prefix-length
filtering does not cover all possible filters
supported by the corresponding MIB object.

children.name: cert-to-name
children.description:
This list defines how certificates are mapped to names.
The name is derived by considering each cert-to-name
list entry in order.  The cert-to-name entry's fingerprint
determines whether the list entry is a match:

1) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of the presented certificate, then consider
   the list entry a successful match.

2) If the cert-to-name list entry's fingerprint value
   matches that of a locally held copy of a trusted CA
   certificate, and that CA certificate was part of the CA
   certificate chain to the presented certificate, then
   consider the list entry a successful match.

Once a matching cert-to-name list entry has been found, the
map-type is used to determine how the name associated with
the certificate should be determined.  See the map-type
leaf's description for details on determining the name value.
If it is impossible to determine a name from the cert-to-name
list entry's data combined with the data presented in the
certificate, then additional cert-to-name list entries MUST
be searched to look for another potential match.

Security administrators are encouraged to make use of
certificates with subjectAltName fields that can be mapped to
names so that a single root CA certificate can allow all
child certificates' subjectAltName fields to map directly to
a name via a 1:1 transformation.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNEntry

children.name: id
children.description:
The id specifies the order in which the entries in the
cert-to-name list are searched.  Entries with lower
numbers are searched first.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNID

children.name: fingerprint
children.description:
Specifies a value with which the fingerprint of the
full certificate presented by the peer is compared.  If
the fingerprint of the full certificate presented by the
peer does not match the fingerprint configured, then the
entry is skipped, and the search for a match continues.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model
  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNFingerprint

children.name: map-type

Mappings that use the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData column
need to augment the cert-to-name list with

to the snmpTlstmCertToTSNData value.  Such objects
should use the 'when' statement to make them
conditional based on the map-type.
children.reference:
RFC 6353: Transport Layer Security (TLS) Transport Model

  (SNMP).
  SNMP-TLS-TM-MIB.snmpTlstmCertToTSNMapType

  for the Simple Network Management Protocol
  (SNMP).

modules.name: ietf-subscribed-notifications
modules.description:
This module defines a YANG data model for subscribing to event
records and receiving matching content in notification messages.

The key words 'MUST', 'MUST NOT', 'REQUIRED', 'SHALL', 'SHALL
NOT', 'SHOULD', 'SHOULD NOT', 'RECOMMENDED', 'NOT RECOMMENDED',
'MAY', and 'OPTIONAL' in this document are to be interpreted as
described in BCP 14 (RFC 2119) (RFC 8174) when, and only when,
they appear in all capitals, as shown here.

children.name: establish-subscription
children.description:
This RPC allows a subscriber to create (and possibly
negotiate) a subscription on its own behalf.  If successful,
the subscription remains in effect for the duration of the
subscriber's association with the publisher or until the
subscription is terminated.  If an error occurs or the
publisher cannot meet the terms of a subscription, an RPC
error is returned, and the subscription is not created.
In that case, the RPC reply's 'error-info' MAY include
suggested parameter settings that would have a higher
likelihood of succeeding in a subsequent
'establish-subscription' request.

children.name: target
children.description:
Identifies the source of information against which a
subscription is being applied as well as specifics on the
subset of information desired from that source.

children.name: stream-filter
children.description:
An event stream filter can be applied to a subscription.
That filter will either come referenced from a global
list or be provided in the subscription itself.

children.name: by-reference
children.description: Apply a filter that has been configured separately.

children.name: stream-filter-name
children.description:
References an existing event stream filter that is
to be applied to an event stream for the
subscription.

children.name: within-subscription
children.description:
A local definition allows a filter to have the same
lifecycle as the subscription.

children.name: filter-spec
children.description: The content filter specification for this request.

children.name: stream-subtree-filter
children.description:
Event stream evaluation criteria encoded in the syntax of
a subtree filter as defined in RFC 6241, Section 6.

The subtree filter is applied to the representation of

children.description:

present, the notification messages will continue until the

children.description:

children.description:

that parent have push updates ready to egress the publisher.

the current subscription if the parent has something ready

children.description:

children.name: update-trigger
children.description:
Defines necessary conditions for sending an event record to
the subscriber.

children.name: periodic
children.description:
The publisher is requested to periodically notify the
receiver regarding the current values of the datastore
as defined by the selection filter.

children.name: period
children.description:
Duration of time that should occur between periodic
push updates, in units of 0.01 seconds.

children.name: anchor-time
children.description:
Designates a timestamp before or after which a series
of periodic push updates are determined.  The next
update will take place at a point in time that is a
multiple of a period from the 'anchor-time'.
For example, for an 'anchor-time' that is set for the
top of a particular minute and a period interval of a
minute, updates will be sent at the top of every
minute that this subscription is active.

children.name: on-change
children.description:
The publisher is requested to notify the receiver
regarding changes in values in the datastore subset as
defined by a selection filter.

children.name: dampening-period
children.description:
Specifies the minimum interval between the assembly of
successive update records for a single receiver of a
subscription.  Whenever subscribed objects change and
a dampening-period interval (which may be zero) has
elapsed since the previous update record creation for
a receiver, any subscribed objects and properties
that have changed since the previous update record
will have their current values marshalled and placed
in a new update record.

children.name: sync-on-start
children.description:

on-change subscription from sending 'push-update'
notifications and (2) pushing a full selection per the
terms of the selection filter MUST NOT be done for
this subscription.  Only updates about changes
(i.e., only 'push-change-update' notifications)
are sent.  When set to 'true' (the default behavior),
in order to facilitate a receiver's synchronization,
a full update is sent, via a 'push-update' notification,
when the subscription starts.  After that,
'push-change-update' notifications are exclusively sent,
unless the publisher chooses to resync the subscription
via a new 'push-update' notification.

children.description:

example, if a 'replace' operation is excluded, only the
creation and deletion of objects are reported.

children.name: id
children.description: Identifier used for this subscription.

records after this time will be replayed to a receiver.

been revised to be later than the time requested by the
subscriber.

subscription is not modified and the original subscription
parameters remain in effect.  In that case, the RPC error MAY
include 'error-info' suggested parameter hints that would have
a high likelihood of succeeding in a subsequent
'modify-subscription' request.  A successful
'modify-subscription' will return a suspended subscription to
the 'active' state.

are sent.  When set to 'true' (the default behavior),

a full update is sent, via a 'push-update' notification,
when the subscription starts.  After that,

unless the publisher chooses to resync the subscription

children.name: excluded-change
children.description:
Used to restrict which changes trigger an update.  For
example, if a 'replace' operation is excluded, only the
creation and deletion of objects are reported.

children.name: subscription-resumed
children.description:
This notification indicates that a subscription that had
previously been suspended has resumed.  Notifications will
once again be sent.  In addition, a 'subscription-resumed'
indicates that no modification of parameters has occurred
since the last time event records have been sent.

children.name: id
children.description: This references the affected subscription.

children.name: subscription-started
children.description:
This notification indicates that a subscription has started
and notifications will now be sent.

children.name: id
children.description: This references the affected subscription.

children.name: target
children.description:
Identifies the source of information against which a
subscription is being applied as well as specifics on the
subset of information desired from that source.

children.name: stream-filter
children.description:
An event stream filter can be applied to a subscription.
That filter will either come referenced from a global
list or be provided in the subscription itself.

children.name: by-reference
children.description: Apply a filter that has been configured separately.

children.name: stream-filter-name
children.description:
References an existing event stream filter that is
to be applied to an event stream for the
subscription.

children.name: within-subscription
children.description:
Filter applied to the subscription.  If the
'stream-filter-name' is populated, the filter in the
subscription came from the 'filters' container.
Otherwise, it is populated in-line as part of the
subscription.

children.name: filter-spec
children.description: The content filter specification for this request.

children.name: stream-subtree-filter
children.description:
Event stream evaluation criteria encoded in the syntax of
a subtree filter as defined in RFC 6241, Section 6.

The subtree filter is applied to the representation of
individual, delineated event records as contained in the
event stream.

If the subtree filter returns a non-empty node set, the
filter matches the event record, and the event record is
included in the notification message sent to the
receivers.

an XPath 1.0 expression.

The XPath expression is evaluated on the representation of
individual, delineated event records as contained in
the event stream.

The result of the XPath expression is converted to a
boolean value using the standard XPath 1.0 rules.  If the
boolean value is 'true', the filter matches the event
record, and the event record is included in the
notification message sent to the receivers.

context:

      prefix and namespace pairs for all YANG modules
      implemented by the server, where the prefix is the
      YANG module name and the namespace is as defined by
      the 'namespace' statement in the YANG module.

      declarations in scope on the 'stream-xpath-filter'
      leaf element are added to the set of namespace
      declarations.  If a prefix found in the XML is
      already present in the set of namespace
      declarations, the namespace in the XML is used.

      function library and the XPath functions defined in
      Section 10 in RFC 7950.

children.name: stream
children.description:

this subscription.

children.name: replay-start-time

this configured subscription, it can compare this time
to the last event record previously received.  If the
two are not the same (perhaps due to a reboot), then a
dynamic replay can be initiated to acquire any missing
event records.

children.name: datastore
children.description: Datastore from which to retrieve data.

children.name: selection-filter
children.description:
The source of the selection filter applied to the
subscription.  This will either (1) come referenced from a
global list or (2) be provided in the subscription itself.

children.name: by-reference
children.description:
Incorporates a filter that has been configured
separately.

children.name: selection-filter-ref
children.description:
References an existing selection filter that is to be
applied to the subscription.

children.description:

node set are selected by the filter.  Otherwise, if the
expression does not return a node set, the filter
doesn't select any nodes.

context:

o  The set of namespace declarations is the set of prefix

   leaf element are added to the set of namespace
   declarations.  If a prefix found in the XML is

o  The function library is comprised of the core

children.name: stop-time
children.description:
Identifies a time after which notification messages for a
subscription should not be sent.  If 'stop-time' is not
present, the notification messages will continue until the
subscription is terminated.  If 'replay-start-time' exists,
'stop-time' must be for a subsequent time.  If
'replay-start-time' doesn't exist, 'stop-time', when
established, must be for a future time.

children.name: dscp
children.description:
The desired network transport priority level.  This is the
priority set on notification messages encapsulating the
results of the subscription.  This transport priority is
shared for all receivers of a given subscription.

children.name: weighting
children.description:
Relative weighting for a subscription.  Larger weights get
more resources.  Allows an underlying transport layer to
perform informed load-balance allocations between various
subscriptions.

children.name: dependency
children.description:

The parent subscription has absolute precedence should
that parent have push updates ready to egress the publisher.
In other words, there should be no streaming of objects from
the current subscription if the parent has something ready
to push.

If a dependency is asserted via configuration or via an RPC
but the referenced 'subscription-id' does not exist, the
dependency is silently discarded.  If a referenced
subscription is deleted, this dependency is removed.

children.name: transport

transport used to deliver messages destined for all

children.name: encoding
children.description:

children.name: purpose
children.description:
Open text allowing a configuring entity to embed the
originator or other specifics of this subscription.

children.name: update-trigger
children.description:

the subscriber.

children.name: periodic
children.description:

children.name: period
children.description:

children.name: anchor-time

this subscription.  Only updates about changes

example, if a 'replace' operation is excluded, only the
creation and deletion of objects are reported.

children.name: id
children.description: This references the affected subscription.

children.name: reason

children.name: subscription-terminated

terminated.

children.name: id
children.description: This references the affected subscription.

children.name: reason

children.name: streams

children.name: stream

the publisher.

children.name: name
children.description:
A handle for a system-provided event stream made up of a
sequential set of event records, each of which is
characterized by its own domain and semantics.

children.name: description
children.description:
A description of the event stream, including such
information as the type of event records that are
available in this event stream.

children.name: replay-support
children.description:
Indicates that event record replay is available on this
event stream.

children.name: replay-log-creation-time
children.description:

the replay function on this event stream.  This time
might be earlier than the earliest available information
contained in the log.  This object is updated if the log
resets for some reason.

children.name: replay-log-aged-time
children.description:

has been aged out of the log.  This timestamp identifies

doesn't extend back to the 'replay-log-creation-time'.

once defined.

children.description:

subscriptions.

children.name: name
children.description: A name to differentiate between filters.

children.name: filter-spec
children.description: The content filter specification for this request.

the configured subscription should start at the
earliest time in the event log or at the publisher
boot time, whichever is later.

children.description: Datastore from which to retrieve data.

children.description:

children.description:
Identifies a time after which notification messages for a
subscription should not be sent.  If 'stop-time' is not
present, the notification messages will continue until the
subscription is terminated.  If 'replay-start-time' exists,
'stop-time' must be for a subsequent time.  If
'replay-start-time' doesn't exist, 'stop-time', when

children.name: dscp
children.description:
The desired network transport priority level.  This is the
priority set on notification messages encapsulating the
results of the subscription.  This transport priority is

children.name: weighting
children.description:
Relative weighting for a subscription.  Larger weights get
more resources.  Allows an underlying transport layer to
perform informed load-balance allocations between various
subscriptions.

children.name: dependency

that parent have push updates ready to egress the publisher.

but the referenced 'subscription-id' does not exist, the

children.name: transport
children.description:

transport used to deliver messages destined for all
receivers of that subscription.  This object is
mandatory for subscriptions in the configuration
datastore.  This object (1) is not mandatory for dynamic
subscriptions in the operational state datastore and
(2) should not be present for other types of dynamic
subscriptions.

children.name: encoding
children.description:
The type of encoding for notification messages.  For a

subscription, if not explicitly configured, the encoding

children.name: purpose

children.name: interface-originated
children.description:

children.name: configured-subscription-state

channel or RPC.  The value indicates the state of the
subscription as established by the publisher.

children.name: receivers
children.description: Set of receivers in a subscription.

children.name: receiver
children.description:

messages of a subscription.  For configured
subscriptions, transport-specific network parameters
(or a leafref to those parameters) may be augmented to a
specific receiver in this list.

children.name: name
children.description: Identifies a unique receiver for a subscription.

children.name: sent-event-records
children.description:
The number of event records sent to the receiver.  The
count is initialized when a dynamic subscription is
established or when a configured receiver
transitions to the 'valid' state.

children.name: excluded-event-records
children.description:
The number of event records explicitly removed via
either an event stream filter or an access control
filter so that they are not passed to a receiver.
This count is set to zero each time
'sent-event-records' is initialized.

children.name: state
children.description:
Specifies the state of a subscription from the
perspective of a particular receiver.  With this
information, it is possible to determine whether a
publisher is currently generating notification
messages intended for that receiver.

children.name: reset
children.description:
Allows the reset of this configured subscription's
receiver to the 'connecting' state.  This enables the
connection process to be reinitiated.

children.name: time
children.description:
Time at which a publisher returned the receiver to
the 'connecting' state.

children.name: update-trigger
children.description:
Defines necessary conditions for sending an event record to
the subscriber.

children.name: periodic
children.description:
The publisher is requested to periodically notify the
receiver regarding the current values of the datastore
as defined by the selection filter.

children.name: period
children.description:
Duration of time that should occur between periodic
push updates, in units of 0.01 seconds.

children.name: anchor-time
children.description:
Designates a timestamp before or after which a series
of periodic push updates are determined.  The next
update will take place at a point in time that is a
multiple of a period from the 'anchor-time'.
For example, for an 'anchor-time' that is set for the
top of a particular minute and a period interval of a
minute, updates will be sent at the top of every
minute that this subscription is active.

children.name: on-change
children.description:
The publisher is requested to notify the receiver
regarding changes in values in the datastore subset as
defined by a selection filter.

children.name: dampening-period
children.description:
Specifies the minimum interval between the assembly of
successive update records for a single receiver of a
subscription.  Whenever subscribed objects change and
a dampening-period interval (which may be zero) has
elapsed since the previous update record creation for
a receiver, any subscribed objects and properties
that have changed since the previous update record
will have their current values marshalled and placed
in a new update record.

children.name: sync-on-start
children.description:
When this object is set to 'false', (1) it restricts an
on-change subscription from sending 'push-update'
notifications and (2) pushing a full selection per the
terms of the selection filter MUST NOT be done for
this subscription.  Only updates about changes
(i.e., only 'push-change-update' notifications)
are sent.  When set to 'true' (the default behavior),
in order to facilitate a receiver's synchronization,
a full update is sent, via a 'push-update' notification,
when the subscription starts.  After that,
'push-change-update' notifications are exclusively sent,
unless the publisher chooses to resync the subscription
via a new 'push-update' notification.

children.name: excluded-change
children.description:
Used to restrict which changes trigger an update.  For
example, if a 'replace' operation is excluded, only the
creation and deletion of objects are reported.

modules.name: ietf-system
modules.description:
This module contains a collection of YANG definitions for the
configuration and identification of some common system
properties within a device containing a NETCONF server.  This
includes data node definitions for system identification,
time-of-day management, user management, DNS resolver
configuration, and some protocol operations for system
management.

authors of the code.  All rights reserved.

Redistribution and use in source and binary forms, with or
without modification, is permitted pursuant to, and subject
to the license terms contained in, the Simplified BSD License
set forth in Section 4.c of the IETF Trust's Legal Provisions
Relating to IETF Documents
(http://trustee.ietf.org/license-info).

This version of this YANG module is part of RFC 7317; see
the RFC itself for full legal notices.

modules.contact:

children.name: system
children.description: System group configuration.

children.name: contact
children.description:
The administrator contact information for the system.

A server implementation MAY map this leaf to the sysContact
MIB object.  Such an implementation needs to use some
mechanism to handle the differences in size and characters
allowed between this leaf and sysContact.  The definition of
such a mechanism is outside the scope of this document.
children.reference:
RFC 3418: Management Information Base (MIB) for the
          Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)
          SNMPv2-MIB.sysContact

children.name: hostname
children.description:
The name of the host.  This name can be a single domain
label or the fully qualified domain name of the host.

children.name: location
children.description:
The system location.

A server implementation MAY map this leaf to the sysLocation
MIB object.  Such an implementation needs to use some
mechanism to handle the differences in size and characters
allowed between this leaf and sysLocation.  The definition
of such a mechanism is outside the scope of this document.
children.reference:
RFC 3418: Management Information Base (MIB) for the
          Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)
          SNMPv2-MIB.sysLocation

children.name: clock
children.description: Configuration of the system date and time properties.

children.name: timezone
children.description: The system time zone information.

children.name: timezone-name
children.description:
The TZ database name to use for the system, such
as 'Europe/Stockholm'.

children.name: timezone-utc-offset
children.description:
The number of minutes to add to UTC time to
identify the time zone for this system.  For example,
'UTC - 8:00 hours' would be represented as '-480'.
Note that automatic daylight saving time adjustment
is not provided if this object is used.

children.name: ntp
children.description: Configuration of the NTP client.

children.name: enabled
children.description:
Indicates that the system should attempt to
synchronize the system clock with an NTP server
from the 'ntp/server' list.

children.name: server
children.description:
List of NTP servers to use for system clock
synchronization.  If '/system/ntp/enabled'
is 'true', then the system will attempt to
contact and utilize the specified NTP servers.

children.name: name
children.description: An arbitrary name for the NTP server.

children.name: transport
children.description:
The transport-protocol-specific parameters for this
server.

children.name: udp
children.description:
Contains UDP-specific configuration parameters
for NTP.

children.name: address
children.description: The address of the NTP server.

children.name: port
children.description: The port number of the NTP server.

children.name: association-type
children.description: The desired association type for this NTP server.

children.name: iburst
children.description:
Indicates whether this server should enable burst
synchronization or not.

children.name: prefer
children.description:
Indicates whether this server should be preferred
or not.

children.name: dns-resolver
children.description: Configuration of the DNS resolver.

children.name: search
children.description:
An ordered list of domains to search when resolving
a host name.

children.name: server
children.description:
List of the DNS servers that the resolver should query.

When the resolver is invoked by a calling application, it
sends the query to the first name server in this list.  If
no response has been received within 'timeout' seconds,
the resolver continues with the next server in the list.
If no response is received from any server, the resolver
continues with the first server again.  When the resolver
has traversed the list 'attempts' times without receiving
any response, it gives up and returns an error to the
calling application.

Implementations MAY limit the number of entries in this
list.

children.name: name
children.description: An arbitrary name for the DNS server.

children.name: transport
children.description:
The transport-protocol-specific parameters for this
server.

children.name: udp-and-tcp
children.description:
Contains UDP- and TCP-specific configuration
parameters for DNS.
children.reference:
RFC 1035: Domain Names - Implementation and
          Specification
RFC 5966: DNS Transport over TCP - Implementation
          Requirements

children.name: address
children.description: The address of the DNS server.

children.name: port
children.description: The UDP and TCP port number of the DNS server.

children.name: options
children.description:
Resolver options.  The set of available options has been
limited to those that are generally available across
different resolver implementations and generally useful.

children.name: timeout
children.description:
The amount of time the resolver will wait for a
response from each remote name server before
retrying the query via a different name server.

children.name: attempts
children.description:
The number of times the resolver will send a query to
all of its name servers before giving up and returning
an error to the calling application.

children.name: radius
children.description: Configuration of the RADIUS client.

children.name: server
children.description:
List of RADIUS servers used by the device.

When the RADIUS client is invoked by a calling
application, it sends the query to the first server in
this list.  If no response has been received within
'timeout' seconds, the client continues with the next
server in the list.  If no response is received from any
server, the client continues with the first server again.
When the client has traversed the list 'attempts' times
without receiving any response, it gives up and returns an
error to the calling application.

children.name: name
children.description: An arbitrary name for the RADIUS server.

children.name: transport
children.description:
The transport-protocol-specific parameters for this
server.

children.name: udp
children.description:
Contains UDP-specific configuration parameters
for RADIUS.

children.name: address
children.description: The address of the RADIUS server.

children.name: authentication-port
children.description: The port number of the RADIUS server.

children.name: shared-secret
children.description:
The shared secret, which is known to both the
RADIUS client and server.
children.reference:
RFC 2865: Remote Authentication Dial In User
          Service (RADIUS)

children.name: authentication-type
children.description:
The authentication type requested from the RADIUS
server.

children.name: options
children.description: RADIUS client options.

children.name: timeout
children.description:
The number of seconds the device will wait for a
response from each RADIUS server before trying with a
different server.

children.name: attempts
children.description:
The number of times the device will send a query to
all of its RADIUS servers before giving up.

children.name: authentication
children.description: The authentication configuration subtree.

children.name: user-authentication-order
children.description:
When the device authenticates a user with a password,
it tries the authentication methods in this leaf-list in
order.  If authentication with one method fails, the next
method is used.  If no method succeeds, the user is
denied access.

An empty user-authentication-order leaf-list still allows
authentication of users using mechanisms that do not
involve a password.

If the 'radius-authentication' feature is advertised by
the NETCONF server, the 'radius' identity can be added to
this list.

If the 'local-users' feature is advertised by the
NETCONF server, the 'local-users' identity can be
added to this list.

children.name: user
children.description: The list of local users configured on this device.

children.name: name
children.description: The user name string identifying this entry.

children.name: password
children.description: The password for this entry.

children.name: authorized-key
children.description:
A list of public SSH keys for this user.  These keys
are allowed for SSH authentication, as described in
RFC 4253.
children.reference:
RFC 4253: The Secure Shell (SSH) Transport Layer
          Protocol

children.name: name
children.description: An arbitrary name for the SSH key.

children.name: algorithm
children.description:
The public key algorithm name for this SSH key.

Valid values are the values in the IANA 'Secure Shell
(SSH) Protocol Parameters' registry, Public Key
Algorithm Names.
children.reference:
IANA 'Secure Shell (SSH) Protocol Parameters'
registry, Public Key Algorithm Names

children.name: key-data
children.description:
The binary public key data for this SSH key, as
specified by RFC 4253, Section 6.6, i.e.:

  string    certificate or public key format
            identifier
  byte[n]   key/certificate data.
children.reference:
RFC 4253: The Secure Shell (SSH) Transport Layer
          Protocol

children.name: system-state
children.description: System group operational state.

children.name: platform
children.description:
Contains vendor-specific information for
identifying the system platform and operating system.
children.reference: IEEE Std 1003.1-2008 - sys/utsname.h

children.name: os-name
children.description:
The name of the operating system in use -
for example, 'Linux'.
children.reference: IEEE Std 1003.1-2008 - utsname.sysname

children.name: os-release
children.description:
The current release level of the operating
system in use.  This string MAY indicate
the OS source code revision.
children.reference: IEEE Std 1003.1-2008 - utsname.release

children.name: os-version
children.description:
The current version level of the operating
system in use.  This string MAY indicate
the specific OS build date and target variant
information.
children.reference: IEEE Std 1003.1-2008 - utsname.version

children.name: machine
children.description:
A vendor-specific identifier string representing
the hardware in use.
children.reference: IEEE Std 1003.1-2008 - utsname.machine

children.name: clock
children.description: Monitoring of the system date and time properties.

children.name: current-datetime
children.description: The current system date and time.

children.name: boot-datetime
children.description: The system date and time when the system last restarted.

children.name: set-current-datetime
children.description:
Set the /system-state/clock/current-datetime leaf
to the specified value.

If the system is using NTP (i.e., /system/ntp/enabled
is set to 'true'), then this operation will fail with
error-tag 'operation-failed' and error-app-tag value of
'ntp-active'.

children.name: current-datetime
children.description: The current system date and time.

children.name: system-restart
children.description:
Request that the entire system be restarted immediately.
A server SHOULD send an rpc reply to the client before
restarting the system.

children.name: system-shutdown
children.description:
Request that the entire system be shut down immediately.
A server SHOULD send an rpc reply to the client before
shutting down the system.

modules.name: ietf-voucher
modules.description:
This module defines the format for a voucher, which is produced by
a pledge's manufacturer or delegate (MASA) to securely assign a
pledge to an 'owner', so that the pledge may establish a secure
connection to the owner's network infrastructure.

The key words 'MUST', 'MUST NOT', 'REQUIRED', 'SHALL', 'SHALL

'MAY', and 'OPTIONAL' in this document are to be interpreted as
described in BCP 14 (RFC 2119) (RFC 8174) when, and only when, they
appear in all capitals, as shown here.

children.name: vrrp
children.description: VRRP data at the global level.

children.name: virtual-routers
children.description: Number of configured virtual routers.

children.name: interfaces
children.description: Number of interfaces with VRRP configured.

children.name: statistics
children.description: VRRP global statistics.

children.name: discontinuity-datetime
children.description:
The time on the most recent occasion at which any
one or more of checksum-errors, version-errors,
vrid-errors, or ip-ttl-errors suffered a
discontinuity.

If no such discontinuities have occurred since the last
re-initialization of the local management subsystem,
then this node contains the time that the local management
subsystem re-initialized itself.

children.name: checksum-errors
children.description:
The total number of VRRP packets received with an invalid
VRRP checksum value.
children.reference:
RFC 5798: Virtual Router Redundancy Protocol (VRRP)
          Version 3 for IPv4 and IPv6.  Section 5.2.8

children.name: version-errors
children.description:
The total number of VRRP packets received with an unknown
or unsupported version number.
children.reference:
RFC 5798: Virtual Router Redundancy Protocol (VRRP)
          Version 3 for IPv4 and IPv6.  Section 5.2.1

children.name: vrid-errors
children.description:
The total number of VRRP packets received with a VRID that
is not valid for any virtual router on this router.
children.reference:
RFC 5798: Virtual Router Redundancy Protocol (VRRP)
          Version 3 for IPv4 and IPv6.  Section 5.2.3

children.name: ip-ttl-errors
children.description:
The total number of VRRP packets received by the
virtual router with IP TTL (IPv4) or Hop Limit (IPv6)
not equal to 255.
children.reference:
RFC 5798: Virtual Router Redundancy Protocol (VRRP)
          Version 3 for IPv4 and IPv6.
          Sections 5.1.1.3 and 5.1.2.3

children.name: vrrp-new-master-event
children.description: Notification event for the election of a new VRRP master.

children.name: master-ip-address
children.description: IPv4 or IPv6 address of the new master.

children.name: new-master-reason
children.description:
Indicates why the virtual router has transitioned to
master state.

children.name: vrrp-protocol-error-event
children.description: Notification event for a VRRP protocol error.

children.name: protocol-error-reason
children.description: Indicates the reason for the protocol error.

children.name: vrrp-virtual-router-error-event
children.description:
Notification event for an error that happened on a
virtual router.

children.name: interface
children.description: Indicates the interface on which the event has occurred.

children.name: ip-version
children.description:
The error may have happened on either an IPv4 virtual
router or an IPv6 virtual router.  The information
related to a specific IP version is provided by one of
the following cases.

children.name: ipv4
children.description: IPv4.

children.name: ipv4
children.description: Error information for IPv4.

children.name: vrid
children.description:
Indicates the virtual router on which the event has
occurred.

children.name: ipv6
children.description: IPv6.

children.name: ipv6
children.description: Error information for IPv6.

children.name: vrid
children.description:
Indicates the virtual router on which the event has
occurred.

children.name: virtual-router-error-reason
children.description: Indicates the reason for the virtual router error.

children.name: yang-library
children.description: Container holding the entire YANG library of this server.

children.name: module-set
children.description:
A set of modules that may be used by one or more schemas.

A module set does not have to be referentially complete,
i.e., it may define modules that contain import statements
for other modules not included in the module set.

children.name: name
children.description: An arbitrary name of the module set.

children.name: module
children.description:
An entry in this list represents a module implemented by the
server, as per Section 5.6.5 of RFC 7950, with a particular
set of supported features and deviations.
children.reference: RFC 7950: The YANG 1.1 Data Modeling Language

children.name: name
children.description: The YANG module or submodule name.

children.name: revision
children.description:
The YANG module or submodule revision date.  If no revision
statement is present in the YANG module or submodule, this
leaf is not instantiated.

children.name: namespace
children.description: The XML namespace identifier for this module.

children.name: location
children.description:
Contains a URL that represents the YANG schema
resource for this module or submodule.

This leaf will only be present if there is a URL
available for retrieval of the schema for this entry.

children.name: submodule
children.description:
Each entry represents one submodule within the
parent module.

children.name: name
children.description: The YANG module or submodule name.

children.name: revision
children.description:
The YANG module or submodule revision date.  If no revision
statement is present in the YANG module or submodule, this
leaf is not instantiated.

children.name: location
children.description:
Contains a URL that represents the YANG schema
resource for this module or submodule.

This leaf will only be present if there is a URL
available for retrieval of the schema for this entry.

children.name: feature
children.description:
List of all YANG feature names from this module that are
supported by the server, regardless whether they are defined
in the module or any included submodule.

children.name: deviation
children.description:
List of all YANG deviation modules used by this server to
modify the conformance of the module associated with this
entry.  Note that the same module can be used for deviations
for multiple modules, so the same entry MAY appear within
multiple 'module' entries.

This reference MUST NOT (directly or indirectly)
refer to the module being deviated.

Robust clients may want to make sure that they handle a
situation where a module deviates itself (directly or
indirectly) gracefully.

children.name: import-only-module
children.description:
An entry in this list indicates that the server imports
reusable definitions from the specified revision of the
module but does not implement any protocol-accessible
objects from this revision.

Multiple entries for the same module name MAY exist.  This
can occur if multiple modules import the same module but
specify different revision dates in the import statements.

children.name: name
children.description: The YANG module name.

children.name: revision
children.description:
The YANG module revision date.
A zero-length string is used if no revision statement
is present in the YANG module.

children.name: namespace
children.description: The XML namespace identifier for this module.

children.name: location
children.description:
Contains a URL that represents the YANG schema
resource for this module or submodule.

This leaf will only be present if there is a URL
available for retrieval of the schema for this entry.

children.name: submodule
children.description:
Each entry represents one submodule within the
parent module.

children.name: name
children.description: The YANG module or submodule name.

children.name: revision
children.description:
The YANG module or submodule revision date.  If no revision
statement is present in the YANG module or submodule, this
leaf is not instantiated.

children.name: location
children.description:
Contains a URL that represents the YANG schema
resource for this module or submodule.

This leaf will only be present if there is a URL
available for retrieval of the schema for this entry.

children.name: schema
children.description:
A datastore schema that may be used by one or more
datastores.

The schema must be valid and referentially complete, i.e.,
it must contain modules to satisfy all used import
statements for all modules specified in the schema.

children.name: name
children.description: An arbitrary name of the schema.

children.name: module-set
children.description:
A set of module-sets that are included in this schema.
If a non-import-only module appears in multiple module
sets, then the module revision and the associated features
and deviations must be identical.

children.name: datastore
children.description:
A datastore supported by this server.

Each datastore indicates which schema it supports.

The server MUST instantiate one entry in this list per
specific datastore it supports.

Each datastore entry with the same datastore schema SHOULD
reference the same schema.

children.name: name
children.description: The identity of the datastore.

children.name: schema
children.description:
A reference to the schema supported by this datastore.
All non-import-only modules of the schema are implemented
with their associated features and deviations.

children.name: content-id
children.description:
A server-generated identifier of the contents of the
'/yang-library' tree.  The server MUST change the value of
this leaf if the information represented by the
'/yang-library' tree, except '/yang-library/content-id', has
changed.

children.name: yang-library-update
children.description:
Generated when any YANG library information on the
server has changed.

children.name: content-id
children.description:
Contains the YANG library content identifier for the updated
YANG library at the time the notification is generated.

children.name: modules-state
children.description: Contains YANG module monitoring information.

children.name: module-set-id
children.description:
Contains a server-specific identifier representing
the current set of modules and submodules.  The
server MUST change the value of this leaf if the
information represented by the 'module' list instances
has changed.

children.name: module
children.description:
Each entry represents one revision of one module
currently supported by the server.

children.name: name
children.description: The YANG module or submodule name.

children.name: revision
children.description:
The YANG module or submodule revision date.
A zero-length string is used if no revision statement
is present in the YANG module or submodule.

children.name: schema
children.description:
Contains a URL that represents the YANG schema
resource for this module or submodule.

This leaf will only be present if there is a URL
available for retrieval of the schema for this entry.

children.name: namespace
children.description: The XML namespace identifier for this module.

children.name: feature
children.description:
List of YANG feature names from this module that are
supported by the server, regardless of whether they are
defined in the module or any included submodule.

children.name: deviation
children.description:
List of YANG deviation module names and revisions
used by this server to modify the conformance of
the module associated with this entry.  Note that
the same module can be used for deviations for
multiple modules, so the same entry MAY appear
within multiple 'module' entries.

The deviation module MUST be present in the 'module'
list, with the same name and revision values.
The 'conformance-type' value will be 'implement' for
the deviation module.

children.name: name
children.description: The YANG module or submodule name.

children.name: revision
children.description:
The YANG module or submodule revision date.
A zero-length string is used if no revision statement
is present in the YANG module or submodule.

children.name: conformance-type
children.description:
Indicates the type of conformance the server is claiming
for the YANG module identified by this entry.

children.name: submodule
children.description:
Each entry represents one submodule within the
parent module.

children.name: name
children.description: The YANG module or submodule name.

children.name: revision
children.description:
The YANG module or submodule revision date.
A zero-length string is used if no revision statement
is present in the YANG module or submodule.

children.name: schema
children.description:
Contains a URL that represents the YANG schema
resource for this module or submodule.

This leaf will only be present if there is a URL
available for retrieval of the schema for this entry.

children.name: yang-library-change
children.description:
Generated when the set of modules and submodules supported
by the server has changed.

children.name: module-set-id
children.description:
Contains the module-set-id value representing the
set of modules and submodules supported at the server
at the time the notification is generated.

children.name: resync-subscription
children.description:
This RPC allows a subscriber of an active on-change
subscription to request a full push of objects.

A successful invocation results in a 'push-update' of all
datastore nodes that the subscriber is permitted to access.
This RPC can only be invoked on the same session on which the
subscription is currently active.  In the case of an error, a
'resync-subscription-error' is sent as part of an error
response.

children.name: id
children.description: Identifier of the subscription that is to be resynced.

children.name: push-update
children.description:
This notification contains a push update that in turn contains
data subscribed to via a subscription.  In the case of a
periodic subscription, this notification is sent for periodic
updates.  It can also be used for synchronization updates of
an on-change subscription.  This notification shall only be
sent to receivers of a subscription.  It does not constitute
a general-purpose notification that would be subscribable as
part of the NETCONF event stream by any receiver.

children.name: id
children.description:
This references the subscription that drove the
notification to be sent.

children.name: datastore-contents
children.description:
This contains the updated data.  It constitutes a snapshot
at the time of update of the set of data that has been
subscribed to.  The snapshot corresponds to the same
snapshot that would be returned in a corresponding 'get'
operation with the same selection filter parameters
applied.

children.name: incomplete-update
children.description:
This is a flag that indicates that not all datastore
nodes subscribed to are included with this update.  In
other words, the publisher has failed to fulfill its full
subscription obligations and, despite its best efforts, is
providing an incomplete set of objects.

children.name: push-change-update
children.description:
This notification contains an on-change push update.  This
notification shall only be sent to the receivers of a
subscription.  It does not constitute a general-purpose
notification that would be subscribable as part of the
NETCONF event stream by any receiver.

children.name: id
children.description:
This references the subscription that drove the
notification to be sent.

children.name: datastore-changes
children.description:
This contains the set of datastore changes of the target
datastore, starting at the time of the previous update, per
the terms of the subscription.

children.name: yang-patch
children.description:
Represents a conceptual sequence of datastore edits,
called a patch.  Each patch is given a client-assigned
patch identifier.  Each edit MUST be applied
in ascending order, and all edits MUST be applied.
If any errors occur, then the target datastore MUST NOT
be changed by the YANG Patch operation.

It is possible for a datastore constraint violation to occur
due to any node in the datastore, including nodes not
included in the 'edit' list.  Any validation errors MUST
be reported in the reply message.
children.reference: RFC 7950, Section 8.3.

children.name: patch-id
children.description:
An arbitrary string provided by the client to identify
the entire patch.  Error messages returned by the server
that pertain to this patch will be identified by this
'patch-id' value.  A client SHOULD attempt to generate
unique 'patch-id' values to distinguish between
transactions from multiple clients in any audit logs
maintained by the server.

children.name: comment
children.description:
An arbitrary string provided by the client to describe
the entire patch.  This value SHOULD be present in any
audit logging records generated by the server for the
patch.

children.name: edit
children.description:
Represents one edit within the YANG Patch request message.
The 'edit' list is applied in the following manner:

  - The first edit is conceptually applied to a copy
    of the existing target datastore, e.g., the
    running configuration datastore.
  - Each ascending edit is conceptually applied to
    the result of the previous edit(s).
  - After all edits have been successfully processed,
    the result is validated according to YANG constraints.
  - If successful, the server will attempt to apply
    the result to the target datastore.

children.name: edit-id
children.description:
Arbitrary string index for the edit.
Error messages returned by the server that pertain
to a specific edit will be identified by this value.

children.name: operation
children.description:
The datastore operation requested for the associated
'edit' entry.

children.name: target
children.description:
Identifies the target data node for the edit
operation.  If the target has the value '/', then
the target data node is the target resource.
The target node MUST identify a data resource,
not the datastore resource.

children.name: point
children.description:
The absolute URL path for the data node that is being
used as the insertion point or move point for the
target of this 'edit' entry.

children.name: where
children.description:
Identifies where a data resource will be inserted
or moved.  YANG only allows these operations for
list and leaf-list data nodes that are
'ordered-by user'.

children.name: value
children.description: Value used for this edit operation. The anydata 'value' contains the target resource associated with the 'target' leaf. For example, suppose the target node is a YANG container named foo: container foo { leaf a { type string; } leaf b { type int32; } } The 'value' node contains one instance of foo: some value 42

children.name: incomplete-update
children.description:
The presence of this object indicates that not all changes
that have occurred since the last update are included with
this update.  In other words, the publisher has failed to
fulfill its full subscription obligations -- for example,
in cases where it was not able to keep up with a burst of
changes.

children.name: schema-mounts
children.description:
Contains information about the structure of the overall
mounted data model implemented in the server.

children.name: namespace
children.description:
This list provides a mapping of namespace prefixes that are
used in XPath expressions of 'parent-reference' leafs to the
corresponding namespace URI references.

children.name: prefix
children.description: Namespace prefix.

children.name: uri
children.description: Namespace URI reference.

children.name: mount-point
children.description:
Each entry of this list specifies a schema for a particular
mount point.

Each mount point MUST be defined using the 'mount-point'
extension in one of the modules listed in the server's
YANG library instance with conformance type 'implement'.

children.name: module
children.description: Name of a module containing the mount point.

children.name: label
children.description:
Label of the mount point defined using the 'mount-point'
extension.

children.name: config
children.description:
If this leaf is set to 'false', then all data nodes in the
mounted schema are read-only ('config false'), regardless
of their 'config' property.

children.name: schema-ref
children.description: Alternatives for specifying the schema.

children.name: inline
children.description:
This node indicates that the server has mounted at least
the module 'ietf-yang-library' at the mount point, and
its instantiation provides the information about the
mounted schema.

Different instances of the mount point may have
different schemas mounted.

children.name: shared-schema
children.description:
This node indicates that the server has mounted at least
the module 'ietf-yang-library' at the mount point, and
its instantiation provides the information about the
mounted schema.  When XPath expressions in the mounted
schema are evaluated, the 'parent-reference' leaf-list
is taken into account.

Different instances of the mount point MUST have the
same schema mounted.

children.name: parent-reference
children.description:
Entries of this leaf-list are XPath 1.0 expressions
that are evaluated in the following context:

- The context node is the node in the parent data tree
  where the mount-point is defined.

- The accessible tree is the parent data tree
  *without* any nodes defined in modules that are
  mounted inside the parent schema.

- The context position and context size are both equal
  to 1.

- The set of variable bindings is empty.

- The function library is the core function library
  defined in the W3C XPath 1.0 document
  (http://www.w3.org/TR/1999/REC-xpath-19991116) and
  the functions defined in Section 10 of RFC 7950.

- The set of namespace declarations is defined by the
  'namespace' list under 'schema-mounts'.

Each XPath expression MUST evaluate to a node-set
(possibly empty).  For the purposes of evaluating
XPath expressions whose context nodes are defined in
the mounted schema, the union of all these node-sets
together with ancestor nodes are added to the
accessible data tree.

Note that in the case 'ietf-yang-schema-mount' is
itself mounted, a 'parent-reference' in the mounted
module may refer to nodes that were brought into the
accessible tree through a 'parent-reference' in the
parent schema.
